summary: Gen works closely with health care leaders on creating a culture of excellence and the creation of structures and processes that support efforts to achieve ANCC Magnet Recognition® and Pathways to Excellence™ (PTE) designations. She has expertise in building best-in-class Cultures of Excellence services including all aspects of the Magnet and PTE journey phases and requirements. This includes conducting readiness assessments, supporting the development of shared governance and professional practice environments, Magnet and PTE document strategies including review and feedback, site visit preparation as well as a wide variety of professional development programs. She is an author and public speaker. She is very proud to share that 100% of the organizations who have partnered with CHCM for comprehensive support for their Magnet® journey have successfully received their initial designation or re-designation. Gen is a co-owner of Creative Health Care Management and is the Chair of the CHCM Board of Directors.\n\nCHCM provides expert guidance and leadership, staff, and team development along with structure and process development and strengthening consistent with ANCC Magnet® and Pathway to Excellence(R) Programs as well as other national recognition programs. Organizations who have worked with CHCM have seen an increase in patient satisfaction, improved clinical outcomes and an increase in staff satisfaction. \n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.5 ~ 2013.2', u'description': u'According to Geoffrey E. Mills (2011), action research is any systematic inquiry conducted by teacher researchers, principals, school counselors, or other stakeholders in the teaching/learning environment to gather information about how their particular school operates, how they teach, and how well their students learn. This information is gathered with the goals of gaining insights, developing reflective practice, effecting positive changes in the school environment, and improving student outcomes and the lives of those involved.\n\nMills, G. E. (2011). Action Research: A guide for the teacher researcher (4th Edition). Pearson Education, Inc.: Upper saddle River, NJ.', u'title': u'Action Research'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'As an educator and social scientist, I want to further expand research focus on cultural competence in pedagogical practices. Specifically, critical social theory is significant in particular to supporting the evaluation and inquiry approach in action research. In addition, the pedagogical process of assessing practices from a critical perspective will involve using my training and experience in quasi-empirical and qualitative methods in order to identify and name injustices or forms of oppression present that is essential in the participatory approach. Furthermore, continued aim is to actively participate as a practitioner, a social scientist as well as a critical social theorist through action research in finding and constructing new forms of knowledge, including those of social justice in educational leadership.', u'title': u'Cultural Competence in Pedagogical Practices'}]

summary: Barbara has 20 years of experience in mid-level management as a proven leader.  Her experience crosses over the areas of program development, regulation compliance and oversight, market research, project management, community outreach, and higher education.  \n\nShe has been involved in the creation of strategic plans for several organizations and engaged in extensive research including leadership, multi-generational communication and workforce development. Passionately active in community and workforce development, Barbara has served on various committees with chambers of commerce’s throughout Missouri and served as board member for nonprofits such as Association for Talent Development, Women in Need of the Ozarks and the Humane Society.\n\nWhile at Metropolitan Community College, Barbara was responsible for implementation, program development, assessment, and reporting for three Department of Labor TAACCCT Grants totaling over 7 million dollars.  \n\nPreviously she was the Director of Outreach Activities and the Coordinator of Leadership Studies, in addition to Adjunct Communications Professor at Drury University.At Drury she researched, developed and implemented the marketing campaigns for the evening, online and nine branch campus programs at Drury University. Barbara also conducted market research for expansion and new branch campus site development. Hired and trained faculty members for a wide variety of subject matter and delivery methods including online and blended formats in her role as Coordinator of Leadership Studies. She also oversaw two bachelors’ degree programs: Organizational Studies and Health Services. \n\nBarbara is a supporter of life-long learning through individualized professional development and certification. She holds a bachelor’s degree in psychology and a master’s degree in communication, a graduate certificate in social media, in addition to post-graduate coursework in leadership and marketing. \n\n\n\n

summary: ** Engineering and equity thought leader who drives mission-focused growth strategies for scaling organizations. \n** Self-initiated and innovative instructional, program, product, and technical designer who creates services, resources, and solutions that bolster revenue and opportunity. \n** Systems thinker who quickly identifies solutions and generates processes for the development, management and supervision of programs and operations, expanding capacity and efficiency. \n** Respected leader who applies organizational change models, process improvement strategies, metrics driven solutions, and equity transformation principles to cultivate an inclusive, aware and balanced workplace. \n\n** Biography ** \nMeagan is the Director of Professional Development for the National Alliance for Partnerships in Equity. In this role, Meagan leads a national team of equity professionals that build educators’ capacity to implement effective solutions for increasing student access, educational equity and workforce diversity. Meagan was a National Science Foundation Graduate Research Fellow, and holds a Ph.D. in Engineering Education from Purdue University, a M.S in Electrical Engineering from Texas Tech University, and a B.S. in Computer Science from Texas Woman’s University. Meagan is focused on engineering equity into education.

summary: I am a Senior Business Executive, National Certified Counselor, Researcher, and Founding Board Certified Executive / Leadership / Corporate / Career/ Wellness / Life Coach.\n\nI leverage my expertise in Cognitive Behavior Therapy (CBT) and Emotionally Focused Therapy (EFT) to build successful business relationships between executives, employees, and teams that enable strong connections with clients and win sales.\n\nWhen I transitioned away from being a private therapist to a business executive, I found that one of my strongest attributes is facilitating relationships for successful business negotiations.  I provide Executive Leadership Coaching by presenting and speaking to large groups, corporations, and business development teams on topics of Effective Communication, Conflict Resolution, and Team Building that strengthen business relations and earn customer loyalty.\n\nSince the beginning of my diverse career as a Police Officer and Peer Counselor for the NYPD, and owning my own business as a Couples Counselor, to my current roles as an Adjunct Professor at Pace University and Business Executive at  a document management company; I have coached others to overcome personal and professional challenges in order to unlock their potential and ignite the drive within.\n\n\n▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬▬\n\nIf you have any questions or would like to discuss my experiences in any of these areas, please feel free to connect with me on LinkedIn.\n

summary: Kaumal is a newly qualified dentist with undergraduate experience in restorative dentistry, oral surgery and oral health and development. Kaumal enjoys working in a diverse and fast-paced environment.\n\nKaumal visited Kathmandu, Nepal in July 2016, as part of a dental outreach programme. The fundraised money was used to provide atraumatic restorative treatment and pain relief for people of Kathmandu who had been affected by the recent earthquake.\n\nAs an undergraduate student, Kaumal was involved in multiple research projects and was awarded the SURE (Summer Undergraduate Research Experience) Award by University College Cork. She also presented her project at the International Association of Dental Research (Irish Division) research day, and was sent to the European conference to present after winning first prize.\n\nKaumal is a Quercus University Scholar for University College Cork since 2015. The Quercus Talented Students Programme aims to support and promote excellence in academia and extra-curricular endeavours, which in Kaumal's case is the visual arts. Kaumal has been a self-taught artist/illustrator since 2014 and has had solo exhibitions in University College Cork, Cork University Hospital and The Institute of Anatomical Sciences. Kaumal specialises in ink drawings and has extended this to medical and dental illustrations.\n\nOverall, Kaumal is an individual with a diverse range of skills with experience in many team and leadership roles. Kaumal gives her utmost to any challenges presented in an academic/professional setting and will strive to achieve personal and team goals.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2010.9 ~ 2011.3', u'description': u'I was the SOA Architect in NYC DOE. Additionally, i played the role of Websphere Message Broker Specialist. My prime job responsibilities included and was not limited to\n\n1. Promoting adoption of ESB across the enterprise\n2. Winning buy-ins for solutions, process and projects from the senior Management. \n3. Product positioning, evaluation and screening. \n4. High level and low level design\n5. Implementing best practices\n6. Architecting and designing Logging, Auditing, Retry and Error-handling frameworks\n7. Devising migration strategies from Message Broker V6.1 to V7.0\n8. Troubleshooting\n9. Compliance\n10. Customer liaison. \n11. Ownership of SLA (service level agreement) enforcement\n12. Delivery and project management. \n13. Implementing SOA governance \n14. Clustering and High Availability in Message Broker V7\n15. Message Broker Development\n\nMy focus area was IBM Websphere Message Broker, IBM Websphere Message Queuing, Datapower, and IBM Websphere Service Registry and Repository (WSRR).', u'title': u'ESB Transformation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ now', u'description': u'Post Obamacare, the healthcare industry is shifting focus towards being consumer-centric. My client being a premier healthcare payer is leading the bandwagon for such transformation. I am the integration lead for the program which is building and maintaining the new state of art platform for enrolling new members and renewing existing ones. Among prominent technologies that are being used are \nIBM Business Process Manager Standard & Advanced (IIB)\nIBM Integration Bus (IIB)\nIBM WebSphere Operational Decision Manager (WODM)\nIBM WebSphere Service Registry and Repository (WSRR)\nIBM Websphere Extreme Scale\nIBM Datapower Gateway XB62\nIBM WebSphere Extreme Scale\nIBM DB2\nJava\nMarkLogic\nCA API Gateway\nSplunk\n\nMy responsibilities included and was not restricted to\n\n>> Liaising with cross functional teams, enterprise architects, product owners, and subject matter experts within Cognizant and my client\n\n>> Leading integration requirements collection, and supporting defining the Business Process\n\n>> Defining solution architecture, integration architecture, high level design, and quality of services for the program\n\n>> Work with IIB, BPM, ODM, DB2, ML, and Java track leads to finalize the low level design\n\n>> Leading integration between EDI gateway, Enterprise Integration Engine, Individual Master, Product Master, B2B gateway, Billing systems, Enrollment Book of Records, Error Book of Records, Organization Book of Records, Plan Providers, layer7, voltage api, event framework, and a multitude of other internal applications using CICS, REST, SOAP, MQ, HTTP, FTP and other protocols. \n\n', u'title': u'Transformation at a Healthcare Giant'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.11 ~ 2014.3', u'description': u'Customer is a global financial services company headquartered in Switzerland. It provides investment banking, asset management and wealth management services for private, corporate and institutional clients worldwide, operating in more than 50 countries. It is considered the world's second largest manager of private wealth assets, with over CHF2.2 trillion in invested assets. The said transformation is for their wealth management division. \nThe customer's IT system is plagued with multiple redundant data sources. IT stakeholders were finding it difficult to determine which source system to resort to, and how many such source systems to resort to. Majority of the core IT applications were IBM mainframe based. Point to point integration with such mainframe systems increased MIPS expenditure.  \nThe program used IBM Integration Bus V9 as an enterprise service bus (ESB). The solution created two ODS. one in z/OS, and one in distributed systems. At any point of time, the ESB kept both these ODS' in sync. The plan was to ensure that the 'golden copy' of data was available in both ODS'. At a later time, when the integrity of data is validated and verified, the ODS in the z/OS would be slowly phased out. Alongside an ESB, the program involved ETL, reporting, and other IT components\nI was the integration architect involved in realizing the ODS and the Enterprise Service Bus. \n', u'title': u'Transformation at a Financial Major'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Telecom companies are facing business and IT challenges in serving its end customers and, in addition, impacting the overall end customer user experience. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2009 ~ 2009', u'description': u'Every drawing needed to have some engineering information associated with it, such as designer, checked, dates, material, QTY, description, assembly, sub-assembly, cooler name, operations, CNC file locations, etc. All these information was typed in or modified manually before. It was time consuming and error prone.\n\nSo I developed a piece of software that minimized engineering effort to put in these information so that about 90% of the drawings can be done with just two clicks, and the others were minimized with required actions. This software utilized a way that repetitive information could be accessed and saved easily. Company operation rules were also integrated into the software so that certain information could be generated automatically without any human interference, such as manufacturing operations and CNC file locations.', u'title': u'Engineering Information Management Software Using SolidWorks VBA Macro'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.4 ~ 2010.4', u'description': u'Developed this silencer from concept prototyping to final full size product. Noise level reduction was from 117db to 76db, exceeding customer required 82db. CFD was heavily used to ensure pressure drop within 1 inch water high at the required air flow rate. Final test result showed my analysis results were more than 95% accuracy.', u'title': u'Radiator silencer development'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.3 ~ 2011.4', u'description': u'Analysis of air flow distributor performance', u'title': u'Cooling Fan Analysis'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011 ~ 2011', u'description': u'When customers request quotes, the time to provide quote drawings or models is critical. The sooner to feedback to customer, the better chance to get orders. In old days, 2D AutoCAD drawings were sufficient for quote purpose. But more and more customers require 3D models for quote nowadays.\n\nTo work out a 3D quote model with more detailed information such as manufacturability, weight and center of gravity, 3 to 5 working days were needed to prepare a quote model with about 300 to 500 parts. To speed up this process, I developed a VBA software program with graphical user friendly interface. It took about 40 seconds to create a model with all details as to every single bold hole.\n\nA detailed quote model like this would obviously provide better image to customers, and that meant a sooner subsequent production could be started once order being placed.', u'title': u'Automatically Create Radiator Package  Using SolidWorks VBA Macro with User Friendly Interface'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.6 ~ 2009.6', u'description': u'This was a project that Copper Core had been working on for a few years without success before I took this project. I found the issue with the original design and changed it. FEA was heavily used to ensure deformation was in check under high pressure. It was tested under 1000 psi continuously 24 hours a day for a week. No leaking was found, far exceeding required 500 psi.', u'title': u'High Pressure Oil Cooler Development'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'To reduce cycle time for the whole assembling process, there was no time allowed for the robot to change its tooling during operation for five different kinds of parts. So the idea was to design a single one tooling to be able to pick up all the five parts. With so many parts to pick up, it meant more parts needed for the tooling. The challenge was that the tooling weight was limited so that robot payload was not exceeded. FEA was used to reduce any possible weight without adding too much manufacturing cost. The design was successful with added self jaw position calibrating functionality, reduced the need for another separate calibration device and some cycle time.', u'title': u'Robot End of Arm Tooling Design'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.3 ~ 2013.3', u'description': u'This is a project had stopped for a while before I took it. This is a typical 3-axis machine design in my career, so there was nothing too excited about the machine itself, but every part came together perfectly. The important thing was that the customer was happy and they added more orders after first delivery. The customer also granted us another type of aberrometer design and build.', u'title': u'Contact lens measuring aberrometer design'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2004 ~ 2004', u'description': u'The rendering needed to convert a very complex model from 3D AutoCAD to SolidWorks, then a rendering with very realistic settings was performed. It needed about 40 hours to create the 20 seconds video. It should be a regular rendering task, but the rendering corrupted two times on my workstation. Then the company decided to run the rendering on the most powerful computer in the company, the server computer. But the rendering corrupted again.\n\nWith all the resources run out and the company needed the video right away, I had one last resort to use: my knowledge in computer. After quick investigation into the corrupted video file, I found out that the rendering was almost finished before corruption. to be exactly, It was only a fraction of a second remaining before the rendering process corrupted. That was a good news. I guessed that SolidWorks just did not have a chance to wrap up the file, then it crashed. What I needed to do is wrap the file up manually with correct information, i.e. repair the file header, which contains information about the video file, such as video frame size, frame rate. I researched into the video file data structure and got an understanding of it. Then I needed to obtain the correct file header. To do this, I rendered the same file with exact the same settings, but just with a very short time of rendering. I got a file modification tool and used it to copy the newly rendered file header and pasted to the corrupted file and with a little more additional manual modifications, the file could be played on Windows Media Player correctly and smoothly. All of these took me half day from morning to noon.', u'title': u'Realistic Video Rendering Using SolidWorks'}]

summary: Andrew is a business and intellectual property attorney with Lenhart Pettit in Charlottesville, Virginia, where he advises companies and individuals regarding intellectual property and technology, cybersecurity and data privacy, business law, and securities and private equity. Andrew has been selected to the Virginia Rising Stars list by Super Lawyers (2013 - 2017) and has received the Emerson G. Spies Award from The Virginia Bar Association. You can follow Andrew on Twitter @AndrewStockment.\n\nAndrew is a technology and innovation enthusiast and works with startups and established companies to form and grow their businesses and develop, protect, and license their intellectual property assets. Andrew counsels clients regarding information governance and data security and privacy issues and assists organizations with data breach notification compliance, and he advises clients regarding the preparation and negotiation of contracts and the organization, operation, purchase, financing, and sale of businesses. Before becoming an attorney, Andrew worked as a software engineer for the Cerner Corporation and owned a website development business for several years.\n\nAndrew is active in The Virginia Bar Association and serves in various leadership capacities. He currently serves on the VBA Intellectual Property and Information Technology Law Section Council and the VBA Board of Governors, and he is the Chair-Elect of the VBA Young Lawyers Division.\n\nAndrew graduated from the University of Virginia School of Law, where he served on the Editorial Board of the Virginia Law Review and the Managing Board of the Virginia Journal of Social Policy & the Law, and he earned his bachelor's degree in Management Information Systems and Political Science from Florida State University. Andrew and his wife, Martha, are active members of Trinity Presbyterian Church and enjoy spending time with their daughter, hiking, and watching UVA Men's Basketball.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'A F#-based library for functions used in solving Project Euler problems along with some basic statistical functions.', u'title': u'Mathematical'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'A library that provides simplified threaded and non-threaded execution of SQL statements. It can be used to expose an interface to Microsoft Excel clients, providing threaded, async operations to a single-threaded application.', u'title': u'SqlExecutionAddIn'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'This sample combines the Facade pattern with the Publisher (Observer) pattern. The primary class, based on the ISubscriber interface, is fairly complicated to use, requiring delegates, threading, and asynchronous callbacks. The facade, based on ISubscriberFacade, encapsulates all the methods required to work with the Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) service , handling threading, delegate creation, and asynchronous callbacks internally, so that that the clients only need to create the object. I wrote the encapsulating client to ease the adoption of the WCF service for legacy clients, seeing that the code complexity was likely a hurdle.', u'title': u'Publisher'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.12 ~ now', u'description': u'Delving into learning F# while working through various texts, writing simple code to solve complex problems.', u'title': u'Learning F#'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.1 ~ now', u'description': u'An exploration of data and analytics, partially triggered by Microsoft's moves to incorporate R into SQL Server, as well as Visual Studio's integration with Python, making data analytics an easier option, as well as a likely necessity for my career.', u'title': u'DATA ANALYTICS WORKOUTS'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'A simple NuGet package for easy access to API's, but only currently supporting Glassdoor. summary: I am a skilled graphic designer with over 10 years of professional experience primarily in corporate design with some freelance, and a dedicated project manager with over 5 years of professional experience. \n\nAs a graphic designer I like to create unique and smart design with a goal of no limitations. I feel that a strong design can be both a solution and an inspiration. My approach to a design project is a detailed outline to use as a foundation and with each iteration see what it evolves to.  \n\nI am most interested in logo/brand design, typography, installation, and trade show booth design. \n\nAs a project manager I am driven by the process, structure, teamwork, and communication required to be successful. These skills also translate well into my graphic design methods. In my current role I have successfully created, implemented, and trained on a number of processes and procedures that have been used across many departments. These processes and procedures have reduced the overall production time spent by both internal and external resources and assisted in maintaining or reducing the project budget.  \n \nCurrently I am responsible for graphic design focused in the international marketing materials, project management of international and special projects, the marketing departments PO processing, document inventory, budget records, vendor records, document control and regulatory approval processing. \n\nExperience: Project coordination/management, graphic design, brand strategy/development, trade show booth design, vendor relations, customer service, time management, presenting/public speaking, budget management, process development/implementation/training, team building exercises, inventory management, PO processing.\n\nSystems: Adobe Creative Suite, Microsoft Office, SAP, NextDocs, BaseCamp, SharePoint, Clarizen.\n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The ultimate aim of this project is to automate the work that is being carried out in Jeyamary Cable TV, Tharuvaikulam. Various Reports are generated for tracking decision and future use. \n\nVisual Basic 6.0, Oracle', u'title': u'Cable TV Management'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The ultimate aim of this project is to computerize the manual work carried out in the hostel. Student personal details are maintained and phone charge, token charge and Other charges have been calculated. Various Reports have been generated to display in the notice board.\n\nVisual C++, Oracle\n', u'title': u'Hostel Management'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Zoho sheet has its own calculating engine known as Zoho Engine. The existing VBA macro used Open Office Spreadsheet API to do all spreadsheet actions. So we planned to remove the dependency of Open Office API due to the performance issue. So we have completely reemployment all the classes which were used Open Office API. The existing Macro execution response to the client is in XML format. We have generated new JSON response for the macro execution and we used similar JSON which is used for action JSON in undo/redo.\n\nResponsibilities:\n Reimplement core classes which are used for VBA macro execution\n Implement most of the VBA classes and used Zoho Engine API\nAdd a JSON object  to a collection for each macro function execution\nSimplify and remove duplicated JSON in the action JSON collection\nCreated a generic class which creates respective JSON response for the specific action JSON\nProcess each JSON in client and update the respective action to the client\nModularized the response creation in server and updating it in client for future use\nImproved the complete performance of Macro execution\nWrite use cases\nTesting\nFixing Defects', u'title': u'Integrate VBA Macro in Zoho Engine'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'After VBA macro implementation, the user has to do many clicks to run a VBA Macro. He has to select the macro menu and then select the Run Macro in the sub menu. It will list all the available VBA macros after that user has to select the macro which has to be run. We planned to support button and user can assign a macro to the button and run the macro by single click.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\nAnalyzed and designed\nUsed respective API to create, modify and read buttons from spreadsheet both in Zoho Engine and Open Office Spreadsheet\nHandled two different implementation in server side one for Zoho Engine and another one Open Office Spreadsheet\nCreate our own javascript button object\nHandled all the UI design for the button such as add new button, change caption, assign macro, resize, move and delete\nChange the button to design mode to modify the button\nRun the macro when user click the button\nShow respective error message if the macro does not exist or any parser error \nShow the messages if the macro has any messages\nGave knowledge transfer to other team member to do the remaining works such as testing, issue fixing and support the feature.\n', u'title': u'Button'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'It is my first project. First i understood what is the product and how it is working. I learnt struts framework and I implemented I18n to Zoho Sheet.\n\nResponsibilities :\n\nAnalyzed the product\nDesigned how to implement it\nGathered all the messages used in the user Interface\nUsed property files to store the messages as key and value pair\nCreated a java bean to get the property message using the user locale\nLoad the default property file if the respective locale file does not exit\nTo support any new language in Zoho Sheet, we need to add the specific property for that language\nAll JSP files uses the java bean to get the message for the key\nCreated a java script object and write it in client at initial loading of a page\nCompletely modified all the text messages using jsp tags for JSP files and used json objects for java script files.\nTesting and Fixing defects\nGave knowledge transfer to all the team members to support I18n for their feature', u'title': u'I18N in Zoho Sheet'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Responsibilities:\nGave knowledge transfer to the team new members how the existing system works\nTrained them how the action JSON works in undo/redo and macro and helped them to reuse it for each action in Zoho Sheet\nHelped them to categorize all the actions in the zoho sheet\nHelped them in developing specific JSON object for each action\nChanged the existing XML response model to JSON response model for all the actions\nReused the macro response update in client and did some changes in it and do update all the client response\nDiscussed and analyzed with other dependent team and worked with them to send our action response to their WMS server and receive the same in our client\nCreate all client Ajax request at one place \nCreated our own Java script Objects to manage the following\nHold the information to create specific AJAX request\nCreate the specific Information object for each client action\nQueue all the AJAX request object in client and send one by one to server\nQueue all the responses and update it sequentially in client\nTrack the missing response and sync with other collaborators in that spreadsheet\nI have implemented many generic objects and used for some of the spreadsheet action\nLater I gave knowledge transfer for the following and trained team members how to use it for all the spreadsheet actions\nAll the client custom java script object\nHow to define information for each action in client\nHow to create respective action JSON in server\nJSON response creation and how it is updated in the client\nIntegrated undo/redo features in the latest implementation\nIntegrated VBA macro in the latest implementation\nInvolved team collaboration testing\nFixing  defects', u'title': u'Collaboration'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The ultimate aim of this project is to Computerize the administration of the AVM Hospital, Tuticorin. This project deals with the works at the reception counter of the hospital, administration and bill processing.\n\nVisual Basic 6.0 , MSAccess\n', u'title': u'Hospital Management'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Responsibilities:\nAnalyzed the existing undo/redo feature implementation\nRedesigned and suggested different styles of implementation depends on future requirements\nFinalized the best design pattern\nIntroduced JSON objects and store each user action information in a file \nUsed stack implementation to store undo/redo actions JSON in server object\n Each user actions are translated to JSON Object\n When user do undo/redo, the respective JSON is parsed and will do the corresponding action\n Created util class for spreadsheet actions, It is used by actual user action, undo and  redo\n  Modularized all the existing spreadsheet actions code and avoided code duplication\n  Handled for all the spreadsheet actions which can be undo/redo\n  Resolved all the limitations which exist in the previous implementation\nRemoved the maximum limit(10) for undo/redo\nSupport undo/redo after sheet rename\nUser specific undo/redo while the spreadsheet is in collaboration mode\nThe cell reference will be changed after row/column insertion or deletion by the collaborators, It has been handled in the latest undo/redo implementation\nGive specific error message when the cell reference is changed while trying to do undo/redo\nImproved performance\nRemoved code duplication both in server side and client side\n   Clean up all the unused code both client and server side after the new implementation\n   Write the use case for undo/redo features\n   Testing \n   Fixing Defects\n', u'title': u'Undo/Redo'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'After Zoho sheet Internationalized, we are in need of the translation for each language. So we planned to do that by our users itself. So we planned to implement in a way that user can do their translation for their own language. We have added more than twenty languages in the translation site. We got more than 80% translation in six languages and it is updated in the Zoho Sheet.\n\nResponsibilities : \n\nAnalyzed and designed \nDiscussed with internal team who did the framework for database operations and find the solutions for maintain the translation for each language in database\nUsed their internal framework to do all the database operations\nMaintained all the languages and translations in database\nList all the translating languages with their progress of translation\nUsers can translate all the messages either in table or WYSIWYG mode\nIn WYSIWYG mode the user can do translation directly in the Zoho Sheet UI itself\nSpecial cases handled for java script and JSP files messages for WYSIWYG mode\nAllowed version view for each language\nUser can rollback to any version\nWhen the translation progress reaches above 80%, will get the translated messages as property file\nTesting \nFixing defects', u'title': u'L10N in Zoho Sheet'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Cell protection is protect the cell, range or sheet in a spreadsheet from modifying it. It is mainly used while the spreadsheet in the collaboration. The spreadsheet owner or co-owner can protect any cell, range or sheet from other shared users. It is a new feature to the Zoho Sheet.\n\nResponsibilities:\nAnalyzed and designed \nWrote the use cases\nCreated our own java script object to handle the protected range\nGive different visual effects to the protected range\nAllow the owner or co-owner of the spreadsheet to create, modify and delete the protected range\nProtect the collaborators from editing the protected range in client side\nProtect the range from modifying via macro, undo or redo in serve side\nAllow the owner or co-owner to change the permissions to all the collaborators including themselves\nShow specific error message if the collaborators try to modify the protected range\nGave knowledge transfer about this project to the team member ', u'title': u'Cell Protection'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The \u2018Data Gathering Tool\u2019 I built for Corporate Citizenship helped save them over 120 hours per month by automating several processes.\n\nCorporate Citizenship have offices around the world, each of which gathers data on its client\u2019s satisfaction. It was then the job of their London office to collate this data and report on it each month. This was a long process that involved lots of emails and cutting and pasting.\n\nMy tool reduced the whole process to just a few mouse clicks. Each office would store their data in a shared location from which the tool could import. Once imported the tool automatically processed the data and presented it in a KPI dashboard report format.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more. ', u'title': u'Data Gathering Tool \u2013 Corporate Citizenship'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'I helped ALUK save over 3,500 hours when they merged multiple stock control systems.\n\nAfter acquiring another business ALUK needed to merge several stock systems that had little or no commonality.  With tens of thousands of SKUs, assemblies and sub-assemblies this created a large problem.\n\nThe data conversion tool I developed for ALUK broke each SKU, assembly and sub-assembly in their component parts before rebuilding the data in to a common format and re-cross referenced. Once in a completed the data was simply re-imported.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Data Conversion Tool - ALUK'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The Excel Expert saved Pepsico an estimated 2,500 hours per year over several projects they completed for them.\n\nOur main project for Pepsico was a hedge fund management tool.\n\nPepsico regularly purchased hedge funds in order to counter pricing movements in their supply commodities. With dozens of Pepsico owned brands and thousands of products to protect, the amount of hedge funds needed exceeded $500m.\n\nThe tool Excel Expert developed for Pepsico helped them manage and monitor the hedge funds performances. This included the preparation of all the legally required hedge fund documentation. Additional features included facilities for producing ad-hoc and pre-set reports.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Hedge Fund Management Tool - Pepsico'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'TT Electronics produce wiring looms and related electronics equipment for the aerospace industry and the military. Each wiring loom is made of numerous components, wires and sub-assemblies. Each sub-assembly is also made of a wide range of components, wires and the occasional sub-sub-assembly.\n\nTT Electronics needed a way to manage materials and production of work orders so Excel Expert developed a materials scheduling tool with two main functions.\n\nThe first section of the materials scheduling tool gathered a list of components, wires, materials and sub-assemblies from TT Electronics existing database. From this, the tool was able to build a complete bill of materials (including sub-assemblies) and cross-referenced them against existing stock levels. The second section of the tool used this information to schedule the work through the factory.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Materials Scheduling Tool \u2013 TT-Electronics'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'At MGN Fire Protection, not all of the construction and installation work they carried out could be pre-planned so MGN required a cost monitoring tool that was both flexible and accurate.\n\nThey discovered existing tools were available but could not cope easily with ad-hoc additions to contracts that they needed to be able to control costs for. Excel Expert created a tool that could accept additional work, track the costs and the payments collected against them. Our system replaced a number of paperwork and spreadsheet systems with an all in one solution.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Contract Management Tool \u2013 MGN Fire Protection'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Weedon PSC needed a production planning tool to manage their manufacturing process (printing, cutting, folding, gluing and assembling). The production planning tool had to take in to account clients just in time ordering, their own just in time purchasing of materials and a variety of prioritisation planning methods.\n\nUsing their existing system as a template we devised an Excel based production scheduling tool that allows the planners at Weedon PSC to enter the details of incoming jobs, including the materials and tools needed, as well as various other variables defining their production machines printing speeds, preparation times and planned down times.\n\nA simple to use planning screen in the production scheduling tool allows their planners to try out various \u201cwhat if\u201d scenarios to check the impact of any planned changes. They can view the impact any changes have on the planning from anywhere between the next hour to the next few weeks. Planning priorities can easily be switched between simple delivery date priorities and other more complex priority methods.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Production Scheduling Tool - Weedon PSC'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'With numerous funders providing leasing deals on thousands of different cars, CarLeasing-Online.co.uk needed a way to automatically pick out the best deals for it\u2019s price comparison website.\n\nThe automated system developed by Excel Expert reduced this heavily manually process (that took over a week to complete), in to one that took just a few mouse clicks to complete.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Car Leasing Pricing Tool \u2013 CarLeasing-Online.co.uk'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'A \u2018Client Analysis Tool\u2019 I developed for The Amazing Support Company saved them 120 hours of manual data processing.\n\nThe Amazing Support Company provide a wide range of IT maintenance contracts at different levels. At the end of each year they needed to study their data to work out which of their clients were profitable, which were not and if there were any new opportunities.\n\nThe Client Analysis Tool Excel Expert built allowed the Amazing Support Company to drill down in to their client data by location, contract types, products covered, number of call outs, expense and profit levels. This level of automation saved them 3 weeks work.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Client Analysis Tool - Amazing Support Company'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The \u2018Financial Reporting Tool\u2019 I developed for AFME helps simplify their reporting process and saves them over 300 hours per year.\n\nAFME Surveyed its members each month on a wide range of topics and needed to combine the results with a number of sources of financial data. This was mainly a manual process of cutting and pasting data from one source to another.\n\nThe financial reporting tool I developed for AFME automated the process. It converted the data in to a common format, cross referenced the data and presented the results in a KPI dashboard.\n\nClick the project heading above to read more.', u'title': u'Financial Reporting Tool - Association for Financial Markets in Europe (AFME)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Unit Birwelco take several months to manufacture their specialist super-heater products used in heavy engineering sites such as power stations. With a full order book, UNIT Birwelco was finding production planning difficult and needed a bespoke production management tool.\n\nI developed an Excel based production planning tool that allowed UNIT Birwelco to enter and edit the details of any contracts they won. The tool then showed their planners several graphical reports instantly showing the impact of the project. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.2', u'description': u'In response to the classic problem of balancing Inventory Investment with Service Level, a numerical model was developed within VBA/Excel to estimate /forecast inventory demand one month into the future. A numerical approach was selected because it was perceived that traditional Statistical methods were suboptimal for estimating inventory demand. The author developed a Numerical Demand Estimation Model that is designed to approximate human Demand Planning /forecasting judgment. This paper determined that the numerical model provides inventory management advantages over two traditional Statistical approaches to demand estimation: (A) the Three-Month Simple Moving Average (3M MA), and, (B) the Six-Month Simple Moving Average (6M MA). However, the advantages come with the sacrifice of a portion of the Service Level that is provided by Moving Averages. A computer simulation of inventory behavior was developed to evaluate the performance of the Numerical Model relative to the capabilities of the 3M and 6M MAs. Tables of sensitivity /performance data for the three models are provided in the \', u'title': u'Sensitivity Analysis - Numerical Demand Estimation Model'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.3 ~ 2009.3', u'description': u'Developed an engineering computer program that reduced the time required for a specific type of high-volume insurance coverage determination from six to 1.5 hours.', u'title': u'Residential Slab Performance Analysis Computer Program'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'Developed and validated a VBA/Excel computer program that simulates the human judgment involved in estimating current demand from monthly historical data. Results: (1) program suppresses short-term Demand Spikes and Demand Surges, thereby preventing high-probability over-buying; (2) program factors in Demand Trend into the Demand estimate; (3) automated Demand estimates have been confirmed by visual inspection (success ratio: 150/150); (4) approximate time savings: 15 hours / month.', u'title': u'Demand Estimation Computer Program'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2004.8 ~ 2004.8', u'description': u'Automated (via PowerBASIC Component Object Model (COM) programming) the acquisition of information required by management for early warning on positive and negative trends in claims data.  Developed performance indicators and the required multi-parameter data sort computer procedures.  Provided critical information to management on trends in its operations data while shifting the equivalent 12-hour manual Excel task to the computer.', u'title': u'Insurance Claims Trend Analysis Computer Program'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2007.10 ~ 2007.10', u'description': u'Engineered a business solution to more restrictive foundation performance requirements imposed by the State of Texas.  Solution determined new foundation requirements based on foundation failure-risk and cost considerations.  Solution enabled insurance company to continue operating in Texas with acceptable risk and a competitively-priced product.', u'title': u'Residential Slab Deflection Risk Management Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.1 ~ 2017.1', u'description': u'Course project for Coursera / Rutgers University online course in \', u'title': u'Supply Chain Planning / Demand Analysis Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'Developed and validated two VBA/Excel computer programs that accomplish the following: (a) determination of statistical lead times from individual purchase order lead time data downloaded from Oracle; (b) assignment of the statistical lead times to an Excel workbook that determines inventory reorder points. Results: (1) increased the accuracy of replenishment lead time estimates; (2) effectively updated vendor lead times without having to contact vendors for current lead times (vendor lead times had not been updated for eight years); (3) a pre-implementation test on four items revealed the applied statistical method accurately estimated lead times while permitting a 100-percent service level. Associated total inventory test savings: $31,373. Based on the success of the pilot program, statistical lead time use was expanded to 383 stocked inventory items.', u'title': u'Statistical Lead Times Computer Program'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.2', u'description': u'To evaluate the performance of the Demand Estimation Model (including its Sensitivity), a ReOrder-\nPoint-based Inventory Simulation Program was developed in VBA/Excel. Following are key aspects of the program.\n\nA. It utilizes actual demand on 197 Purchased-Finished Goods (PFG) items from Supplies shipping\nhistory. (This decision imposes a real-world condition on the simulation and permits accurate model error assessment.)\n\nB. The test forecast period is 12 months (2014) with the simulation commencing on 1/1/2014 (with inventory starting at the Reorder Point), and concluding on 12/31/2014.\n\nC. The Simulation Program calls the Demand Estimation Model being evaluated. In other words, the Simulation Program is a test program, separate from the Demand Estimation Model.\n\nD. Lead time variation was not included in the simulation.\n\nE. Order minimums and multiples were not included in the simulation because this helps isolate\nDemand Estimation Method efficiencies, making them as apparent as possible.\n\nF. Inclusion of a 30-day Economic Order Quantity. This means that when the Reorder Point is reached, the program orders enough for 30-days' demand beyond the Reorder Point; thereby imposing once-a-month ordering.', u'title': u'Inventory Behavior Simulation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.6 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'Developed and validated a VBA/Excel computer program that determines the basic Material Requirements Planning (MRP) parameters: ReOrder Point and Economic Order Quantity.  Program capitalizes on prior Inventory Management programming work: Statistical Lead Times, Demand Estimation.', u'title': u'Material Requirements Planning (MRP) Parameters Computer Program'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.6 ~ 2013.6', u'description': u'Developed and validated a VBA/Excel computer program that: (a) captures inventory sales data from a \u201cSales-By-Vendor\u201d Excel workbook, (b) groups it by geographical region; (c) captures and reports award-customer sales data; and (d) graphs inventory sales data along with the associated regression lines and centered moving averages. Results: (1) improved the estimation of sales trend and volume (fundamental inventory management parameters) by replacing visual inspection of number matrices with a simple graphical method; (2) increased inventory management productivity by about 300 percent with no loss of demand forecasting accuracy.', u'title': u'Historical Demand Graphs Computer Program'}]

Also available for evening technical training sessions.\n\nRoy likes to help projects to improve and optimize their applications by constantly review and evaluate the implemented system.\n\nRoy is also experienced with Agile methodologies, currently holding the following Srcum.org certificates: Professional Scrum Developer (PSD 1), Professional Scrum Master (PSM 1), Professional Scrum Product Owner (PSPO 1)\n\n** Skills **\nBlogger, writer, speaker, coach, trainer, coaching-on-the-job and generating new business.\n\n\n** Tools and techniques **\nOperating systems: Windows, Mac, Unix desktop, Unix server and virtualization\n\nProgramming skills: Java, PHP, C#\n\nJava: Apache Components, Jersey, Maven, Spring, Selenium WebDriver,\nJbehave, TestNG, Junit\n\nPHP: Composer, PEAR, PHPunit, Behat, Mink, PHPWebDriver, codeception,\nphing (php build automation)\n\nTools: JUnit, TestNG, Jbehave, FitNesse, Nunit, OSMO (Model Based\nTesting), Selenium (IDE, RC / WebDriver, Grid), White, Jmeter, SoapUI,\nTestlink Test Case Management, Mantis Bug tracker, Jira, Hamcrest (including custom matchers), Jenkins CI\n\nTechniques: Automated functional testing, automated localization\ntesting, Excellent understanding of REST APIs and structured responses\nsuch as JSON or XML, Image comparison, server-side components/Web\nservices (like WSDL and XML/RPC), Behaviour Driven Testing, Page Object\nModel, Data Driven Testing, all kinds of website optimization\ntechniques.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'I developed and reviewed Test Case Verification Analysis (TCVA) within the Astronics Advanced Electronics System (AES) Electronic Circuit Breaker Unit (ECBU) used with C code for requirements being verified under the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) 61508-3 Software Requirements Safety Standard.  Astronics\u2019 ECBU is used as a circuit breaker for power supplies within various commercial airplanes, and my work assisted the verification of the software within such units.\n\nThe IEC 61508-3 work was done on Verocel\u2019s VeroTrace Requirements-Based Testing (RBT) Computer-Aided Software Engineering (CASE) tool.  I was responsible for developing TCVAs which combined my analysis of the latest ECBU source code with head real-time timing results of that code; which provided an assessment whether each timing requirement was being met based on both test results and how the source code was structured.  These assessments were a combination of narrative text supplemented by spreadsheets that extracted key timing results.  I also reviewed the TCVAs developed by other team members.  My contributions (along with those of others on the team) were combined to provide a complete RBT of the entire ECBU.', u'title': u'Astronics Advanced Electronics System (AES) Electronic Circuit Breaker Unit (ECBU) Software Certification'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.8', u'description': u'I reviewed detailed requirements, Requirement Verification Analysis (RVA), Test Cases (TC) and C language Test Files (TF) for requirements being verified under the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) DO-178C Software Requirements Safety Standard for Real-Time Innovations\u2019 (RTI) Connext Micro Data Distribution System (DDS) for XCalibur1700 target processors (Power PC) using the VxWorks Real-Time Operations System (RTOS).  RTI\u2019s DDS is an implementation of the Object Management Group\u2019s (OMG) DDS standard, which provides a \u201cpublish & subscribe\u201d model of reliably delivery data over distributed computer networks.  DDS is a variation of OMG\u2019s Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) optimized for data transport, using CORBA\u2019s model of data readers and writer which a derived a run-time from pre-defined \u201cfactory\u201d object patterns that produce these services.\n\nThe DO-178C work was done on Verocel\u2019s VeroTrace Requirements-Based Testing (RBT) Computer-Aided Software Engineering (CASE) tool.  I was responsible for reviewing assigned portions of the RTI-developed DDS requirements for testability and correctness, ensuring RVAs & TCs were reviewed to verify these software requirements, and reviewing the TFs that individually tested each DDS requirement.  My contributions (along with those of others on the team) were combined to provide a complete RBT of entire RTI DDS.', u'title': u'Real-Time Innovations\u2019 (RTI) Connext Micro Data Distribution System (DDS)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'OFP is an avionics support application that monitors aircraft performance, relays pilot instructions to various aircraft components, and provides cockpit status displays.\n\nResponsible for developing:\n\u2022\tDevelopment of Requirement Verification Approaches (RVA) for customer\u2019s requirements for some of the OFP components\n\u2022\tFormal review of other team members\u2019 requirements, RVAs, and Test Files for assigned OFP components\n\u2022\tProblem Reports to formally raise technical issues with these requirements, RVAs, Test Files and other artifacts with the customer\n\nI used Verocel's proprietary VeroTrace requirement and test Validation & Verification (V&V) management tool to support Requirement-Based Testing (RBT) approach. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'', u'title': u'BEAST'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'Laboratory summary: investigate physiological brain pathways underling generation and regulation of pain and emotion. The study of relationships between brain processes, affective responses, and physiology using interventions and outcomes relevant for emotional health. \n\nISSUE:\nLoss of 500,000 fMRI PTSD image dataset because of 10-15% were corrupted.\n\nSOLUTION SUMMARY:\nAnalyzed noisy PTSD fMRI data utilizing machine-learning methods to save image dataset.\n\nALGORITHMS:\nSupport Vector Machine (SVMs): supervised learning algorithm used for classification and regression analysis. The SVM is binary classification algorithm. Given a set of training examples, SVM training algorithm builds a model that assigns new examples to one category or the other, thus a non-probabilistic binary linear classifier. \n\nPrinciple Component Analysis (PCA): technique that finds underlying variables (principal components) that best differentiate data points. Principal components are dimensions along data points are most spread out, utilizing a Singular Value Decomposition (SVD). \n\nLAB and DATA TOOLS:\nFunctional magnetic resonance imaging or functional MRI (fMRI) is a functional neuroimaging procedure using MRI technology that measures brain activity by detecting changes associated with blood flow. \n\nData resides within a local linux hard drive\nFSL \u2013 Brain imaging software - utilized to access and view fMRI images \nUtilized R various packages for algorithm analysis and visualization.\n\nRESULTS AND CONCLUSION:\nInitial training gave only a marginal accuracy. The second attempt after performing a PCA to reduce dimensionality and improve signal to noise ratio provided a trained algorithm of 87%. Saved the entire test dataset of 500,000 images utilizing our trained SVM classifier. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.5 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'Mr. Prasad worked on designing a niche mental health electronic medical record solution for the capture, storage and tracking of behavioral health information. The application of this solution will be in the areas of post traumatic stress disorder military personnel and sports concussions and related injuries of athletes at different transition points in their continuum of care. While techniques, assessments and imaging technologies exist for the identification of mental health related conditions, there is a capability gap for the storage and tracking of this data. \n\nThis solution will also incorporate multi-factor security measures to ensure data privacy. This increased security capability will help to reduce stigma associated with mental health disorders and encourage patients to be more open about sharing information their condition. This security process will also allow the privacy for the patient while at the same time leaving the de-identified data available to perform decision support and population health analytics. \n', u'title': u'Behavioral and Mental Health EMR Solution'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2002.7 ~ 2005.5', u'description': u'Mr. Prasad has been engaged as an enterprise IT architect for the Department of Defense Business Modernization Management Program (BMMP) since its inception in 2002. He worked on developing the Business Enterprise Architecture (BEA) for DoD. Mr. Prasad has provided inputs to management on enterprise transformation, architecture requirements and usage, and conceptual design of a service-oriented architecture. He has performed the functional analysis and design for a defense-wide, reference implementation architecture. Mr. Prasad has represented BMMP and participated in DoD-wide working groups on the DoD Global Information Grid, Net Centricity and Net Centric Enterprise Services programs. These topics include Enterprise Services Management, Core Enterprise Service Metadata, Information Assurance, Messaging, Mediation, GIG Enterprise Services Strategy, as well as DoD Executive Boards and Steering Groups. In this capacity, he has performed functional requirements analysis on DoD-wide functional requirements and also provided technical guidance on the design and performance of technical capabilities in a service oriented environment, using the DOD Architecture Framework (DODAF). Mr. Prasad has co-authored two white papers: \u201cGIG Mission Area Integration Strategy\u201d and \u201cCore Business Mission Impact on the DoD Business Enterprise Architecture\u201d. ', u'title': u'DoD Business Enterprise Architecture'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2000.10 ~ 2001.5', u'description': u'Mr. Prasad served as part of the Complex e-Business Review Team within IBM. In this capacity and in conjunction with the chief architect of the team, he performed technical reviews and quality assurance on all large-scale technical solution and implementation designs on engagements larger than one million dollars for IBM customers. Reviews ranged from proposal definition and refinement to technical solution design to software coding and development guidance. Engagements included leaders within the automotive, distribution, consumer and retail, government, and transportation industries.', u'title': u'Complex Projects Analysis and Review'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.1 ~ 2012.10', u'description': u'Mr. Prasad is currently working on a planned community in Nigeria, at the request of one of the state governments. This project covers up to 3500 hectares and at least 4000 housing units. The community is designed to be a self-sustaining community with its own infrastructure, power, utilities, and commercial and residential facilities. ', u'title': u'Planned Community and Real Estate Development in Africa'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.4 ~ 2012.2', u'description': u'Mr. Prasad has played a critical role in the pre-planning efforts supporting the development of hydroelectric and renewable energy capacities in Nigeria. This includes the development of the project proposal for Power Group Global Industries covering initial feasibility and engineering design phases in advance of construction. Mr. Prasad has also coordinated project principals in key tasks and activities and in future project management responsibilities including task tracking, cost management, coordination of US and African engineering teams, data collection and onsite engineering support, and contract negotiations. ', u'title': u'Hydroelectric and Renewable Energy in Africa'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2005.12 ~ 2007.2', u'description': u'Mr. Prasad has been engaged in an IBM internal project for its Human Resources division called the Global Opportunity Marketplace. It is job applicant tracking system for IBM employees and candidate job seekers. Mr. Prasad worked through the entire first phase from an end-to-end lifecycle deployment starting at vendor and technology selection to design and testing. This was a Service Oriented Architecture deployment utilizing a third-party vendor solution for applicant tracking and integrating it with IBM data resources and global networks. This first phase is a pilot for India and five European countries. Mr. Prasad developed the integration requirements and high-level global integration design to support this solution. He also worked with the network design team to develop a bandwidth expansion solution for the India segment of the global network solution. He also helped in the integration and data standards management processes for the project technical team. Mr. Prasad attended HR taxonomy working group meetings in support of Global OM and was also its representative to the IBM HR Workforce Management Initiative Architecture Council. ', u'title': u'IBM Global Opportunity Marketplace'}]
skills: [u'Architecture Frameworks', u'IT Strategy', u'Healthcare', u'Enterprise Architecture']
summary: Currently, Mr. Prasad is focused on developing a cloud-based, integrted healthcare technical framework prototype leveraging televideo, big data, data visualization, brainwave monitoring sensors, and eventually an electronic medical record to address needs within the employee stress reduction, veterans with PTSD and sports concussion monitoring. \n\nMr. Prasad previously worked as VP, Architecture and Technology for Integral and Open Systems, focusing on infrastructure/platform-as-a-service and cloud solutions for IOS customers. He has also served as an enterprise architect and management consultant with over 20 years of experience in the fields of engineering and computer science and over 10 years at the enterprise level. \n\nMr. Prasad has worked for ten years as an enterprise architect at IBM’s Enterprise Architecture & Technology Center of Excellence. He has consulted for the largest Fortune 100 companies and government organizations providing IT assessments, architectural analysis and design, systems and performance review and design, and white papers and other thought leadership. \n\nPrior to his work at IBM, Mr. Prasad worked for twelve years as an electrical engineer at the US Army’s Night Vision Research Lab. He has a B.S. and M.E. in electrical engineering and a B.S. in computer science.\n\nSpecialties: Healthcare Information Technologies\nCloud, Platform and Infrastructure Services\nEnterprise Architecture and Assessment\nExecutive Consulting\nCross-Industry Architecture and Technology\nGlobal Business Solutions

summary: David has 24 years of IT experience in the retail and supply chain industries.  David has 17 years experience in software and system architecture and with 8 years experience in Enterprise Architecture with very large and heterogeneous systems\n\nDavid is currently using a modified TOGAF/DODAF framework for developing enterprise Architecture.  David has developed a 4-step process within TOGAF that he has used with the business in elaborating their strategies, identifying the business gaps, risks and solutions, identifying the IT gaps and solutions and developing the business/IT alignment, proposed transition plans, dependencies and estimated budgets.  David has developed a framework of capabilities, processes, domain entities, application features, components and technology platforms that he uses to rationalize and simplify IT.\n\nDavid leverages OOAD techniques to identify the core components of the business and develop the conceptual information structures and ontology as well as the potential software components.  David utilizes UML and MDA techniques to develop the conceptual, logical software and system designs.  David has experience in designing n-tier and SOA based applications on the MVS, Unix and Microsoft operating platforms.\n\nDavid is an experienced process engineer leveraging BMM, BPM and UML to develop conceptual business designs, functional process flows and detailed workflows.  David has facilitated as well as participated in business design workshops identifying business change and requirements.  David has experience in both Monte Carlo and discrete simulation to improve process efficiency.  \n\nDavid is considered an IT subject matter expert in supply chain including replenishment, order management, inventory management, distribution and transportation.  He has led architectural engagements that have integrated the traditional retail supply chain with the multi-channel supply chain.

summary: Joe Shepherd is a Booz Allen Principal with over 25 years of management and technical experience within DOD as both a government civilian and contractor. He played a key role in the development of the Booz Allen Dahlgren office and led a firm-wide initiative to develop the growing Directed Energy (DE) business from a small group of engineers to one of the largest providers of DE engineering services for the DOD. Prior to his current role, Joe led the cross-cut sales agent team chartered with the growth and integration of Booz Allen Engineering Services (BES) within Booz Allen, and served as the Navy Warfare Center market lead. Drawing on his experience in complex weapon system development and as an established leader in the firm’s DE business, Joe serves as the Principal Lead of Booz Allen's DE Innovation Service Offering.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2002.3 ~ 2005.12', u'description': u'My assignment to Space Launch Initiative (SLI) was to write the proposal sections dealing with overall program and configuration management, and systems engineering. SLI's goal was the commercialization of space access, in half the time to market and at half the cost of the Space Shuttle. The SLI proposal included many concepts that had been outlined in earlier proposals, but with the notable exception that I stated that these goals were a work in progress as opposed to misleading the customers into thinking the environments already existed.\n\nThe concepts and approaches outlined were lauded by the customers reviewing committees and were included in the initial contract. As a result of the contract award reviews, I was assigned the dual role of implementation at the program level of the processes, systems, and environments implied contractually and further approved as an enterprise approach internally to Boeing. Over the next several years, my team and I developed a number of processes, information models, data models, and proposed systems architectures. Although I had responsibility and accountability for the goals & objectives, executive management failed to come through with the authority required to implement.\n\nAs a lead systems engineer I tried to teach the program & leadership the requirements of a space-related system-of-systems architecture and what was needed for the technology proposals expected for the various aspects of this study contract. Unfortunately the majority of the staff had only ever been involved with commercial aircraft. Another impediment was the division president pitting four different programs against one another in the same arena. This situation was a drain on resources and caused great consternation and confusion with the customers. The program was eventually canceled due to lack of technical progress. Upon final review, the customers still wanted both my technical and management concepts but internal executive support was lacking.', u'title': u'Space Launch Initiative'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1993.10 ~ 1999.9', u'description': u'Manager initially, then Senior Manager of Engineering Technical Systems, Configuration Management, and Systems Engineering', u'title': u'International Space Station'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2001.1 ~ 2002.3', u'description': u'As a Staff Systems Engineer in Corporate Core Engineering, I was assigned to assist the Future Imaging Architecture team in Seal Beach CA in translating the systems engineering and program management requirements that were included in the final proposal to the government customer and subsequently imposed contractually into reality.\n\nMany of the methods and systems that were needed were very similar to what was being proposed for the Joint Strike Fighter program. (Many of these concepts were being included by most of the contractors vying for these large defense contracts and were expected to be included by the customers.)\n\nThe primary issue turned out to be that the infrastructure projects that were derived from these proposals were being run by \', u'title': u'Future Imaging Architecture'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1987.4 ~ 1990.7', u'description': u'Staff Engineer', u'title': u'Titan IV Launch Vehicle Fairing'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1999.9 ~ 2000.12', u'description': u'As a Staff Systems Engineer in Corporate Core Engineering, I was assigned to assist the Joint Strike Fighter team in Seattle in developing the systems engineering and program management requirements to be included in the final proposal to the government customer. This was a comprehensive proposal, outlining methodologies and systems which would've been a major leap forward in managing complex programs.\n\nAfter the proposal was complete, I was asked to help develop the processes and systems required to meet the proposed contract requirements. This task was very difficult in that most of the existing Boeing processes were heavily reliant on paper and manual work and most of the major systems were antiquated and not integrated.Boeing lost the contract award and the work was terminated at that time.', u'title': u'Joint Strike Fighter'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1987.4 ~ 1990.7', u'description': u'Staff Engineer', u'title': u'Delta II Launch Vehicle'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1990.7 ~ 1993.10', u'description': u'Manager of Engineering Technical Systems and most of Configuration Management.', u'title': u'Space Station  Freedom'}]

summary: Donald R Hill\nEnterprise Systems Engineer, Enterprise Architect & Problem Solver\nOrange County area, CA\n657.217.2075\ndonaldrhill56@gmail.com\n\nStrengthFinder® Talents: Ideation, Strategic, Responsibility, Context, Learner\n\nConnecting-the-Dots\n\nI solve operational problems for virtually any type of organization, be it commercial, government, or military. I use my systems engineering (SE) background to perform requirements development, root cause analysis, cause-and-effect analysis, business analysis, and operational analysis to understand what the true issues or opportunities are and the goals/objectives of the organization is trying to attain. I use storytelling as the primary means of conveying what I’ve heard and understand back to my customers, adjusting the story until we are in agreement.\n\nI can create new or reengineer existing systems (people, processes, tools) necessary to meet organizational goals and/or mission requirements. I use storytelling as the means to convey the requirements and expectations of the systems. This is also providing the basis that I use for training/mentoring the users.\n\nMy SE approach identifies all business, operational, and technical requirements and manages them jointly toward the development of a viable, cost-effective solution set. My requirements management technique incorporates risk/opportunity management, verification, and validation approaches and goals.\n\nOnce I engineer a viable, workable system, I can develop the Enterprise Architecture. I develop the information architecture needed to drive any new or upgraded applications. I extract this information through process analysis, analysis of existing data, and interviews with the subject matter experts, operational users, functional organizations and leadership. The goal is to define the information needs of all the stakeholders, establish precedence of their value-added activities, and engineer processes to take advantage of automation and information reuse.

summary: Find additional contact information at rkarmstrong.com.  \n\nI own a small consulting business, Epicural, LLC, that helps companies to streamline critical processes and solve hard problems.\n\nI am an elected At-Large member of the Board of Directors to the Society for Simulation in Healthcare. (www.ssih.org)\n\nCurrently, I perform three separate but related jobs at Eastern Virginia Medical School (EVMS).  \n\n1.  I am the Director of the Sentara Center for Simulation and Immersive Learning (SCSIL).  We use simulation to help develop mastery level skills for clinicians and healthcare providers. We also perform research into human and device based simulation, and develop tools to increase the value of simulation based learning.\n\n2.  I am Program Director of the National Center for Collaboration in Medical Modeling and Simulation.  This organization provides an opportunity for industry and universities to research and develop new medical M&S capabilities, and provides validation and verification services for emerging medical technologies and products.\n\n3.  I am also the Director of Corporate Relations for Eastern Virginia Medical School.  As Director, I lead efforts to translate our research and development intellectual property into commercial opportunities.  My focus is on outreach to academic and primarily industry/corporate collaborators and partners.\n\nI served as the 2010 Conference Chairman for the Modeling and Simulation World Conference and Expo (MODSIM World), held 13-15 October at the Hampton Roads Convention Center.\n\nI am on the Industry Board of Advisors to the Virginia Modeling, Analysis and Simulation Center at Old Dominion University.
