projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2005.1 ~ 2013.1', u'description': u'Crossing four employers and more than five customer engagements, with dozens of Federal Agencies and companies involved. I spent about 8 years of my life working to find and promote technologies to improve counter-terrorism and natural disaster response with a diverse set of other folks.  This personal project is ending with our group thesis from National University (Chuck Frawley, Paul Agosta).  Tihis was also the subject of two practicum courses at FEAC Institute (Amy El-Naggar, Rob Abbott, Jeff LaRue, Mike Foresman). At this point there are over a dozen projects and programs at DHS to support civilian situation awareness and C2, and we have succeeded.  This unofficial project had some support at very high levels in government, and was thought very important to the country by several folks not listed anywhere (and the top leaders not listed here either).  Many more persons were involved.   Some not in the linked in \', u'title': u'Civilian Command and Control for Counter-Terrorism & Natural Disaster'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006 ~ 2007', u'description': u'Enterprise architecture support to total asset visibility system of FEMA.  This is a large geospatial system that tracks the position of goods delivered to disaster areas using GPS.\n\nThis system uses Manhattan logistics software, geospatial software from GeoDecisions, and orbiting satellites that receive updates from battery powered GPS systems that transmit coordinates on an adjustable schedule.', u'title': u'FEMA TAV (Total Asset Visibility) Architecture'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2007 ~ 2007', u'description': u'Developed FEMA FNARS architecture documentation using DODAF.  About FNARS, but not this project:  Marty ran this for the Government.  FNARS is a huge radio network (\', u'title': u'FNARS FEMA National Radio System Architecture'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009 ~ 2011', u'description': u'Supported attempts to establish shared situation awareness between NYPD/CTD and the regional partners, Federal government.  Susan managed this for the Federal Government.', u'title': u'\'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2005 ~ 2011', u'description': u'Development of system and architecture (DODAF) to connect RN sensors to multiple operations centers and thwart the illegal movement, storage or use of RN material.  Lots of sensors and detectors involved.  This is a massive SOA of a sort, with real-time messaging.\n\nEventually the project was contracted to a new government lead and prime, and died a slow death.', u'title': u'DHS DNDO MCM Mission Critical Messaging Architecture'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006 ~ 2011', u'description': u' Software system supporting the adjudication of nuclear spectra for determination of threat status.  JACCIS used Agile & Scrum, HP blades, Linux, Apache, JBOSS, Mule, LifeRay, and a ton of cool custom Java code from SPAWAR East.\n\nThis system was actually a failure of enterprise architecture to convince management of improved alignment.  For several years I and Jack Bryan (Chief System Engineer for JACCIS) pointed out that this system should be devoted to situation awareness, not adjudication of spectra.  (Vayl Oxford had originally said that when a detector anunciated he wanted a light to go on in the analysis center.)   The users were people who adjudicated spectra and ultimately Agile automated what the users wanted.  Unfortunately that was a redundant function performed by 3 other agencies in government and DNDO did not need to replicate it.  In the end that function was eliminated.', u'title': u'JACCIS  Joint Analysis Center Collaborative Information System, System Engineering, Governance'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006 ~ 2007', u'description': u'Initial architecture of Integrated Public Alert and Warnings System produced with DODAF.  Today this is a huge SOA system in operation to warn the public of disaster using a central ORACLE ESB.  Originally it was going to use  a distributed grid of SNL SPOR routers, that did not seem to work in practice.  Either way it is a huge SOA distributed system, and it includes embedded equipment at the radio or TV station. ', u'title': u'IPAWS  Integrated Public Alerts and Warnings Architecture'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006 ~ 2011', u'description': u'Advanced Spectroscopic Portal, sensor system for acquiring nuclear spectra.  $3/4 billion.  Cool He3 neutron detectors and solid state crystal gamma detectors were used with multiple embedded controllers.  This system had improved sensitivity and the ability to capture Gamma Ray spectra, which the CBP RPM did not have.\n\nUnfortunately the main customer, CBP, had business processes at the ports of entry that could not benefit from improved sensitivity or spectra.  Primary inspection (nuclear detection) takes place in the queue of vehicles crossing the port, and any detection at all suspect is sent to secondary inspection, which is not busy and delays are unimportant for those few vehicles. Today the ASP is only used in secondary inspection, where the ability to take spectra and increased sensitivity are of benefit.', u'title': u'ASP  Advanced Spectroscopic Portal (nuclear detector), System Engineering, Governance'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1974.6 ~ now', u'description': u'I began teaching myself computer science in 1974, when I received the issue of Popular Electronics describing the first personal computer.  Later I read every episode of Byte Magazine cover to cover.  I read shelves full of books on programming, object oriented programming, programming languages, processor architectures, algorithms and operating systems.  I read books on databases, agents, CORBA, .Net and more.  I taught myself Basic on a superminicomputer in 1979, and every version of Visual Basic thereafter.  I wrote small programs in various languages to try them.  \n\nThe first computer I ever loaded a program into was the processor of an AN/ALR 46 Airborne Warning Receiver in  1978 in the USAF.  The first computer i repaired extensively was a 1964 CDC 3200 supercomputer used by the SR-71 program.  I taught myself BASIC on a Gould SEL 32/55 bit-slice super-minicomputer in 1979.  The first computer I built myself, with a soldering iron, was a Z-80 CP/M system in 1980, which I embedded in my Z-19 terminal.  I rewrote MDM-740, in assembler, for that system.  I later designed 3 Z-80 controller boards and an 86C188 (and modem, power supply, etc) controller at Arbitron.  And so on...\n\nPeople have asked why I did not get a second degree in Comp-Sci:  I have already covered the material.  They have asked why I do not program in Java:  it is an inefficient language with complex directory structures that annoys me.  They have asked why I do not program for a living:  Managing technology usually pays better.', u'title': u'Self Education in Computer Science'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.9 ~ 2013.3', u'description': u'In 2011 Vivek Kundra left OMB claiming widespread corruption in US Government Information Technology.  Enterprise architecture was conceived in 1989 to form an independent basis for IT portfolio management decisions in the United States Government, and to guide implementation.  The question arose as to if Kundra's accusations applied to my portion of the IT Industry.  Whet were practices and factors that could interfere with the accomplishment of the mission of enterprise architecture set forth by OMB?  I undertook to look around and see what I could find after some discussion with senior architects.  I will produce a brief report for narrow distribution to government managers and academics in early 2013.  No specific persons or companies will be named or implicated, only questionable practices, factors and other non-identifying information.', u'title': u'Preliminary Independent Investigation into Corruption in Enterprise Architecture'}]

summary: 25 years of professional experience in the areas of satellite communications, antenna designs, hardware delivery, business development, customer interactions, proposal writing, sub-contract management, technical management etc. Made significant contributions to mobile, fixed satellite service, and personal communications payloads for more than 25 satellite programs. Seasoned professional with progressive responsibility in engineering design, project management, and business development. Worked with Lockheed Martin Space Systems, Boeing Satellite Systems, L-3  and MDA Space in Canada. Professional experiences cover the whole spectrum of satellite antennas from software simulation, numerical analysis, hardware components, sub-system development, to the design and build of very complex satellite antenna systems such as C&Ku-band FSS/BSS antennas, L & S-band antenna, Ka-band as well as EHF antennas. Travelled around the world for the technical related issues both for the satellite operators as well as for the satellite manufacturers. Technical expertise include antenna systems, multiple beam antenna (MBA), shaped beam antenna, reflector antenna, cup dipole antenna, horns, beam forming networks, (high-level/low-level), hybrid matrix networks, Rotman lens beamformer, T&C antenna, DRA phased array antenna, reconfigurable antenna, microstrip arrays, low PIM & high power antenna design/test, spacecraft antenna integration and test. Recipient of numerous awards from  Boeing and Lockheed at corporate level for technical excellence and innovations. Holder of 5 US patents for innovative satellite antenna design, and published  20 technical papers in technical journals and IEEE-APS Symposium.

summary: Dr. Tolk is Technology Integrator for the Modeling, Simulation, Experimentation, and Analytics (MSEA) Tech Center of The MITRE Corporation in Hampton, VA. He is an adjunct Professor at Old Dominion University.\n\nDr. Tolk was Chief Scientist at SimIS Inc. in Portsmouth, Virginia between 2013 and 2015, where has been responsible for the evaluation of emerging M&S technologies. He was also supporting key projects with systems engineering expertise.\n\nDr. Tolk has been a faculty member (Professor) in the Department of Engineering Management and Systems Engineering at the Old Dominion University from 2006 to 2013. He held a joint appointment with the Modeling, Simulation, and Visualization Engineering department. He received his Ph.D. in Computer Science (1995) and has a M.S. in Computer Science (1988) from the University of the Federal Armed Forces, Germany. His emphasis was Applied Systems Science and Military Operations Research.\n\nDr. Tolk was Senior Research Scientist at the Virginia Modeling Analysis & Simulation Center (VMASC) from 2002 to 2006. He was Vice President for Land Weapon Systems at the German company I.A.B.G., the main contractor for the German Ministry of Defense for Operations Research and Simulation applications for analyses, training, and experimentation, from 1998 to 2002. He was project manager for decision support systems and integration of M&S into Command and Control systems from 1995 to 1998.\n\nHe received the Excellence in Research award from the Frank Batten College of Engineering and Technology in 2008, first Technical Merit Award of the Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization (SISO) in 2010, the Outstanding Professional Contribution award of the Society for Modeling and Simulation (SCS) in 2012, and the Distinguished Professional Achievements Award of SCS in 2014. He was recognized as a Fellow of SCS in April 2016.\n\nDr. Tolk is senior member of ACM, IEEE and SCS.

Marion Leboyer, director of the Foundation FondaMental, and Dr. Fran\xe7ois Iris, scientific director of Bio-Modeling Systems.', u'title': u'PSYCHIATRIC IMMUNO-INFLAMMATORY RESEARCH PROGRAM'}]

summary: Lost time can never be replaced. \n\nMy professional goal is to significantly reduce the time it takes to successfully create complex systems like automobiles and heavy duty vehicles. By creating system models and developing repeatable methods, the productivity of a development team is improved. Automation and optimization reduces costs, reduces errors and produces consistent results. Improved productivity enables a development team to focus on building the right system the first time. I help create methods and tools to enable this kind of work.\n\nMy primary focus is the development of methods and tools to synthesize mechatronic systems: systems consisting of mechanical, electrical, chemical, thermal, and software components.\n\nI have successfully applied my work to automotive powertrains, high precision manufacturing systems, batteries, inverters, man-machine interfaces, power transmission systems, and multi-agent systems.\n\nSpecialties: \n• systems engineering\n• design optimization\n• model development\n• dynamic optimization\n• optimal control\n• signal processing & state estimation\n• real-time & embedded software\n• data mining

I have written sections of the initial SysML specification and I am still active in the ongoing work on SysML. I am involved in many MBSE activities and you can meet me at several conferences about MBSE and related topics.\n\nAs a consultant, I have advised many companies in different domains. The insights into their challenges are one source of my experience that I share in my books and presentations. I have written many books about modeling including Systems Engineering with SysML (Morgan Kaufmann, 2008) and Model-Based System Architecture (Wiley, 2015). I am the editor of the pragmatic and independent MBSE methodology SYSMOD – the Systems Modeling Toolbox and VAMOS - Variant Modeling with SysML. Both are published in books by MBSE4U.\n\nYou can contact me at tim@weilkiens.de and read my blog about MBSE at www.model-based-systems-engineering.com.\n\nSpecialties: Model-Based Systems Engineering, Engineering Processes, UML, SysML, Functional Architectures, Variant Modeling, SYSMOD, VAMOS, Agile Systems Engineering

I have pursued my Masters degree in Mechanical Engineering (controls) and have over 11 years of experience in areas of control system, algorithms, mathematical modeling, systems simulation, reliability & data analytics in Energy and Aerospace industry. I am very passionate about solving complex industrial and business problems through the application of data analytics and machine learning. Core to our success was also Saffron Technology's IP. summary: Now is the time to understand more, so we fear less.  \n- Marie Curie (7 November 1867 – 4 July 1934) \n\nThings in the world are getting more complex. And it means that eastern and western, developed market and emerging market perspectives are needed. \n\nHolding executive or operational roles, my career has been about building competency, expertise and relationships across multiple:\n\n-\tDisciplines (i.e. engineering, sales, software development, management, systems thinking) \n-\tIndustries (i.e. healthcare, pharma, telecom, oil & gas, transportation, agriculture)\n-\tNations (i.e. Asia and North America)\n\nI like asking the hard questions. And I value partnerships as a source of understanding and innovation.\n\nI am now building a team to understand human behavior in the context of our health and emerging markets. summary: As a senior decision support and risk advisor, I provide guidance, deep insights, and valuable solutions for senior decision-makers facing complex, high-risk problems related to\n    • strategic planning\n    • risk analysis and management\n    • project finance, valuation, and planning\n    • project portfolio analysis & management.\n\nOver my twenty-one-year career, I have provided solutions to my clients’ complex problems by employing creative thinking and advanced quantitative, business, engineering, systems analysis, and training.  My experience spans diverse industrial and commercial fields including energy, utilities, logistics & transportation, pharmaceuticals, electronics manufacturing, telecommunications, IT, and commercial real estate.\n\nI aim to introduce and develop within client organizations the guidance, processes, and systems that improve the firm's ability to anticipate and manage risks and capture upside value associated with strategic planning, capital allocation, and project selection & management.\n\nSpecialties: I provide facilitation of problem framing, advanced quantitative modeling for decision support & risk analysis, portfolio analysis & management, strategic planning, systems engineering. Other notable skills include simulation programming with Analytica and R.

summary: As a Biomechanical Engineer/Scientist and Project Manager I strive to apply my expertise in biomechanics and bioengineering and strong project management skills to drive innovative solutions to challenging biomedical problems.\n\nI am the Principal Investigator for programs on physical performance and musculoskeletal injury with applications to operational performance, training injury predictions, and head supported mass. I have a knack for seeing the big picture and being able to deliver a unique research solution across a diverse range of research programs. It's incredibly rewarding to do research that directly benefits our Service Members.\n \nI've provided technical leadership for a number of projects including\n- Physical performance models developing physiology and musculoskeletal biomechanics models to predict muscle fatigue and energetics and physiologic response\n- Development of software to reconstruct 3D dummy kinematics from sensors\n- Modeling blast lung injury injury including the effects of body armor\n- Modeling hearing loss from blast events\n\nBefore joining L-3/ATI, I earned my PhD at the University of Utah. My dissertation focused on modeling and simulation studies to determine the muscle contributions for fatigue-resistant sit-to-stand transitions in spinal cord injury (SCI) patients and to develop a framework for future modeling studies to restore unaided gait after SCIs. \n\nI’m passionate about my work and always eager to connect with other researchers. While I enjoy all aspects of my job, my favorite part is working with a team of highly motivated researchers with diverse areas of expertise to solve really interesting problems. I enjoy working with individuals to leverage their expertise and skills to deliver a high quality research product to the customer. I’m also studying for the PMP exam having satisfied the PDU requirement.\n\nSkills: Modeling/Simulation, Biomechanics, Physiology, Technical Leadership, Project Management, Proposal & Technical Writing

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2014.2', u'description': u'The project involved using ETAS HIL, LABCAR EE, LABCAR IP, INCA, Test handler, MATLAB, SIMULINK, and Vector CANalyzer, for testing and validation of engine controls. The work involved creating DVPRs,  automated test scripts and manually testing the software on the HIL.\nDocuments were backed up in TFS.', u'title': u'Testing and Validation of Engine Controls Software (Bosch/Continental)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ 2013.3', u'description': u'The project involved development of hybrid Powertrain and its controls on construction equipment. The project involved using Dynasty for the machine hydraulic and mechanical systems modeling, Matlab/Simulink interface with Dynasty for the machine controls, and Python interface with Dynasty for iteration of data through excel for Design of Experiments, and statistical analysis of the simulation results and comparison with machine data from DATK.', u'title': u'Real Time Energy Management Control Strategies for Hybrid Powertrains'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2004.9 ~ 2005.6', u'description': u'The project involved manufacturing and testing a thrust magnetic bearing to complete a test rig consisting of 2 axial magnetic bearing and 1 thrust magnetic bearing and developing and testing a control algorithm for the rig which was done in Matlab and in C code.', u'title': u'Completion and Analysis of a magnetic bearing test rig.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2005.9 ~ 2009.7', u'description': u'The purpose of this project was to study the effect of joints flexibility on spatial robot dynamics and the determination of the flexibility coefficients of the new developed model. The project involved using Matlab/Simulink, Data Acquisition, Uni-graphics UGS NX4, AutoCAD, developing the electronic controls, robot and circuits manufacturing.', u'title': u'Modeling and Simulation of Joints Flexibility Effect on the Dynamic Performance of Spatial Robots'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.8 ~ 2010.7', u'description': u'General computational multibody system (MBS) algorithms allow for the linearization of\nthe highly nonlinear equations of motion at different points in time in order to obtain the\neigenvalue solution. This eigenvalue solution of the linearized equations is often used to\nshed light on the system stability at different configurations that correspond to different\ntime points. Different MBS algorithms, however, employ different sets of orientation\ncoordinates, such as Euler angles and Euler parameters, which lead to different forms of the\ndynamic equations of motion. As a consequence, the forms of the linearized equations and\nthe eigenvalue solution obtained strongly depend on the set of orientation coordinates\nused. This paper addresses this fundamental issue by examining the effect of the use of\ndifferent orientation parameters on the linearized equations of a gyroscope. The nonlinear\nequations of motion of the gyroscope are formulated using two different sets of orientation\nparameters: Euler angles and Euler parameters. In order to obtain a set of linearized\nequations that can be used to define the eigenvalue solution, the algebraic equations that\ndescribe the MBS constraints are systematically eliminated leading to a nonlinear form of\nthe equations of motion expressed in terms of the system degrees of freedom. Because in\nMBS applications the generalized forces can be highly nonlinear and can depend on the\nvelocities, a state space formulation is used to solve the eigenvalue problem. It is shown in\nthis paper that the independent state equations formulated using Euler angles and Euler\nparameters lead to different eigenvalue solutions. This solution is also different from the\nsolution obtained using a form of the Newton\u2013Euler matrix equation expressed in terms of\nthe angular accelerations and angular velocities.  It is shown that such an eigenvalue analysis can lead to wrong conclusions regarding the stability of nonlinear systems.', u'title': u'Study of nonlinear system stability using eigenvalue analysis: Gyroscopic motion'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.12 ~ 2012.7', u'description': u'The project involved development of Powertrain controls and testing them. The project involved virtual prototyping / MIL / SIL / HIL,  Model Based control design and simulations, control algorithms design, working with version controlled software and using Matlab/Simulink/Stateflow, dSPACE TargetLink, ControlDesk, Vector CANalyzer, and C codes. Contributions to the project were developing Calibration algorithm, Fault diagnostics, and non-powertrain hydraulics controls.', u'title': u'Powertrain Controls Development'}]

summary: Continuous improvement, exploration and contribution to modern advancements in automotive systems is a lifelong goal of mine. I acquired my BS in Mechanical and Industrial engineering from Cairo University and attained thesis based MSc in Multibody dynamics and robotics. I was granted my PhD from the University of Illinois at Chicago in Mechatronics and controls with focus on hybrid commercial vehicle torque management controls for maximizing fuel economy and emission reduction. \nI have 7 years collectively in industry majorly in the automotive field around product development life cycle. My work ranges from requirements development and analysis, DFMEA, physical modeling, controls and software development, integration, calibration, verification and validation.\nI have worked as part of teams and managed teams and resources.

summary: Keynote Speaking, Public Speaking, Executive Training, Leadership Training, and Advising on: Analytics, Automation, Artificial Intelligence, Big Data Strategies, Data Monetization, Digital Strategies, Risk Management, Data Science, Innovation, Negotiations, Business Development, Credit Risk, Enterprise Risk Management (ERM), Operational Risk, Credit Cards, Banking & FinTech\nwww.russellwalkerphd.com\n@RussWalker1492\nbigdatatobigprofits.com\nConnect with me  ► rw31@cornell.edu ◄\n\nProfessor\nRussell Walker, Ph.D. is Clinical Professor of Managerial Economics and Decision Sciences at the Kellogg School of Management, Northwestern University. Russell teaches courses in the application of Analytics, Risk Management, and Global Business Strategy. These courses include: the Analytical Consulting Lab, Enterprise Risk Management, the Risk Lab, Strategic Data-Driven Marketing, Global Leadership, and Global Lab. \n\nAuthor\nRussell Walker is the author of From Big Data to Big Profits: Success with Data and Analytics (2015), Winning with Risk Management (2013), Operational Risk in the Insurance Industry (2013), a chapter in Risk Management in Financial Institutions, and 60+ business cases.\n\nDigital, Big Data & Analytics\nRussell served as a corporate strategist at Capital One Financial, where he led research on new analytical techniques. He teaches is the Northwestern University Masters of Science in Analytics and advises firms on developing analytical capabilities and leveraging Big Data in the digital age.\n\nRisk Management\nRussell founded and led the Kellogg Complete Course in Risk Management for Executives along with additional executive education programs in Enterprise Risk Management, Operational Risk Management, and Managing Regulation, Reputation and Risk.\n\nGlobal Strategy\nDr. Walker has led the Kellogg courses on international business in Latin America and the Gulf States. He has directed comprehensive studies on Medical Tourism for Turkey and Tourism Transformation for Mexico.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'Used design thinking methods from the d.school to help develop a plan for Exxon Mobile to showcase its huge tech side to tech students and recent graduates to promote itself as an innovative and big developer of tech solutions. We came up with effective ways the solution can be implemented and scaled to Exxon Mobile recruiting locations all over the world. We used readily available tools to come up with ways recruiters can interact with potential candidates and help the recent graduates with the transition to full time work as a proud Exxon employee.', u'title': u'On-boarding Tech Employees in a traditionally non Tech company'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2014.6', u'description': u'Collaborated with New Business Development Innovation team within Panasonic Corp. to develop a working prototype of a new product to address senior health care within 9 months. This involved many iterations of need-finding, concept ideation, prototyping, user-testing, and benchmarking. The team developed prototypes for caregivers to transport immobile seniors from their bed to the shower/bathroom and gamification of process to help seniors adhere to their medical pills. The final product and prototype was designed to help seniors with depression and anxiety in senior care facilities, using memory therapy techniques. ', u'title': u'ME310: Product-Based Engineering Design, Innovation, and Development'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.1 ~ 2014.3', u'description': u'\xbb Worked in a team of four to develop quantitative models of combustion, gasification, liquefaction, and electro-chemical systems.\n\xbb Developed models using Matlab and Cantera.\n\xbb Systems modeled include gas and steam combined cycles, boilers, autothermal fuel reformers (coal and biomass), distillation columns, and SOFC fuel cells.', u'title': u'ME 370B Energy Systems II: Modeling and Advanced Concepts'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'The study looked at the actual price the homeowners are paying for electricity from their solar panels in California. The analysis included the efficiency of panels, the amount of sunlight, subsidy received from the government while also looking at the electricity rate structure for homes. A further study was done on the inclusion of net metering and current feed-in tariff rate. The study also looked into how the actual value received by solar installers is underestimated as it overlooks infrastructure cost and distribution cost that over subsidizes solar installations. We looked at getting the optimal feed-in tariff rates to replace the net metering system and include the factors over looked by net metering and how this would impact the growth of solar installations in California. The study also analyzed the distributional consequence of solar subsidy and how that would be eased due to optimization of the feed in tariff.', u'title': u'Optimal Residential Solar PV Feed-In Tariff in California (a Study)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.1 ~ 2014.6', u'description': u'\xbb Researched and modeled a 100-200kW SOFC/MGT system using electro-chemical, heat, and mass transport principles.\n\xbb Reviewed scientific literature that would provide explanation to design and equations to be used in modeling\n\xbb Used Cantera and MATLAB to model the system and optimized for maximum exergy efficiency.\n\xbb Implementation of optimization function for system performance rather than component performance\n\xbb Inclusion of GUI to facilitate parameter tweaks while preventing fixed design parameters from accidental modifications\n', u'title': u'ME 370C: Modeling and Simulation of Triple Cycle in Solid Oxide Fuel Cell-Micro Gas Turbine Hybrid Cycle (SOFC/MGT) for Optimum System Performance'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.2 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Developed a model that looked at deployment of Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion (OTEC) systems to reduce the coal powered plants in the United States. MARKAL was used to do the economic modelling using a general equilibrium model. The operational details of OTEC was modeled into MARKAL along with its economic performance characteristics. The modelling also looked at how increasing Carbon cost on electricity generation over the next 50 years can improve the prospects of OTEC, a renewable energy source and reduce the Carbon-dioxide emissions into the atmosphere. ', u'title': u'Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion (OTEC) deployment: Modelling with MARKAL'}]

summary: • Modeling and simulation scientist in the areas of PK/PD and QSP (Quantitative Systems Pharmacology) in pre-clinical and clinical development.\n\n• Expertise in designing and implementing preclinical PK/PD models, mechanistic PK/PD models, Physiologically-based PK models, QSP models, multi-scale computational models in support of pre-clinical and clinical development projects.\n\n• Ph.D. degree in Chemical Engineering and academic/industrial postdoctoral experience in computational systems biology in immune systems and QSP modeling in human blood coagulation to guide efficacious human dose selection. \n\n• Specialties: Mechanistic PK/PD modeling, quantitative systems pharmacology modeling, biological modeling, cellular bioengineering, computational systems biology, fluid mechanics, quantitative cellular assay, immunology, hemostasis/thrombosis, bio-rheology.\n\n• Proven success as an influential member in multidisciplinary teams; Peer-reviewed publications and external presentations.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2010 ~ 2013', u'description': u'1) Developed a prototype of portable and reconfigurable solar PV charger for meeting various load request, including 2.5V NiMH battery, 5V USB load, and 12V lead-acid battery;\n2) Developed a prototype of a dc-dc converter to reconfigure PV sub-modules under high-switching frequency;\n3) Built a multi-level 3-phase inverter based on the dynamic reconfiguration of PV modules distributed in the switch matrix.', u'title': u'Solar Photovoltaic Arrays Dynamical Reconfiguration'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008 ~ 2009', u'description': u'1) Modeled, simulated and studied the switching transient of shunt capacitors in the IEEE 14-bus transmission systems using the ATP (Alternative Transient Program), including various power system components, such as generators, synchronous condensers, transmission lines, transformers, capacitor banks, circuit breakers and loads.\n2) Modeled and simulated four types of faults in the IEEE 14-bus power systems, with both grounded and ungrounded wye-connected transformer windings. Faults include single-line ground fault, double-line ground fault, line-to-line fault and 3-phase-to-ground fault. Fault scenarios in different groundings are compared and analyzed using sequence networks.', u'title': u'Modeling and Simulation of Faults in Power System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008.10 ~ now', u'description': u'1) Modeled, simulated and implemented various types of fault experiments in a commercial-scale 35kW grid-connected solar PV systems;\n2) Analyzed the unique fault transient behavior and post-fault steady-state for PV systems;\n3) Developed new fault detection and classification algorithms for PV systems using machine learning and outlier detection rules;\n4) Built a DC-arc generator in PV arrays, and developed fault detection algorithms in time and frequency domain;\n5) Developed and integrated a graphical user interface (GUI) to a commercial PV monitoring system for end users, including the developed fault detection algorithms.', u'title': u'Fault Analysis, Detection, Classification and Protection in Solar Photovoltaic (PV) Systems'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.5 ~ now', u'description': u'1) Modeled and simulated the boost converters for PV voltage regulation;\n2) Developed average-current mode control of boost converters;\n3) Developed the Maximum Power Point Tracking (MPPT) algorithms;\n4) Developed a digitally-controlled prototype.', u'title': u'Interleaved DC-DC Boost Converter for Solar PV Modules'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010 ~ 2010', u'description': u'1) Designed the measurement and RTU placement in the IEEE 39-bus system,\nwhich made the system observable under various cases, such as the base case, single RTU failure, and several pre-selected outages.\n2) Developed the algorithm for cost optimization of measurements and RTUs.', u'title': u'Power System State Estimation'}]

summary: I am a creative researcher, a hands-on engineer and a self-motivated team player.\n\nMy research experiences mainly focus on increasing the reliability, safety and efficiency of both grid-connected and stand-alone solar photovoltaic (PV) systems using power electronics and control techniques, machine learning approaches and outlier detection rules. \n\nThrough the interdisciplinary research, I have gained the skills in brainstorming, discovering “blind spots” in existing solutions, exploring new ideas, prototyping and developing commercial products.\n\nDuring my research projects and class projects, I have had the privileged opportunity to work in a wide range of fields in electrical and computer engineering, including 1) Power Electronics--modeling and control of dc-dc power converters, digitally controlled power converters, 2) Power Systems--modeling, simulation and power flow analysis, post-fault steady-state analysis, transient analysis, and state estimation; 3) Modeling and control of electric drives; 4) Computer Engineering--machine learning, data mining, outlier detection rules and data analysis.\n\nI have won Best Student Presentation Awards twice in IEEE conferences. I have filed one US patent application about PV string monitoring systems. \n\nI am the author of three IEEE peer-reviewed journals, and have published 10 IEEE conference papers in Power Electronics and Photovoltaics. \n\nI had 3 years of industrial experience as a sales/technical support engineer in ABB high-voltage switchgear, China. \n\nI have hands-on experience in 500V dc solar PV field. I helped design, implemented and analyzed various faults including dc-arcs in a 35kW PV laboratory in Saint-Bonnet, France. \n\nTECHNICAL SKILLS\n> Simulation: MATLAB/Simulink, ATP-EMTP, Multisim, Pspice, Foundation, PVSYST, SIMetrix, PLCES\n> Prototyping: Microchip’s and TI’s MCUs, Zigbee, Altium Designer for PCB, LabVIEW, PLC, dSPACE\n> Programming: MATLAB, C, C++, assembly, FPGA with VHDL, ladder logic diagram

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2005.11 ~ 2005.11', u'description': u'Developed advanced thermal model of gas turbine engine rear sump using in-house proprietary modeling tools and UG-NX CAD model.  Applied convective cooling boundary conditions and radiation heat transfer using customized correlations and advanced cooling methods.  Performed both 2D and 3D analysis for steady state and transient for a wide range of flight conditions based on engine cycle data.  Modeled high speed air bearing thermal response.  Provided thermal results to stress engineer for component stress and thermal growth calculations.', u'title': u'Gas Turbine Engine Thermal Model'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006.3 ~ 2006.3', u'description': u'Developed 2D axis-symmetric FLUENT CFD models to predict air flow patterns and swirl velocity in high speed compressor rotors.  Used boundary layer meshing with k-omega SST turbulence model for 5 stage compressor.  Model was developed from UG model cross section and meshed using Gambit.  Results were utilized to improve compressor rotor heat transfer and secondary flow model accuracy.', u'title': u'Prediction of Fluid Swirl using Axis-Symmetric CFD Model'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.7 ~ 2012.7', u'description': u'Development of 20 million element CFD model using ANSYS Fluent 13.0, to predict thermal profile of Advanced Nuclear Waste Treatment processing system using molten glass storage method.  Model included combined liquid and gas fluid domains, conjugate heat transfer, laminar and turbulent flow, and radiation using Discrete Ordinate Model.  The model was developed by importing Solid Works geometry into ANSYS Workbench and meshing using hybrid CFD Tetra method and multi-core parallel processing.   ', u'title': u'Low Acivity Waste LID Thermal Profile'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008.2 ~ 2008.2', u'description': u'Developed 2D axis-symmetric thermal models of compressor case for military engines.  Used ANSYS thermal and in-house proprietary modeling tools to predict compressor case thermal transient response for a range of flight conditions.  Correlated thermal predictions with test results from three different engines and used results to predict blade tip clearances.', u'title': u'Compressor Case Thermal Model'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.8 ~ 2011.8', u'description': u'Developed large complex thermal model of computer chassis using ANSYS Icepak to model temperature profile inside of computer cabinet.  Model included cooling fans, multi level circuit boards with CPU's, DIMMS, grilles, power supplies, heat sinks and flow baffles.  Model was developed by using native Icepak objects and PRO-E CAD geometry.  Model was used to predict internal flow patterns, to size cooling fans and heat sinks and to optimize the location of electronic components for optimum cooling.  Parallel processing was performed for 5 million element models.', u'title': u'Development of CFD Model for Computer Thermal Management'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2001.11 ~ 2001.11', u'description': u'Starting from conceptual design, developed coupled 2D-3D high pressure rotor heat transfer model.  Model was developed from native UG geometry engine cross section and imported in PATRAN P-Thermal for meshing and applying loads and boundary conditions.  The thermal model was coupled to the YFT secondary flow model through convective boundary conditions.  The model included several innovative features including combined axis-symmetric 2D ad 3D geometry using a sector method, 3D surface to surface radiation, and 2D axis-symmetric turbine blade model correlated to aero-thermal model temperature predictions. ', u'title': u'Turbine Rotor Heat Transfer Model'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2005.1 ~ 2005.1', u'description': u'Developed FLUENT model of gas turbine engine combustion process with combined gaseous and liquid fuel injection, using discrete phase injection and Finite Rate Eddy Dissipation Model.  Liquid droplet injection incorporated droplet size distribution using Rosin-Rammler method.  Model was developed using Pro-E geometry model and Gambit meshing tool.  Model was used to predict thermal mixing and fuel air distribution.', u'title': u'Modeling of Gas Turbine Combustor with Super Critical Fuel Injection'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ 2011.2', u'description': u'Development of thermal model using SINDA to predict electro-mechanical actuator transient thermal response during space mission.  Model was developed by importing UG-NX geometry into MSC Patran and meshing and applying loads and boundary conditions.  Model included radiation and simulated thermostatically controlled heaters with time varying actuator heat loads.  Model included motor windings, bearings, gears, rotating shafts, and thermal contact.  Five different actuator models were developed and models were correlated with experimental data.', u'title': u'Electro-Mechanical Actuator Thermal Profile'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.1 ~ 2013.1', u'description': u'Developed CFD models of large nuclear waste tank using FLUENT.  Meshing of 15-20 million fluid cell models using boundary layer method and advanced turbulence modeling techniques such as k-omega SST and enhanced wall treatment.  Used mass transfer with turbulent diffusion.  Used CFD model to size nozzles and predict jet mixing.  Generated final reports for customer approval.', u'title': u'Tank Mixing CFD Models'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1998.3 ~ 1998.3', u'description': u'Utilized advanced CFD modeling tools to develop thermal models to predict operating temperatures of automotive lighting products.  Models included combined specular radiation and natural convection using state of the art ray tracing method in ADINA-F software code.  Model was developed using UG, MSC Patran and Adina-F.  Results were correlated with test data and used for design optimization and virtual prototyping.', u'title': u'Development of Automotive Lighting Thermal Model'}]

summary: Dr. Saurabh Mittal  is Lead Systems Engineer/Scientist in the Architecture Analytics Department at the MITRE Corporation in McLean, VA. He is also affiliated with Dunip Technologies, LLC, Society of Modeling and Simulation International (SCS), USA and Enterprise Architecture Body of Knowledge (EABOK) Consortium. \n\nHe is an elected member of the Board of Directors, SCS and serving a 3-year term. \n\nHe has extensive experience in modeling and simulation-based systems engineering, complex adaptive systems thinking, formal systems M&S using DEVS and leading associated research endeavors. He has contributed to M&S efforts at National Renewable Energy Lab, Department of Energy, Colorado; Link Simulation & Training at Wright Patterson Air Force Base, Dayton, Ohio; Northrop Grumman Information Technology at  Defense Information Systems Agency, Ft. Huachuca, Arizona and at the University of Arizona, Tucson.  \n\nDr. Mittal served as General Chair, Vice General Chair, Program Chair and Track Chair for Spring, Summer and Winter Simulation Multi-conferences over 2013-2017 period and continues to stay involved as Track Chair and Steering Committee member.\n\nDr. Mittal received his Ph.D. (2007) in Electrical and Computer Engineering (ECE), with dual minors in Management Information Systems, and Systems and Industrial Engineering, and has M.S. (2003) in ECE from the University of Arizona, Tucson. \n\nDr. Mittal has contributed over 70 peer-reviewed articles and two books titled: Guide to Simulation-based Disciplines: Advancing our computational future (2017) and Netcentric System of Systems Engineering with DEVS Unified Process (2013). He is a recipient of Outstanding Professional Contribution Award (2017) and Outstanding Service Award (2016) by SCS. He also received the highest civilian Department of Defense (DoD) contractor recognition “Golden Eagle” Award (2006) and Herculean Effort Leadership Award from the University of Arizona (2004).

summary: After graduating with a Professional Science Master's degree in Applied Physics, I worked at DISTek Integration as a Test Engineer for approximately five years. While I was with DISTek, I applied my knowledge of physics and mathematics to the engineering of test systems and LabVIEW software for various customers. I became a National Instruments Certified LabVIEW Architect (the highest level of LabVIEW certification) and taught LabVIEW courses as a Certified Professional Instructor. As my engineering skills matured, I became more involved in the design and development of advanced Hardware-in-the-Loop (HIL) simulators for autonomous, off-highway vehicles and vehicle systems using VeriStand on Real-Time (RT) controllers and Field-Programmable Gate Arrays (FPGAs).\n\nUpon moving to Virginia, I became an independent contractor providing engineering services. In addition to remotely collaborating with customers to manage and develop some technically and financially successful test and simulation projects, I have began applying my scientific background more directly by assisting in the development of physics-based plant models and control models for vehicles using MATLAB and Simulink.\n\nI've recently returned to DISTek as the founder and leader of DISTek’s Integrated Projects Engineering (IPE) team. This team was conceived with the goal of more fully integrating DISTek’s engineers across disciplines and accelerating our ability to pursue new fields and concepts. The IPE team is comprised of motivated engineers that have each established themselves as an expert in at least one of DISTek’s core disciplines in the off-highway vehicle industry (embedded software, test and automation, or modeling and simulation) through years of experience completing successful projects. The team has established an environment where these individuals can work together in a challenging atmosphere to learn from each other and explore innovative approaches to our business.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ now', u'description': u'Mammalian genomes contain over 700 zinc finger proteins (ZFPs), but most have unknown functions. One example, PR Domain Containing 9 (PRDM9), regulates location of meiotic homologous recombination by binding to the DNA, causing epigenetic modifications and allowing for a double strand break (DSB); however its targeting mechanism is not fully understood. Knockouts in mice PRDM9 have been associated with infertility, which is suspected to be caused by mislocation of DSBs during meiosis. Over 100 alleles of PRDM9 are known in mice, each of which contains a unique zinc finger array and therefore selects different DNA binding sites for PRDM9. To detect and quantify all binding sites of PRDM9 without interference by additional regulatory effects (protein abundance, chromatin accessibility), we used a novel, in vitro assay called Affinity-Seq. We found over 39,000 significant binding sites for the PRDM9Dom2 allele in C57BL/6J mouse DNA. Quantification of the binding frequency at each sequence enabled estimation of binding affinity at each site in addition to standard nucleotide frequencies. To gauge the contribution of each nucleotide, we built a linear regression model that includes additive and interactive effects on the binding preference of PRDM9. We identified a few core nucleotides required for binding and additional bases that quantitatively modify binding affinity. We tested this model by performing Affinity-Seq on the CAST/EiJ genome providing various natural polymorphisms for quantitative validation. Our work yields a detailed view of the targeting mechanism of PRDM9 in meiosis and can be broadly applied to any ZFP.', u'title': u'Modeling the Multiple Zinc Finger Protein PRDM9 Binding with Affinity-seq'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'Although failure of DNA Mismatch Repair (MMR) is associated with microsatellite instability\nand colorectal cancer, little is known about MMR except for its biochemical pathway.\nBy assembling known regulatory interactions, we built a novel gene regulatory network of MMR using a time- and state-discrete stochastic modeling framework. This model includes genes and microRNAs targeting MMR genes: MSH2, MSH6, MLH1, PMS2. We support the hypothesis that microRNAs can stabilize network dynamics, thus enhancing genomic stability, by showing that overexpressing microRNAs increases robustness while knocking them out seems to have the opposite effect. In\naddition to providing a gene regulatory network of MMR, the model yields various predictions and enables further analysis of the potential stabilizing effect of microRNAs on gene regulatory networks.', u'title': u'A Regulatory Network of DNA Mismatch Repair'}]

summary: Resume: http://goo.gl/JkkEI8 Cover Letter: http://goo.gl/3ScndK\n\nCross disciplinary modeler who has worked in analytics development, data visualization, and modeling, across hard and soft science disciplines:\n  - consumer packaged goods\n  - competitive draw analysis  \n  - electrical engineering & ecology, \n  - econometrics, \n  - statistics, & \n  - data-based patent negotiation\n  - data-based damages negotiation\n\nEnthusiastic mentor of remedial Excel users, budding data scientists, data visualization seekers, and the Pivot Table curious. \n\nStrong SQL skills: entity-relationship modeling, systems analysis, and accounting information systems. \n\nFluent in statistics software (R, SAS, SPSS, SYSTAT, ggplot 2), Excel PivotTables, and developing Excel applications to replace statistical software. \n\nDeep data visualization skills: Lee Wilkinson (President and author of SYSTAT) was on a quest to develop the ultimate data visualization language. His quest led: (a) to his developing SYGRAPH to prototype his language, and (b) to his book THE GRAMMAR OF GRAPHICS (or free), which Hadley Wickham used to create ggplot2 for R … which has since been ported to Python.\nWhile in graduate school, I threw myself head-first into SYGRAPH and became a technical graphics guru on MSU’s campus. Even the Bayesian HLM statistician Ph.D. students would come to me saying “it is not possible to do the graph I need with SYGRAPH!” … and then … “Thanks for your help!”\n\nEnthusiast of the R environment, and using split-apply-combine via plyr package and ggplot2. Man would this have saved a bunch of hair pulling with my first million record database!!!  \n\n20+ years experience in developing presentations, dashboards, ad hoc data-based arguments under tight time deadlines. \n\nDelivered over 250 training workshops across the USA, Australia, Singapore, India, Germany, France, and the UK.

summary: Dr. Yafei Yang has 15 years of experience in research, product development, business and management in computer and communication industry. From May 2008 to March 2016, he worked at Qualcomm Inc. (Office of the Chief Scientist and QCT), responsible for Qualcomm product security strategy, including smartphone chipsets, automotive chipsets, networking chipsets, IoT chipsets and server chipsets. Dr. Yang graduated from Univ. of Rhode Island and holds 7 US patents. He was invited to perform expert reviews on the technical proposals submitted under BTOP (White House Broadband Technology Opportunities Program) in 2010. To honor Dr. Yang's outstanding contribution to US economic recovery, US Secretary of Commerce (Gary Locke) and Assistant Secretary (Lawrence Strickling) wrote appreciation letters to him. \n\nIn April 2016, Dr. Yang co-founded a startup DAPU with IEEE Fellow Prof. Qing Yang. DAPU develops next-generation data storage and SSD products for high-performance storage systems in cloud and enterprise data center applications, with more innovation, intelligence, security and less cost.

summary: Anne Marie Smith is an enterprise information management strategist, data governance leader, data warehouse strategist with broad experience across industries. She has exceptional, demonstrated skills in enterprise information management (EIM) strategic consulting, business requirements gathering and analysis, data governance program development and implementation, data and information architecture, data and process modeling, master and reference data management, metadata management, data quality management, data warehouse strategy and planning.  She has developed and led data governance programs and led the development of enterprise information management programs for corporations and consultancies.\n\nAnne Marie has extensive experience as an instructor and course developer in the areas of  enterprise data / information management, data warehousing and business intelligence, project management, business analysis, data governance and stewardship.\n\nAnne Marie is an accomplished speaker, facilitator, and has served as an assistant professor of Management Information Systems (MIS) at various universities.\n\nAnne Marie writes frequently for data management publications and speaks often at conferences and seminars on her areas of expertise.  Anne Marie is a member of DAMA International (http://www.dama.org), and other professional organizations.\n\nAnne Marie holds a Ph.D. in Management Information Systems with a concentration in enterprise data management. summary: Recent graduate seeking engineering job. Though my doctorate is in mechanical engineering, I have a strong background in mathematics and computer science and a very wide breath of experiences in developing various software. My research focus during my doctorate has been primarily concerned with intelligent control systems but from the many years of working on my dissertation I recognize that there is never a universal best solution, so I always maintain a keen eye and an open mind when looking for the most suitable methods to attack a given problem. I believe the wide range of my interests also gives me an advantage when presented with a task. For example I’ve implemented genetic algorithms using MPI on a 64 node supercomputer, written minimax probability regression machine learning algorithms in C++, designed tools for game designers in using MFC and QT, developed 2D Butterworth filters to remove Moiré patterns from scanned halftone images, and debugged other programmers MIPS assembly code. Those experiences plus the research I’ve done while working on my doctorate have given me a strong foundation to solve many research problems. Even when I encounter new problems outside of my expertise, as long as the problem piques my interest, I’m a very fast learner and I’ll persist until I find a solution.

summary: I am actively seeking a job opportunity in the field of control, dynamic modeling, robotics. My expertise lies in the field of nonlinear control and dynamical systems. I am interested in challenging projects and would be interested to work in new emerging technologies. My expertise lies in the following areas –\n\nDynamic modeling and Simulation\n●\tExperienced in dynamic modeling and generating Simulink models of engineering systems.\n●\tDeveloped System ID process for aeroelastic wing using unsteady aerodynamic theory.\n●\tDesigned PID, LQG optimal and robust control, and Kalman filters using MatLab.\n●\tGood knowledge of C\\C++, algorithms, Assembly language programming and LabVIEW.\n\nControl and Optimization\n●\tExpertise in Lyapunov stability analysis, passivity based control, and networked control.\n●\tStudied model predictive control, robust and optimal control, and adaptive control theories.\n●\tExperience with convex optimization using CVX and MatLab programming.\n\nDynamical Systems Theory\n●\tResearch experience in dynamical systems theory, Markov chains and stochastic dynamics.\n●\tSet based methods of computing stability of complex systems and dynamical characteristics.\n●\tKnowledge of polynomial chaos based uncertainty propagation and sensitivity analysis.

summary: EXPERIENCE HIGHLIGHTS\n 8 years of experience in vibroacoustics in the human space exploration industry. 8 years of experience in noise & vibration computer aided engineering (CAE) analysis and testing in the business aviation industry. 2 years of industry experience in noise and vibration CAE analysis of automotive air intake systems and duct acoustics. 7 years of research experience in modeling and analysis of turbofan engine inlet noise propagation and radiation using analytical techniques and numerical methods. Extremely proficient in vibro-acoustic numerical techniques like Finite Element Method (FEM), Boundary Element Method (BEM) and Statistical Energy Analysis (SEA). 4 years of research (theoretical and experimental) experience in modeling and active control of vibration (flutter) in wing structures. Have in-depth knowledge of structural acoustics, active & passive control strategies in noise and vibration, duct acoustics and turbofan engine inlet noise. 5 years of university teaching experience in the area of acoustics, vibration and engineering math. A combined total of over 25 years of professional experience in the field of noise & vibration engineering. \n\nRecipient of NASA Space Flight Awareness (SFA) Honoree Award\n\nIssued US Patent No. 8,511,601 – Aircraft with Tuned Vibration Absorber Mounted On Skin\n\nElected 2012 Associate Fellow of AIAA.\n\nRecipient of Raytheon Excellence in Technology (EIT) award fours years in a row (2002 – 2005). \n\nSpecialties: Noise & Vibration, Human Space Flight Vibroacoustics, Aircraft Acoustics, FAA certification, Automotive NVH

summary: I am an applied mathematician / engineer with a wide range of computational skills and broad knowledge of mathematical modeling, numerical computation, applied analysis, signal processing, programming, and engineering. I have extensive experience with a number of powerful programming languages (Matlab, C/C++, Python) and with development in Linux and other Unix-like environments. My research expertise involves computational and statistical methods that are equally beneficial to applications in scientific and industrial contexts.\n\nI also have several years of experience as an electrical engineer specializing in embedded systems development. This experience complements my mathematics background with an understanding of low-level computing architecture, digital design, and practical systems development.\n\nI have strong scientific writing skills and am capable of translating complex mathematical and technical concepts for a variety of audiences. I have publications in refereed technical journals and have presented my research at engineering conferences. I have experience teaching mathematics at the university level. \n\nFinally, I have some experience leading the hiring process for computational research positions.

summary: Life is what we make of it and life is excellent!  I am a U.S. Navy aviation veteran (S-3A/B Viking torpedo bombers) and retired U.S. Air Force (B-52 Stratofortress flight and mission commander, Joint Terminal Attack Controller, replicator/trainer in defeating integrated air defenses, and program manager of integrating close air support training within joint-multinational air and land forces).  Clearances included TS/SCI/NATO for those that such has meaning.  I have a variety of degrees and specializations to include a Ph.D in business administration and project management.  In addition to teaching as an adjunct associate professor for ERAU, I am the program manager and research analysis for several ongoing multi-million-dollar research projects with DoD and Federal agency applications.  I enjoy flying, research, and statistical analysis with equal measure.  Scientific research is a means to understand the universe about us in a unique way to innovatively bring meaning where none before existed.  Do be bold and by all means do be alive in every way.  With fortune (not that I believe in such) I always enjoy rolling up my sleeves in life with other crazy like-minded razors creating meaning from chaos in the pursuit of the forest through the illusion of just trees.

summary: Grace Druml's adventurous and determined personality is illustrated throughout her work on the agency and corporate side of marketing and advertising.  Her hardworking mentality and pristine leadership skills exemplify her dedicated and ambitious character.  She is an active problem solver qualified to accomplish tasks under pressure in an organized and positive manner.  Grace’s powerful interpersonal and communicative skills were illustrated throughout her work with Paul Davis Restoration’s Marketing Department, as she worked face to face with current and potential clients promoting sales.  She similarly was recognized for her professionalism, diligent work ethic, and positive attitude as the New Business Intern at Laughlin Constable, a prestigious advertising agency.  Throughout her experience with Laughlin Constable, Grace formulated and presented pitches on infamous brands, organized market research on relevant trends, generated decks and visual aids for potential clients, as well as updated the agency’s social media platforms.  \n      In addition to her professional career, Grace illustrates her passion for volunteering by giving back to her community.  Throughout her four years in Denver, she has remained committed to the Anchor Center for Blind Children, SCORES Denver, and Children’s Hospital Colorado, where she has the opportunity to fill children and their families with happiness and hope one smile at a time.  She similarly has conducted youth leadership service trips to Guatemala and Jamaica over the summer months, as well as help the ALS Association of Wisconsin organize and plan for their annual gala.\n      Grace exemplifies her determined work ethic in the office, her compassionate character in her community, and her adventurous spirit in the outdoors.

summary: Ravi is an experienced Lean/Agile/DevOps/Gamification & Leadership Coach, Trainer, and Scrum/Scrumban/Kanban expert. His expertise ranges from assisting leaders & teams to large-scale transformation; by conducting hands-on training and coaching on adopting Agile/Scrum or Lean/Kanban process frameworks, with XP practices and DevOps core tenets related to people, process & tools.\n\nRavi has over 20 years of professional experience in various domains. He has been working in major silicon valley companies in SF bay area for past 18+ years.  Prior to Infosys, he worked at Western Digital, Cisco, PayPal & Symantec for last 7 years, coaching at all levels of agile adoption- individuals, teams, management and executives, specifically on servant leadership, software craftsmanship, agile software/hardware/firmware development & DevOps. During 8 years prior to that, Ravi worked as Development Manager in a startup. During 4 years during Dot Com era, hands-on Software Developer & Architect. Prior to settling in US (SF Bay Area), Ravi spent 3 years consulting on software engineering methods with various offshore software development centers including C-DAC in Pune and Telecom NZ in Auckland NZ. Ravi contributed to UML 0.8 draft for IEEE task force, during that time.\n\nIn summary, Ravi has grown through progressive ranks as Developer, Enterprise Architect, Dev Manager, SM, and most recently Agile Coach, Evangelist and DevOps Consultant. Ravi believes in community giving, specifically the agile-lean communities. Ravi is co-founder of agilecamp.org in SF bay area, organizer of SV-ALN, and co-founder of Cisco’s internal coaches network.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.11', u'description': u'Developed an interactive game in Greenfoot using JAVA which involved implementing Gang of Four design patterns and using Agile Scrum methodology for game development.\nDesigned the key functionality for maintaining Audio controls performed on different actor actions using inbuilt Java classes.\nDesigned the functionality for health check and maintaining final score board.\nThe patterns implemented were : Chain of Responsibility, Command , Decorator, State and Observer pattern. \nTools used : Java , Greenfoot, Astah UML and Modeling Tools\nThe Game demo Advertising video can be viewed at : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ARH1R9aKPcM', u'title': u'SuperBird Game in Greenfoot'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Created a clustered environment on Amazon EC2. \nUsed Puppet for configuration management to ensure configuration changes on many puppet agents (AWS EC2 instances). \nPerform replication and sharding on multiple virtual machines using MongoDB.\nFor better performance, proper security groups and an Elastic Load Balancer was also attached in front of all the instances for efficient request handling.', u'title': u'Cloud System Administration and Configuration'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.11', u'description': u'In this project, I used IBM Bluemix services to show how to analyze Section 8 housing fmr dataset by storing it in IBM dashDB and performing Data analytics using Apache Spark with Scala. The FMR dataset contains the rental value that is reimbursed by govt. in different county's around United States. SparkSQL queries are used to detect fraud with analysis such that if Actual prevailing Rent value represented by ACT_ is greater than 1.4 times of FDR_value then that county need to be checked for fraud since such spike in rent from FDR value can mean prevalent fraud in that county.', u'title': u'Apache Spark-Scala for Fraud Detection'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Created Java grammer to parse java source code classes to generate UML diagrams.\nPlantUML library used for UML class diagram generation and other open sorce API's used\nTechnologies used: Java, PlantUML, doclet API', u'title': u'Java UML Parser for Reverse Engineering'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Twitter Sentiment Analysis project gives positive and negative reviews on our favorite words search based on Twitter tweets. It has been implemented using Alchemy API  with BigData Hadoop to get social media stream data regularly into HDFS , and MongoDB to store sentiment analyzed data.\nDatabase : MongoDB\nLanguage : Python', u'title': u'Twitter Sentiment Analysis'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.11', u'description': u'Ordering and pickup Application for food courts that provide real time notifications for Food ordering and pickup. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013 ~ 2013', u'description': u'Utilized UniqueSoft state-of-art software data mining tools to reverse engineering the source code of the current system to understand the system features, architecture and design, major improvement opportunities and identify modernization strategy/plan. Used UniqueSoft DSL (Domain Specific Language) to define data model template and the data mining tools to generate concrete data model from template for the purpose of data mining and Web interface of data visualization using various statistical/machine learning algorithms, including:\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Python for data pre-processing \n\u25ba Data mining/statistical learning algorithms in use: tree induction, maximum entropy, support vector machine, logistic regression, k-means, hierarchical clustering, nearest-neighbor reasoning, ROC graphs and curves, etc.\n\u25ba Data mining process: followed the CRISP-DM (Cross Industry Standard Process for Data Mining) process: Business understanding, data understanding, data preparation modeling, evaluation, and deployment.', u'title': u'SGSN GTP'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011 ~ 2011', u'description': u'Developed P25 ISSILoader system for ISSI Gateway load testing automation. The system served as a configurable number of peer ISSI gateways that automatically generates group call load traffic to/from the ISSI Gateway under development. The automated functions of the system include registering, initiating, receiving, and monitoring group calls and related multi-media data.\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Automatic code generation with the integration of TDL modeling with SIP Stack', u'title': u'P25 ISSILoader'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2007 ~ 2007', u'description': u'Led the effort of migrating an existing SDL based real-time telecommunication system (called DCC) to UML 2 to get prepared for developing new products in the future using the state of art MDD methodology. Replaced SDL models with UML, regenerated application, data marshaling, and platform integration code using new automatic code generation tools. The migrated system passed all the required unit, integration, box, and system testing successfully. \n\nChartered Motorola iDEN division-wide (100+ software engineers and developers) Model-Driven Engineering methodology roadmap, including new software development processes, standards, platforms, protocols, modeling & programming languages, tools, etc.\n\nLeadership, Technology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Technology roadmap\n\u25ba UML 2 modeling and automatic code generation\n\u25ba Automatic data marshaling code generation using iSL (Interface Specification Language)', u'title': u'Migration of SDL Projects to UML 2 & Technology Roadmap'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008 ~ 2008', u'description': u'Developed an innovative POC prototyping system that pioneered in the integration of UML model with Motorola SIP (Session Initiation Protocol) Stack for the purpose of developing new public safety products. One of the major challenges at the time is that the existing language (iSL) for data marshaling code generation in Motorola only supports binary protocol, but SIP is a protocol in textual format. Major contributions in innovation (with another software engineer) include re-writing the whole SIP standard in ASN.1 and successfully using it for automatic generation of UML classes/types and SIP data marshaling code. This POC system has been adopted as a template in the development of the real public safety system ISSI.1 Gateway.\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba SIP re-writing in ASN.1\n\u25ba Automatic code generation with the integration of UML 2 models with SIP Stack\n\u25ba Automatic data marshaling code generation using iSL (Interface Specification Language)', u'title': u'UML 2 & SIP Integration POC Prototyping'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013 ~ 2013', u'description': u'Developed smart data storage system for Cleversafe to re-implement the current Cloud computing (Amazon Simple Storage Service -S3) enabled data storage system using Model-Driven Development (MDD) methodology. Other contributions include presenting the MDD methodology to customer on customer site.\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Cloud computing: Amazon S3, AWS Java API, etc.\n\u25ba TDL modeling and automatic code generation\n\nNote: TDL is a Textual Design Language that extends UML 2 with Aspects.', u'title': u'Smart Data Storage System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013 ~ 2013', u'description': u'Developed network traffic testing automation system to automate network topology configuration, network traffic generation, traffic data capture, transformation, statistical analysis, and performance reporting. Implemented both traditional and new design patterns in Java such as Publisher-Subscriptions, Proxy, Thread Pool, Callback, Retry, Buffering, etc. Achieved defects-free deployment of the system into customer\u2019s real environment with 25+ machines running simultaneously. \n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba TDL modeling and automatic code generation\n\u25ba Network configuration/provisioning automation\n\u25ba Implementation of various design patterns', u'title': u'Network Traffic Testing Automation System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012 ~ 2012', u'description': u'Developed smart phone service provisioning test automation system to automate selective wireless service provisioning, wireless traffic data generation, monitoring, statistical data collection and analysis, performance data reporting, state/data persistence to survive planned system shutdown & restart, unexpected shutdown, etc. Utilized various modern software development methods (to connect the system to other system components), including SOAP/WSDL Web services, Java RMI, automatic SFTP downloading, Java clients to Oracle database, Aspects for state/data persistence, etc. Implemented both traditional and new design patterns in Java such as Publisher-Subscriptions, Proxy, Thread Pool, Callback, Retry, Buffering, etc.\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba TDL modeling and automatic code generation\n\u25ba Aspect-Oriented Modeling for data persistence \n\u25ba Implementation of various design patterns\n\u25ba Distributed computing: SOAP/WSDL Web services, Java RMI, SFTP\n\u25ba Database: Oracle', u'title': u'Smart Phone Service Provisioning Test Automation System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014 ~ 2014', u'description': u'Developed generic software data mining project to demonstrate the capability of UniqueSoft state-of-art software data mining tools in reverse engineering the complex open source system - Open SSL. Utilized UniqueSoft DSL (Domain Specific Language) to define data model template and the data mining tools to generate concrete data model from template for the purpose of data mining and Web interface of data visualization using various statistical/machine learning algorithms. Identified major issues with the current Open SSL libraries and possible solutions. The major issues identified include: over use of C macros, lack of layered design between the SSL library and the cryptography encoding/decoding library, complex code in C for data marshaling and the implementation of state machines, etc.\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Python for data pre-processing \n\u25ba Data mining/statistical learning algorithms in use: tree induction, maximum entropy, support vector machine, logistic regression, k-means, hierarchical clustering, nearest-neighbor reasoning, ROC graphs and curves, etc.\n\u25ba Data mining process: followed the CRISP-DM (Cross Industry Standard Process for Data Mining) process: Business understanding, data understanding, data preparation modeling, evaluation, and deployment.', u'title': u'Generic Software Data Mining Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.8 ~ 2010.8', u'description': u'Developed software that served as bridge between Astro P25 two-way radio network and peer broadband networks. Implemented RTP / XIS packet translation, audio floor state management, and ISSI registration and group call procedures to optimize group call and private transmissions using formal modeling and fully automatic code generation techniques, including the code generation of integrating UML model with SIP stacks.\n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Automatic code generation with the integration of UML 2 models with SIP Stack\n\u25ba Automatic data marshaling code generation using iSL (Interface Specification Language)\n\u25ba Object-Oriented Programming for audio floor state management', u'title': u'P25 ISSI Gateway'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009 ~ 2010', u'description': u'Developed the public safety system ISSI.1 Gateway as bridge between Motorola\u2019s Astro P25 two-way radio network and peer broadband networks using MDD methodology. Major contributions include: Creating the Agile MDD process, establishing and training development team, writing box requirements document, performing OO analysis/architecture/design/development, coding the interface between ISSI.1 Gateway and XIS media system in iSL (Interface Specification Language), coding SDP (Session Description Protocol) and other related MIME standards/protocols in ASN.1, writing SIP integration glue code in C++, interfacing to tool vendors, tracking and resolving development issues, promoting knowledge sharing, mentoring team members, etc. These efforts significantly contributed to the successful release of the product in time with quality. \n\nTechnology & Innovation Highlights:\n\n\u25ba Agile Model-Driven Development (refer to the article in IEEE Software, 2011 for details)\n\u25ba Automatic code generation with the integration of UML 2 models with SIP Stack\n\u25ba Automatic data marshaling code generation using iSL (Interface Specification Language)', u'title': u'Motorola Solutions ISSI.1 Gateway System'}]

summary: Ruth Raventós is one of the co-founders and CEO of Nelio, the company behind Nelio Content & Nelio A/B Testing. \n\n- Nelio Content: The all-in-one editorial calendar for WordPress to generate and schedule quality content efficiently and with high impact by promoting it on your social networks.\n\n- Nelio A/B Testing is the only WordPress Conversion Optimization Platform.\n\nRuth obtained her PhD in Software Engineering at Universitat Politècnica de Catalunya - BarcelonaTech and did a Master of Information Systems at DePaul University (Chicago). \n\nShe has professional experience in the business world and at the University. She is also certified in Inboud Marketing.

summary: Scott Cinnamond has about 17 years of progressive commercial shrink-wrap and enterprise software architecture experience, a proven track record with many products and most enterprise systems still in production today. Scott has 13 years experience using SOA, Java/J2EE and Cloud technologies such as HBase, Cassandra, Hadoop, Mahout, Spark, ESB, JMS, SDO, EJB, JPA, JDBC, SOAP, REST, JSF, XSLT and XML-Schema. He has gained expertise in system design and implementation using Service-Oriented (SOA) and Model-Driven Architecture (MDA) principles and all major Application Server products. Scott Cinnamond has excellent communication and leadership skills and possesses several letters-of-recommendation from executive-level industry representatives in the D.C. Metro and Silicon Valley areas.\n\nOPEN SOURCE PRODUCT OWNERSHIP / DEVELOPMENT\n* CloudGraph® - HBase, Cassandra, complex modeling, object mapping. See http://cloudgraph.org \n* Plasma - Service Data Objects (SDO) implementation. See http://plasma-sdo.org \n* FUML - Foundational UML Reference implementation. See http://modeldriven.org/fuml \n\n* Architecture: SOA, ESB, MDA, TOGAF\n* Languages & Technologies: Java 6, HBase, Hadoop, JMS, SDO, JPA, EJB, Hibernate, SQL,  JAX-WS, Spring, REST, JSF, PrimeFaces, RichFaces, AJAX, XML, XSL, XSLT, XML-Schema, SOAP, OWL/RDF, JAAS\n* Big Data: HBase 0.9.x, Cassandra 2.x, Hadoop 1.x, Spark 1.1, MapReduce\n* Machine Learning: Mahout 0.9, Stanford NLP\n* SOA Tech/Governance: IBM DataPower X150, HP Systinet Platform, Registry\n* Messaging Servers: Weblogic JMS, Sun One MQ, IBM MQ-Series, OpenJMS\n* Enterprise Service Bus: JBoss-Fuse, Custom ESB, OpenESB, ServiceMix, Mule\n* Data Access: HBase, Cassandra, SDO, OpenJPA, Hibernate, Oracle, MySql \n* Modeling: UML, SysML, MagicDraw, Sparx EA, Eclipse Papyrus\n* Operating Systems: Linux, Sun Solaris, Windows, AIX
