projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ 2012.4', u'description': u'KCPAVS is an integrated software platform having features required at different stages of biological research using pathway data. KCPAVS is highly interactive, user friendly, unified web server for: 1) browsing and searching KEGG metabolic -, signaling-, disease- pathways and global maps of ~25 organisms; 2) pathway analysis using general statistical methods like Fisher's test and Binomial proportions test and by specialized algorithms like like PAGE;  3) visualizing experimental data and analysis reports; 4) comparative pathway analysis;   5) collaboration and mind mapping on a pathway to exchange information and ideas;  and 6) accumulation of annotations from the biological research community and serving as a knowledge-base.', u'title': u'KcPAVS: KEGG based Collaborative Pathway Analysis and Visualization System for Comparative Biological Studies'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.1 ~ now', u'description': u'Cardiovascular thesaurus consists of controlled phenotype terms collected by the experts from books, literature, websites (e.g. wiki, online medical dictionary), keywords used in biomedical  database and related ontologies (anatomy & phenotype ontologies). This thesaurus will be eventually developed into a standard cardiovascular phenotype ontology. The curated terms are annotated with definition, reference to source(PMID, URL), synonyms. If a similar terms exist in other ontologies  they both are linked together by adding xrefs. The thesaurus is avaialbe in OBO format and assembled using freely available OBOedit tool.', u'title': u'Mammalian Cardiovascular Phenotype Ontology'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.9 ~ 2010.1', u'description': u'The website provides you with interactive and more detailed shecmatic diagrams corresponding to figures 1 to 4 of the publication: Biology of endoplasmic reticulum stress in the heart Cir Res 2010. These diagrams describe endoplasmic reticulum stress pathways with more emphasis towards its role in cardiac physiology and pathology. The diagram representation follows Systems Biology Graphical Notation format (SBGN).\n\nFollowing interactive figures are provided:\nFigure S1: Endoplasmic reticulum stress-induced PERK signaling pathway\nFigure S2: Endoplasmic reticulum stress-induced activation of ATF6 pathway\nFigure S3: Integrated map of ER stress-induced pathways\nFigure S4: Activation IRE1 pathway by endoplasmic reticulum stress ', u'title': u'Interactive map of endoplasmic reticulum stress-induced pathways'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.9 ~ now', u'description': u'We are interested in studying mechanisms underlying the action of ER stress chemical chaperone proteins and potent drugs known to relieve the ER stress and thus having beneficial affects by preventing heart progressing to failure. We are using molecular biology, biochemical and systems approach generate, integrate and analyze experimental data including high throughput data ( micro-array and MS/MS proteomics data) obtained from pressure overloaded animal heart samples and chemically treated cell models.', u'title': u'Studying mechanisms of chemical chaperone proteins/drugs known to alleviate the ER Stress using systems methodology in heart'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2003 ~ 2004.12', u'description': u'The Database of Quantitative Cellular Signaling is a repository of models of signaling pathways. It includes reaction schemes, concentrations, rate constants, as well as annotations on the models. The database provides a range of search, navigation, and comparison functions.\n\nContributors to the database\n\nThe true contributors to this database are the thousands of biochemists, pharmacologists and molecular biologists who have worked out the details of signaling pathways and their rates. As anyone who has done experiments of this kind will attest, this involves long hours of work, often involving nasty chemicals and radioactivity, to obtain a couple of rate constants. This project is dedicated to their efforts and to the hope that this database will help to bring them together with modelers to better understand the chemistry of life.\nUpinder S. Bhalla.\n\nThe impetus for developing the DOQCS database came from a discussion with Shinya Kuroda and Jeanette Hellgren-Kotaleski at the Stockholm Workshop on Computational Neuroscience, organized by Anders Lanser and Sten Grillner in June 2001. My thanks to all of them.\n\nInitial seed pathway models were compiled in published papers:\n\nBhalla, U.S. and Iyengar, R.\nEmergent properties of networks of biological signaling pathways. Science 283:381-387, 1999.\n\nBhalla, U.S. and Iyengar, R.\nRobustness of the bistable behavior of a biological signaling feedback loop. Chaos 11(1):221-226, 2001\n\nThe DOQCS pathway database entry project has been initiated with the help of\nS. Sivakumaran\nS. Hariharaputran\nJ. Mishra\n\nLater Model contribution continued by\nPradeep Kumar.S\nSharat J.Vayttaden\nPragati Jain  (currently working in Lab)\nPrasoon Agarwal  \n\nThe programming of the doqcs site is done by\nU.S. Bhalla and\nHarsha Rani.G.V ', u'title': u'Database of Quantitative Cellular Signaling (DOQCS) database'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1993 ~ 1994', u'description': u'The objective of this semester long project was to get hands on experience growing crops; follow complete crop cycle for seasonal cereal crop Ragi on a quater acre plots. We were expected to follow scientific methodologies (e.g. improved means for delivering agrochemicals, soil and water conservation, irrigation) and enhance yield. We were also given opportunity to experience traditional animal forming methods that were followed. As a result of this course I was able to develop practical, problem solving and research skills that are needed in crop production. This course gave me opportunity to bring the theoretical concepts and principles of sustainable agro-ecosystem design, function and management to practical realization.\n', u'title': u'Crop protection and production strategies for agricultural crops'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ now', u'description': u'The MCPG-DB is a comprehensively-structured mammalian (mouse,human & rat) cardiovascular phenome knowledgebase. Information in MCPG-DB is manually curated and also integrates related information from several public databases. MCPG-DB contains evidence connecting cardiovascular phenotypes, associated molecular members (gene, protein, marker, small molecule), pathways, and perturbants (genetic, chemical, drug and environmental).\n\nMCPG is also equipped with search, data management, comparison, analysis, visualization and reporting tools.\n\nThe aim of MCPG database is to provide a useful integrated cardiovascular resource to the physicians, cardiovascular research community and biomedical and health informaticians ( including medical informaticians, systems biologist and bioinformaticians). MCPG fuels data-driven medicine bridging basic research and medical research. The clinicians and researchers can employ data and tools in MCPG-DB to understand how genetic variations contributes to phenotypes/diseases/traits.', u'title': u'Mammalian Cardiovascular Phenome-Drug-Target Integrated Database'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.6 ~ 2012.8', u'description': u'This was a collaborative project with the experimental colleagues in my laboratory to research on importance of Endoplasmic Reticulum Stress (ER stress) response in heart during hypertrophy and heart failure.  The study investigated whether PBA, a known chemical chaperone drug, could be used as therapeutic drug in pressure-overload cardiac hypertrophy in mouse. We found that PBA reduced ER stress response and also attenuated hypertrophy. We expected complete attenuation of hypertrophy but interesting results showed that there was only partial attenuation. I could address this question only by systems approach by integrating all the available knowledge from literature and experimental data by building a qualitative network. I found very little interaction between hypertrophic genes and ER stress genes (~16 among 250 hypertrophic genes frequently reported in PubMed had some experimental basis for interaction). Thus, in light of the experimental results and the insilico analysis we concluded that since cardiac hypertrophy is a complex disease, there could be other ERstress-independent mechanisms that could also be contributing factors, which PBA may not affect and thus there was no complete recovery as expected.', u'title': u'Effects of the chemical chaperone 4-phenylbutyric acid on pressure-overload cardiac hypertrophy'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ now', u'description': u'Collaborative environment systems give researchers an easy way for interaction through internet (overcoming physical distance and isolation) where knowledge and experience can be effectively shared between peers. Multiple remote participants can be actively involved in investigation. Such technology is very useful for modern biological research where often multiple research groups collaborate over the same project and are usually dispersed geographically. Pathway communities, collection and collaboration system (p3c) is a online collaborative system customized to maximize its utility in biological research in context of storing, publishing, sharing and communicating biological pathway data.\n\n(P3C) is a free online pathway publishing and repository application that allows users to accumulate pathways related documents (images, documents, publications, videos, audios, multimedia materials and links), data in as spreadsheets, presentation, and text document, organize them into categories and share them with other collaborator. P3C system currently allow publishing two types of commonly used standard pathway formats: CellDesigner pathways and KEGG pathways. This allows researchers, students and educators to share their work with others, collaborate over a task and save all the information online (cloud) for access on any computer with any operating system, internet browser and internet connectivity.', u'title': u'P3C: The Pathway Communities, Collaboration and Collection System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.10 ~ now', u'description': u'Integrated Pathway Resources, Analysis and Visualization System (iPAVS) is an integrated biological pathway database designed to support pathway discovery in the fields of proteomics, transcriptomics, metabolomics and systems biology. The key goal of IPAVS is to provide biologists access to expert-curated pathways from experimental data belonging to specific biological contexts related to cell types, tissues, organs and diseases. IPAVS currently integrates over 500 human pathways (consisting of 24\u2009574 interactions) that include metabolic-, signaling- and disease-related pathways, drug\u2013action pathways and several large process maps collated from other pathway resources. IPAVS web interface allows biologists to browse and search pathway resources and provides tools for data import, management, visualization and analysis to support the interpretation of biological data in light of cellular processes. Systems Biology Graphical Notations (SBGN) and Kyoto Encyclopedia of Genes and Genomes (KEGG) pathway notations are used for the visual display of pathway information. The integrated datasets in IPAVS are made available in several standard data formats that can be downloaded. IPAVS is available at: http://ipavs.cidms.org.', u'title': u'IPAVS: An Integrated Pathway Resources, Analysis and Visualization System'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'The OnTheLine Database is an International Press Institute (IPI) project that aims to systematically monitor online harassment of journalists as a response to their reporting.\nCurrently, the Database reflects data collected on Turkey since January 2016 and on Austria since September 2016. Additional countries will be included at a later point.\nThe online harassment of journalists and independent news sites \u2013 particularly in the form of targeted efforts led by states or powerful non-state actors \u2013 presents a serious threat to free expression in the digital space, which has traditionally been a safe haven for media operating under repressive regimes. This project seeks to understand the scope of online harassment and its impact on journalists and the free flow of information. Although this issue has been the focus of growing media attention, most coverage so far has been based on anecdotal evidence.\n\nProject Leader: Javier Luque', u'title': u'OnTheLineDB - Tracking Online Harassment of Journalists'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.1', u'description': u'Model-Based Adaptation Engineering (MAE) in Automation Systems Engineering (ASE) (MAE4ASE) is a module of the Christian Doppler Laboratory on Software Engineering Integration for Flexible Automation Systems. It addresses the upcoming need of ASE to raise the level of flexibility of automation systems even further in order to better react to changing environments. For instance, this is of particular importance in the context of the emerging Industry 4.0 initiative which aims, amongst other goals, at providing increased flexibility for production systems to better adapt to the changing needs of customers, organizations, and society. As a consequence, systems are no longer designed to be, but they have to be designed to evolve. Of course, raising the level of flexibility by switching to evolvable systems directly impacts the requirements on and complexity of the engineering process for such systems. To cope with this new kind complexity in ASE, dedicated concepts, techniques, and tools are needed to enable change and to ensure a systematic, safe, and predictable adaptation of systems to prevent the negative side effects of ad-hoc changes. A promising way to tackle this problem is to apply modeling and simulation approaches in combination with the establishment of adaptations as first class entities throughout the whole engineering process which is the mission of MAE4ASE.', u'title': u'Model-Based Adaptation Engineering in Automation Systems Engineering'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012 ~ 2012', u'description': u'DFAnalysis\u2019 service offers an objective profile of an athlete\u2019s boxing performance, and is designed to also include those aspects of performance which even expert viewers have difficulty detecting visually. This information can be used in different ways; e.g. during the training phase as well as in preparation for fights with individual opponents.\nDFAnalysis service is realized through an informatics software which has been devised as a result of the experience obtained by the lead researcher while coaching and supervising high level athletes ', u'title': u'DFAnalysis'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2013.9', u'description': u'Model-Driven Performance Analysis Methodology and Tools Integration', u'title': u'CRAFTERS -ConstRaint and Application Framework for Tailoring Embedded Real-time Systems'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.4 ~ 2011.4', u'description': u'The PRESTO project aims at improving test-based embedded systems development and validation, while considering the constraints of industrial development processes. This project is based on the integration of:\na) test traces exploitation (generated by test execution in the software integration phase induced by the industrial development process, to validate the requirements of the system) along with\nb) platform models and\nc) design space exploration techniques', u'title': u'PRESTO'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.1 ~ 2017.1', u'description': u'Understanding Uncertainty\nProviding a comprehensive and extensible taxonomy of uncertainties, classifying uncertainties, their properties, and their relationships.\n\nModelling Uncertainty\nCreating an extensible and configurable Uncertainty Modelling Framework relying on exiting modelling/testing standards to support modelling uncertainties.\n\nDiscovering Uncertainty\nDeveloping smart techniques relying on existing search algorithms to discover unknown uncertainties.\n\nTesting Uncertainty\nCreating an Uncertainty Testing Framework to generate cost-effective test cases to test CPS under uncertainty.', u'title': u'U-TEST'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Leveraging fUML, we realized the Agilla Modeling Framework (AMF), an executable model library, that permitted to conveniently design agent-based software applications and to carry out its timing analysis upon the execution of the corresponding fUML model.', u'title': u'Agilla Modeling Framework (WiP)'}]

summary: Luca Berardinelli is a postdoc at the Distributed System Group (DSG). He received his Ms and PhD degrees in Computer Science from the University of L’Aquila, Italy. He has been a postdoc at the Univ. of L’Aquila (Quality of Services, Model-Driven Engineering). Since 09/2012 he is a post doc at TU Wien. He worked on MDE applied to cyber-physical production systems (Industrie 4.0). From 01/2017 he is working on modeling and analysis of uncertainty of cyber-physical systems (see u-test.eu project).

summary: From a deep seated desire to contribute to work that positively impacts the quality of peoples’ lives, wish to utilise my extensive and varied experience in financial and management accounting within an organisation dedicated to providing quality care to the elderly.\n\nEducational Qualifications and Work Exposure \n* Member CPA Australia \n* CPA examination, USA\n* Chartered Accountant ICAI  \n* Bachelor of Commerce \nWith a varied experience in Big4 global accounting firm – Ernst and Young, ASX listed – Funtastic (Madman division) and not for profits\n\nSolid practical knowledge of all finance functions \n* All aspects of Finance department operations including accounts payable, accounts receivable, general ledger, capital expenditure, allocation of costs to programs, accruals, reconciliations\n* End of month and end of year processes within strict timelines and liaising with auditors\n* Budgeting and forecasting\n* Financial modeling\n* Project accounting\n* Profitability and risk analysis\n* Finance department policies, processes and internal controls\n* Change and project management\n* Compliance and reporting\n* Preparation of statutory accounts\n* Government grant acquittals\n* Design and development of Board reports \n* Incisive analysis of performance, variances and trends \n* GST and Withholding tax\n\nAccounting systems \n* Accounting Packages – Pronto, Sage, MYOB, Quickbooks, BaaN, Tally\n* Reporting – COGNOS, Crystal, TM1, Verity, MS Office suite\n\nStrong determination to contribute to the Aged Care sector \n* Ability to research industry changes and reforms to ensure organisation responsiveness\n* Well-developed analytical skills to inform and support the development and implementation of the strategic direction \n* Passion and perseverance to achieve the goal while building on relationships at all levels \n* Continuous Professional Development - Accounting in Aged Care, Active Service model,  developments in the industry\n* Aged Care Today website launched to share resources

We have given you interview tips along with a writing resume guide to help you fill in the 16 beautifully designed templates. \n\nResumeExpert is a free to download app that allows you to save to your favourite cloud storage, email or print directly from you mobile device. summary: I am an accounting professional with an emphasis in taxation. As an Enrolled Agent (EA) I am a federally authorized tax practitioner who has technical expertise in the field of taxation. An EA is empowered by the U.S. Department of the Treasury to represent taxpayers before all administrative levels of the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) for audits, collections, and appeals.\n\nMy goal is to understand your business and challenges to more effectively work towards achieving your goals.  I want to be your business partner to proactively find effective solutions to your needs and help you to better manage your time and money.  Consistent and timely communication and risk management are tools I utilize to exceed client expectations.  With your goals and aspirations in mind, I can help you in the right direction and on budget.  I am highly organized with strict attention to detail.\n\nIf you wish to contact me, please do so at jayson@jcwtaxaccounting.com or 262-299-3772.\n\nSpecialties: My specialties include personal and small business tax preparation and planning.  My professional tax preparation saves clients money as well as hours of personal stress and frustration.  I also provide payroll and full service bookkeeping services as a cost effective alternative for small business owners.  This allows them to spend more time and resources on revenue generating activities and less time working through the always changing and highly regulated financial aspects of business.

summary: Vasili Sofiadellis has transitioned from playing professional soccer in both Greece and South Africa to being a Chartered Accountant. Sofiadellis worked at PwC, performing numerous deals and due diligence assignments, where after he Co-Created PwC's Strategy in Innovation / the Startup Ecosystem. \n\nHe is now a director at Visions2Ventures, a bespoke advisory and VC firm and also the founder of Changemakers Lab.\n\nVasili is passionate about people, tech entrepreneurship and accelerating the SDGs. He thrives at creating an enabling environment, through which entrepreneurs and other stakeholders can flourish and achieve their objectives. \n\nOne of his greatest strengths is his ability to put himself in others shoes, thereby being objective and able to add value to respective stakeholders. \n\nHis passion for people and entrepreneurship, has led Vasili to being a member on multiple committee’s and exciting initiatives. These include:\n- Member of the Silicon Cape’s Executive Committee - Silicon Cape strives to be the catalyst for tech in the Western Cape. We bring together entrepreneurs, developers and investors to foster startups in the Western Cape.\n\n- Founding crew member of Startupboat - Startupboat brings together different stakeholders who create solutions for the social challenges currently faced by the refugee crisis.\n\n- Mentor for Tech Lab Africa - Tech Lab Africa is a RISE Africa initiative, in partnership with Barclays, designed to discover, nurture and empower the next generation of financial services, health technology and health information technology innovators.\n\n- Committee member of the Hellenic Community of Cape Town and Environs – Responsibilities include ensuring a vibrant Hellenic community.\n\n- Member of the EBAN Committee - EBAN aims to pave the way to setting impact investing as the new standard of excellence.\n\n- Co Founder of Startup Safari - A travel immersion program that connects entrepreneurs & startups to the fastest growing eco-systems globally.

summary: Denise is a creative, business solutions and values based executive with over 20 years of general management, financial and strategic planning, accounting, human resource management, instructing, facilitating and consulting experience across private and public sector industries.  \n\nSince 2003 Denise has focused on evolving and developing her consulting practice with a specialized focus on strategic planning, coaching and customized leadership, action learning, finance, process management, and human resource development to executives in a vast number of industries.  Concurrent with leading her own business practice, Denise was a part time instructor at the University of Manitoba instructing in Financial Reporting, Introductory Management Accounting, Intermediate and Advanced Cost Accounting.\n\nIn the preceding fifteen years, Denise’s business expertise was solidified through active leadership with major strategic change in aggressive industry settings. While in the role of CFO with a brewing company following a public offering, challenges included strategic planning to facilitate all financial and human capital aspects as well as a successful statutory amalgamation with another brewery. \n\nDenise is a co-moderator/facilitator in the Society of Management Accountant’s Strategic Leadership Program. The program’s ongoing reviews and studies of business case analysis and the business life cycle in conjunction with all phases of strategic development within an organization, provide Denise with current learning and applications to best practice organizational development, and leadership development. \n\nDenise has further demonstrated her passion for facilitation and leadership development in her work with the Asper School's Executive Program through content development and delivery to the various clients of the University of Manitoba's, Asper School.\n\nSpecialties: •\tStrategic Planning\n•\tLeadership Development and Coaching\n•\tGroup Facilitation and Instruction\n•\tCustomized learning programs\n•\tMulti-generational Realities\n•\tChange Management\n•\tPerformance Management\n•\tRole Reviews and Performance Evaluation Design\n•\tOrganization Structure and Management Team Development\n•\tFinancial Analysis and Reporting\n•\tProject Management and Tactical Change Implementation\n•\tGeneral Management\n•\tHuman Resource Management\n•\tPolicy and Procedure Development

With over 26-years of experience of financial management, strategic planning, forecasting and risk management in the private, public and not-for-profit sectors, we can also train and motivate you and your team to take more focused and collective control over your finances and decision-making. \nTo provide you with more detailed oversight of what's happening to your enterprises's finances, we encourage your business to team up with Xero as your flexible online Software as a Service (SaaS) accounting system, giving you real-easy, real-time access - 24/7/365 - directly to your own financial management information via the cloud on any web-enabled device. Here's a link to explain how the cloud facilitates smartworking - http://www.pinterest.com/pin/518547344565523285/\nWe believe that tech-savvy businesses which embrace the cloud by utilising SaaS will be more efficient, profitable and happier companies in which to work.

summary: About Us\nEight Square was founded in 2004 by Amanda Li and Richard Bryant to provide fiscal management\nand advisory services to nonprofit organizations in New York City. The firm’s partners have a\ncombined forty years of experience serving the nonprofit community, offering a full range of\nmanagement and professional services. The firm focuses on applying effective and responsible fiscal\nmanagement across the organization and provides complementary services in human resources,\noperations and technology for small to mid-size nonprofit and philanthropic organizations.\nManagement Team\nAmanda Li\nMs. Li, a founding partner at Eight Square Inc., has over twenty years of experience in all aspects\nof non-profit fiscal and contract management; from audit, financial statements, payroll, U.S. and\nforeign government, foundation and corporation contract management, fund accounting systems\nand database management. summary: Experienced CFO and business advisor with a knack for simplifying and organising businesses for growth. \n\nI see any business as a system that can be improved. A fascinating assembly of people, processes, information and tools, somehow coming together to solve a problem, fulfill a need and please a customer. A complex machine with lots of moving parts which can often be simplified and optimised to do remarkable things.\n\nI believe that lack of focus, noise, unnecessary complexity and clutter (in minds, methods and communication) hinder most businesses from ever achieving greatness. And I enjoy nothing more than untangling, decluttering and organising businesses (and the minds of their leaders) to help them focus on what really matters and reach new heights.\n\nI have a passion for simplicity, logic and common sense. I value clear, structured thinking and economy of speech. I am on a constant hunt for a 'simpler and better way' and enjoy applying my creativity to this pursuit. \n\nI am independently minded and am keen to express unconventional views when I can clearly see a better outcome. I am a pragmatic and resourceful leader who recognises strengths in people, and can work with the tools available...often after fueling that potential and improving those tools.\n\nI organise businesses for profitable growth. My top three tools are simplicity, clarity and focus. My methods involve understanding the business economics, setting ambitious targets, optimising operations, measuring what matters, and equipping people for success. I have a habit of re-organising finance functions to drive business performance. \n\nI also have a geeky side, constantly learning about available tech tools and searching for ways to exploit their power in business.

summary: There is a chance that when you first glance over the résumé I’ve submitted, your reaction will be; “This person doesn’t seem qualified for a job in the fashion industry...she’s a finance manager”.\nMy objective is to convince you that the knowledge and experience I’ve acquired gaining my college education makes me an ideal candidate for out-performing the expectations of any position within your group that requires:\n•\tIntelligence, \n•\tDedication to results\n•\tAn entrepreneurial mind\n•\tPassion for fashion public relation and marketing \n•\tA true desire to work in the fashion industry.\nAs my résumé details, I’m excellent with numbers (handle Excel and SAP with ease), adapt well to changing environments and differing assignments and function effectively in teams, whether as a member or the leader.  No one has ever been disappointed giving me an assignment, a due date and a not-to-exceed budget.  \nAnd if you need someone to deal with Asian suppliers and/or customers, I’m it...since I speak and write both of the major Chinese languages and, being Chinese, I understand the culture as only a native can.\nAll I’m missing is that little piece of direct fashion industry experience.  But if my prior experience grasping the fundamentals of the diverse businesses I’ve worked in is any indication, I will come up to speed faster than you probably think possible.\nIf a true “diamond in the rough” would be a beneficial addition to your organization, than a short meeting to discuss my full potential could be a good idea for the both of us.  In anticipation of arranging a convenient time for us to meet, I will call you shortly.

summary: Do you find bookkeeping is distracting you from running your business? We can help.\n\nI created my first business, Digits & Decimals, 14 years ago. By observing my clients, I noted that some of them spent too much time either trying to organize their bookkeeping, or avoid paying penalties, instead of focusing on building their businesses. To service this need, I created my second business, Calculated Approach. \n\nHere’s who we work with:\n\n✓ START UPS: Did you just start your business? Are you unsure about what accounting system to use? We will advise you on the best solutions for your business. We also provide you training to ensure your business is on a solid foundation, right from the start. \n\n✓ GROWING BUSINESS: Is your business growing? Are things getting out of hand? Do you feel unorganized? We will create customized solutions and systems to help you grow seamlessly.\n\n✓ INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS: Do you want to expand your international business into Canada, but you are uncertain about Provincial or Federal laws? We work with international companies of all sizes to ensure that their bookkeeping practices are in compliance with Canadian laws and regulations. \n\n✓ ESTABLISHED BUSINESSES: Are you worried about possible inconsistencies or suspect a fraud in your books? As trained fraud specialists, we will investigate and detect any problematic situations and set up processes that will protect you from potential loss. \n\n✓ SOLOPRENEUR: Are you overwhelmed by all there is to do in running your business? Do you need objective and practical advice in your bookkeeping to help you see where your money is going and what you should be watching for? We will educate and help you make the right decisions at the right time. \n\n✓ BOOKKEEPERS & ACCOUNTANTS: Do you wish your clients would clearly understand what you are trying to tell them? Take one of our fun one-day accounting workshops. It is a proven training program that is unique. \n\nContact us Now! ✆ 604-336-3913

summary: 20+ years of finance and accounting experience, ranging from an early career in public accounting to finance leadership for a NASDAQ healthcare business with $429 million in revenues. In my current role as CFO at InterDent, I successfully administer all financial controls for the $350M dental practice management company with 180+ retail locations. I have executed a critical role in sell-side due diligence and financial preparation for the PE sale of the business – presenting the business to multiple buyers. \nActive and high energy, I create a spirited and engaging work environment. My leadership style is consultative and I believe in building high achieving teams. I build trust-based relationships with my teams forged by respect and mutual commitment in reaching our goals, inspiring them to move forward and create unique solutions to difficult problems. \n\nStrong knowledge of the Retail/ Healthcare / Workers Compensation industries. Both public company and private equity experience, including a sales process. \n\nExamples of effectiveness as CFO: \n\n► Managed entire corporate accounting function and Treasury Services department. Able Ideaz is a Metro Detroit based comic book creation company and producers of the web series Comics Beer and Sci-fi, whose site I also consult on. \n\nPrior to that I worked as a Web Developer for DataStax, a database management solutions retailer. While working there I worked on two different projects the redesign of DataStax Academy: an eLearning website built in Drupal 7, and the deployment of new content on Planet Cassandra, another DataStax owned web-site, built in WordPress.\n\nBefore that I worked as a UX Designer for Nexient LLC. An Ann Arbor based web development consulting company. While at Nexient I helped create prototypes, user stories and designed mobile interfaces for the Best Buy Geek Squad Mobile App. I also designed and developed administrative features for 11Main, an eCommerce app created by Alibaba.\n\nPrior to that I worked as an Application Developer at AK Rewards LLC. I was primarily responsible for the development of a Family Organizational Management Application built in PHP CodeIgniter. I was also responsible for Front End Development, creating prototypes of new, and existing product specifications, using Keynote, and Source Control Management using Git. \n\nPrior, to that I worked as a Web Developer for the Detroit Media Partnership from 2011-14. The Detroit Media Partnership works in conjunction with the Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News to expand their brands' and the brands' of their advertisers by developing web, and mobile applications. I worked with PHP, jQuery, Drupal 7, Wordpress, and Python.\n \nFrom 2010-11, I worked as a Technical Illustrator at Technical Illustration Corporation in Dearborn, MI. summary: Mr. Gerrard has over 30 years’ experience in supporting the commercial market and the Department of Defense as a graphic artist and illustrator. Mr. Gerrard has worked on various types of conceptual illustrations, proposals, brochures/handouts, large-format posters, manuals, newsletters and briefings. He has also designed various command logos, and artwork for numerous publications. Mr. Gerrard designed and developed product display concepts; created, designed and composed advertising copy. He ensures all customer requests are met in an efficient and timely manner, and that the highest quality standards are met and maintained. Mr. Gerrard provides excellent customer and stays in contact with section managers and updates with new business leads and opportunities.\nMr. Gerrard has created graphics and briefings that were used in the White House and various Senate Briefings. At Lockheed Martin Mr. Gerrard has provided graphics support to numerous proposals (classified and unclassified). He was IPT-co chair for the Graphics Artists Group. While at TASC, he created 3-D models for inclusion into animations and provided custom graphic support to the Director of Advanced Science & Technology (AS&T) a subdirectorate of the National Reconnaissance Office (NRO). While at Pacific-Sierra Research (PSR) he created graphics for CD-ROM-based interactive training tool and created custom battlefield scenarios.\nWhile at Decision Science Applications (DSA), he designed promotional posters for Air Combat Simulation Software (TAC BRAWLER), and Helicopter Air-to-Air Value-Driven Engagement Model Simulation Software (HAVDEM). At AMS he illustrated various reports including the report for the Naval Medical Command's Artificial Intelligence in the Navy Medical Community Symposium held in Dublin, Ireland. At ROH he was responsible for developing system and equipment drawings for The U.S. Navy Towing Manual, The Space Shuttle Challenger Salvage Report, and The U.S. Navy Salvage History.

summary: M. Alex O. Vasilescu received her education at MIT and the University of Toronto. She was a research scientist at the MIT Media Lab from 2005–07 and at New York University’s Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences from 2001–05. She has pioneered the development of multilinear (tensor) algebra for computer vision, computer graphics, and machine learning. She has published papers in computer vision and computer graphics, particularly in the areas of face recognition, human motion analysis/synthesis, image-based rendering, and physics-based modeling (deformable models). She has given several invited talks and keynote addresses about her work and has several patents and patents pending. Her face recognition research, known as TensorFaces, has been funded by the TSWG, the Department of Defense’s Combating Terrorism Support Program, and by IARPA, Intelligence Advanced Research Projects Activity.  Her work was featured on the cover of Computer World, and in articles in the New York Times, Washington Times, etc.  MIT’s Technology Review Magazine named her to their TR100 List of Top 100 Young Innovators.\n\nM. Alex O. Vasilescu research on perceptual signatures distilled from biometric data is fundamental to human-centric technologies such as the burgeoning security industry, and when directed at ourselves, it can enhance our self-awareness, understanding, and health, and they can facilitate our interaction with each other and computers. \n\nContact Information: maov@cs.ucla.edu; maov@tensor-vision.com\n\nGoogle Scholar Citations: https://goo.gl/BaonBn\nQuora Profile:                  https://goo.gl/HOcd8M\nQuora Q&A: \nHow are tensor methods used in computer vision & machine learning? https://goo.gl/K9EZlB\nWhat is all the current fuss with tensor data analysis? \t                      https://goo.gl/qaX1U6

summary: I am an Instructor and Ph.D candidate in Human-Computer Interaction at Virginia Tech's Computer Science program. \n\nMy main longer-term research goal is to design and develop technologies and interactions that encourage others to build and work in the real world. I see so many people empowered by technology, and yet, there's a gap between learning from a computer screen and learning hands-on, in the real world. I want to explore how to encourage those who want to sew or build, but do not have the knowledge or resources yet to make the first step. \n\nSpecialties: I specialize in Human-Computer Interaction, DIY culture, maker spaces, 3D User Interfaces, Gaming Information Visualization, Multi-Touch/Pen Interfaces, and usability.

summary: Nearly thirty years ago I fell into graphic design purely by chance and proximity rather than intent, but it was love at first sight and there was no turning back. \n\nIn 1987 I landed a job as an engineering technician that would literally steer me head on into the world of graphic design.  I had already been producing maps, surveys and reports on tight deadlines and I loved it.  In 1991 I was asked to find the software and create a public service brochure on recycling, and oh yeah it had to be to the printer in two days. I love a challenge so it was game on and that's how it all started.\n\nMy passion and craft have grown leaps and bounds since that day but I knew I wanted more. I retired from the job that started it all and returned to college.  In 2016 I completed my associate degree in graphic design from the Art Institute of Pittsburgh - Online Division, and currently attending for my Bachelor's in graphic design as well .\n\nI love graphic design, but to define it in a traditional sense would be too limiting- it's somewhere between a quiet, intimate dinner  and an international rave party. Its a complex, harmonic visual language that unites the cerebral and the creative to  translate the intangible into a clean, contemporary design that evokes a powerful, emotional connection with the observer.\n\nCheers\n\nNancy \n\n Professional Membersips:\n\nAIGA - Professional Association of Design\nGraphic Design Guild\nRGD - Registered Graphic Designers, Student\nSociety of Illustrators

summary: My field of expertise is Image Processing, Color Science, High Dynamic Range Imaging, Color Appearance Modeling and advanced display technologies. \nI am engaged in developing color management models for both professional and consumer displays (dynamic range and gamut mapping concepts). This involves active research, code development and QA as well as applying metrological and psychophysical concepts for verification. I have carried out picture quality assessment and tuning for several display technologies from customers all over the world. Additionally, I have experience in neuroscience and psychological concepts related to the Human Visual System (signal processing in the retina and higher visual cortex).\n\nI have more than ten years of training in color and imaging science for display devices as well as pre-press and fine art printing. This is supported by more than 20 years of experience as landscape and architecture photographer for clients in several countries. \n\nFurther, I have a background in Physical Geosciences (Remote Sensing and geospatial image processing, GIS, Vegetation- and Ecosystem Modeling) and have worked in these fields with research departments at Lund University in Sweden, Lincoln University in New Zealand, and the University of Dar es Salaam in Tanzania.

summary: Among other things, Rachel considers herself an engineer, an artist and an educator. She's passionate about a mixture of technical and creative work, especially with applications in games.  Her computer science major and creative writing minor sum it up pretty well. She currently teaches a class at the University of Pennsylvania on procedural content generation in computer graphics (creative coding), of her own design. By day, she works as a 3D graphics engineer/developer advocate for Cesium, an open-source globe rendering platform. Rachel /loves/ games of all stripes -- board games, narrative games, strategy games and those special conversations that evolve into games of sorts. \n\nRachel recently graduated from the University of Pennsylvania with an MSE in Computer Graphics and Game Technology. Before that, she earned a BS in computer science, and a minor in creative writing at the University of Chicago. She also has background in linguistics, and is generally interested in computational linguistics, NLP and machine learning. Her favorite languages are C++ and Python. She is currently looking ways to get involved in video games as a technical craft and an art form.\n\nAway from the computer, Rachel enjoys playing games, origami, white-boarding algorithms, biking and collecting or inventing ridiculous science fiction scenarios for discussion. She also helps organize the world's largest scavenger hunt.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'We created a prequel to Thresh Wars on Facebook. We mainly wanted to build a fb game and learn the ropes, and dip our toe in the water. I developed the front-end (Flash/Flex), Ethan developed a completely new back-end, and Jim did the artwork. The results proved to be very similar to Thresh Wars and while we had a reasonable plan to get over the monetization hump, I was ready for something new.', u'title': u'TW2525 (Thresh Wars redux on fb)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008 ~ 2011', u'description': u'Thresh Wars was a turn-based strategy game that was inspired by Games Workshop. The game ran in a web browser (via Flash/Flex front-end + Rail backend). Every player started with a small army and earned credits to buy more units by winning single-player campaigns against an AI. A multi-player lobby enabled players to chat, strategize, and form teams to play against other player teams. We introduced premium units that could be purchased via game credits or cash.\nscreenshots: http://www.flickr.com/photos/rikk/sets/72157607718705795/\nblog: http:threshwars.wordpress.com\n\nPost-mortem: The game grew to ~50,000 players, but engagement levels stagnated, primarly due ot the synchronous turn-based mechanic (i.e. one slow player could ruin the battle). Monetization was very good, but the engagement issues prevented it from growing. We tried various common sense solutions to the synchronous problem (e.g. AI steps in to make a slow player's move), but we realized that asynchronous (e.g. KixEye) was a better business. In the end, we decided that it would be better to start from scratch on a new game than continue with the existing code base.', u'title': u'Thresh Wars game'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'We created a casual restaurant game for tagged.com. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'Human communication is much more than verbal. Our facial expression and eye movements also help convey important information about our feelings. In this exhibit we will be presenting custom built systems, which capture and use facial expressions and eye gaze to manipulate computer-generated characters and create emotionally expressive artwork.', u'title': u'Facial Expression and Eye Gaze in Computer Graphic'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'In this project we explore the possibility to use movement data from two fish, \u201cMarlin\u201d (Red fish) and\n\u201cDory\u201d (Blue fish) using a standard webcam while in their aquarium home. The fish are detected and tracked using standard webcam and computer vision algorithms. The fish movement data is mapped to two virtual animated fish (in real-time using computer graphics) in a 3D maze game.  The objective for the virtual fish is to complete the maze to escape into a virtual aquarium at each exit of the maze. Also we have a scary \u201cBruce\u201d the shark, which is hungry for some fish food. If any of the virtual fish complete the maze successfully the real-world fish (Marlin and Dory) will get fish treat for their hard work. If Bruce, the shark in the maze wins then the real-world fish do not get any treat and the game is reset. We track the win count of both Marlin and Dory and also keep a track of how many times Bruce got them.   \n\nThe project is an effort to combine computer vision, computer graphics and some specialized hardware to make a fish controlled 3D maze game.', u'title': u'Fishy Maze'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.5 ~ 2012.5', u'description': u'We present a novel gaze-based image retrieval application. The application is designed to be run on a dual monitor setup with a separate eye tracking device dedicated to each monitor. A source image is displayed on one monitor and the retrieved images are displayed on the second monitor. The system is completely gaze controlled. The user selects one or more objects or regions in the source image by fixating on them. The system then retrieves images containing similar objects from an image database. These are displayed in a grid on the second monitor. The user can then fixate on one of these images to select it as the new source image and the process can be repeated until a satisfactory image is found.', u'title': u'Gaze-Based Image Retrieval'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'We use real-time eye tracking to identify, track and recall objects in a given scene. Subject fixation data is used to capture information of the scene being viewed and relevant objects are identified from a database of known objects and the objects identity is recalled and information related to the object are presented to the user. This system is real-time and can sever as a useful technology in learning and educational environments.', u'title': u'Real-Time Gaze Based Object Recall'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.5 ~ 2014.5', u'description': u'Modern media recommendation systems work based on the content of videos previously seen. While this may work for the habitual viewer, it is not always appropriate for many users whose tastes change based on their moods. A lot can be gathered from a person\u2019s facial expression while they are engaged in an activity, for example by observing someone as they view a film, we can likely tell\nif they enjoyed it or not. While a content providing company may not have the resources to employ human observers to watch audiences (or the inclination to do so, because it is not a very appealing\nidea), an automatic system that does this would be more feasible. Photoplethysmography is a field in which a person\u2019s physiological details can be gathered optically without requiring any physical\ncontact with that person. By monitoring the intensity of light on a patch of the viewer\u2019s skin, we can accurately estimate their heart rate. Our system combines heart rate measurement and facial expressions to quantify how much a user enjoys a video.', u'title': u'An Affective Movie Rating System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.5 ~ 2014.5', u'description': u'Keyboard and mouse are outdated and gesture based systems are becoming more pervasive. Its more intuitive to use gestures and for some applications (esp. Games) it is more natural to use gestures to interact with a computer. In this demonstration we use a Microsoft Kinect to play Rock-Paper-Scissors game with computer. We also show the ability of users to interact with the video and images using their hands. This highlights the practical uses of gesture based recognition system in the real world. This also shows the ease to configure gestures to control and seamlessly interact with computer applications.', u'title': u'Gesture Recognition-Based Kinect Game'}]

summary: I am working as an Imaging Data Scientist at DuPont Pioneer, Johnston IA.\n\nI did my Ph.D. at Rochester Institute of Technology, NY (RIT), under the guidance of Dr. Reynold Bailey. My research interests are in Applied Visual Perception in Computer Vision and Computer Graphics, Predictive Analytics, Machine Learning, and Gaze-Based Computer Interactions. My dissertation mainly focused on understanding human visual perception, with special focus on gaze prediction, gaze guidance and real-world task inference. I have developed a comprehensive model of human visual attention prediction that incorporates, scene context, scene saliency, task at hand and eye movement data to predict the distribution of a viewer's gaze on a given scene. summary: You can call me a jack of all trades...or at least the trades that interest me. I never found something that I was passionate about that I didn't dive into head first (It’s a blessing and curse). Through my professional career I have done a variety of jobs. Each one teaching me something different that has helped me get to where I am today. From painting graffiti in my high school years, to programming and selling my own software, I am passionate about creating, and my passion knows no bounds as long as the curiosity is there. \n\nIn the last 17 years I have taken my varied experiences and used them to help organizations create better experiences for people. From creating better products and services to the marketing that promotes them . I have helped those organizations win awards, get talked about in the press, and even patent new technology . My goals today are the same goals I had painting graffiti as a teenager. Make things that people will talk about: work that I can be proud of, and work for a place that has purpose greater than just making money.\n\n\nFull Portfolio available upon request.\n\nSpecialties: Ideation, Strategy, Technology, Product Development, Graphic Design, Leadership, Mentorship, Entrepreneur, Going above and beyond the call of duty, Saying the things no one wants to say, Honesty, Passion, Undying need to do things differently for the sake of constantly evolving myself, my team, and the brands I work for.

summary: Professor Kenny Mitchell is head Interactive Graphics at Disney Research Los Angeles (DRLA) and Edinburgh (DREd) providing practical technology solutions for Disney. Over the past 20 years he has shipped video games using high-end graphics technologies including voxels, volumetric light scattering, motion blur and curved surfaces. His Ph.D. introduced the use of real-time 3D for information visualization on consumer hardware, including a novel recursive perspective projection technique. In between contributing to Split Second, Spielberg's Boom Blox (BAFTA winner), and the Harry Potter franchise games he is involved in developing new intellectual properties. His work serves Disney Interactive, Feature Animation, Consumer Products, and Imagineering, Pixar, ILM/Lucasfilm and many successful funded University collaborations. He is the most senior Disney research representative managing the UK lab, he is based in LA. Contact him on drkennymitchell at yahoo dot com.\n\nSpecialties: 3D graphics, vision, visualisation, real-time, video games. DirectX, OpenGL, CUDA, OpenCL. iPhone, PC, console & online.

summary: At VMware I'm part of the OCTO developing infrastructure technologies for large scale Industrial IoT systems. Prior, I worked on UI remoting technology, GPU virtualization & novel approaches to Cloud-Native multi-device applications. Before VMware, I was an independent consultant for 7 years, I served in an engineering management capacity at Microsoft for 9 years, Sun Microsystems for 6 & RPI for 5.\n\nI am passionate towards the design & development of digital life solutions that improve people's lives through simplicity, elegant design & ease of use.\n\nI'm the founding chairman of the UPnP Forum in October 1999. I chaired its steering committee for four years, while growing it to a successful international consortium. There are more than 2B certified UPnP devices at this point, including: PCs, smart TVs and Internet gateways.\n\nI founded & led an advanced development team at Sun that conceived the TBAG graphics & multimedia system that was presented at Siggraph '94 & later refined into Internet graphics products at Microsoft.\n\nI developed the algorithmic & mathematical formulation for the graphical processing of Trimmed NURB surfaces as part of my Ph.D. work at RPI & later refined the technology into industrial products at Sun including GPU accelerated processing.\n\nI participated in the development of the PHIGS 3D graphics standard starting in 1984 & later the PHIGS+ extension. I led its first implementation on the IBM-5080 graphics terminal & the development of a hardware engine using PC grade components including the Weitek floating-point chip set.\n\nI presented in international conferences including WinHEC, PDC, Siggraph & Eurographics. I've authored a couple dozen technical papers -- with three award winners; see http://www.abiezzi.com/Salim/publications. I was awarded a dozen patents; see below.\n\nI completed a PhD & MS in CS from RPI & a BS in CS from UMass Lowell, summa cum laude, at age 19, which led to a Graduate Assistantship at RPI.

summary: Main website for research work: www.folleymarie.com \n\nBackground:\nFrom 1998 to 2004 I was with Brown University where I co-founded the SHAPE Laboratory, devoted to the study of digital modeling with applications to archaeology and cultural heritage [www.lems.brown.edu/shape/]. I am still attached to the SHAPE Lab and held a Visiting (adjunct) Professorship in Engineering at Brown from 2007 to the end of 2009. \nIn 2004, I crossed the Atlantic once more and joined Goldsmiths College part of the University of London, where I first initiated and ran a graduate program in Arts Computing until 2007. This MSc at the frontier of perception, realism, imagination and digital creativity has now become an MFA in computational Studio Arts. In 2008 I introduced together with William Latham (whom I brought to Goldsmiths) a new MSC in Computer Games and Entertainment.\nIn recent times, I am developing a mathematical language for shape representation with potential for applications in various domains and industries, from the Arts and Performance areas to Biology, Medicine, Computer Aided Design (CAD), Architecture, and more [www.aikon-gold.com , www.foldsynth.com, www.bioblox.org , www.doc.gold.ac.uk/morpholingua]\nOn the topic of serious games and gamification, I was invited keynote on the topic at Trento University (March 2014; https://youtu.be/3tozFqDQp7w ), I co-lead the development and release in 2015 of the on-line math+physics game Age of Algorithms [www.ageofalgo.com], commissioned by Creative Skillset and developed by London Geometry Ltd. (LG) for which FFL is co-director. On-going work in leading the development of a protein docking game was presented at BiVi (Edinburg, 2015), VizBi (Germany, 2016) and Imperial Festival (London, 2016) and will be on show at the up-coming New Scientist Live (London, Excel, end of Sept. 2017): www.bioblox.org .\n

ElimiQuest\n* -- Block A Shot\n* -- Alley Oop\n* -- Give & Go\n* -- Bang the Boards\n* -- Numerous NBA themed Pinball Tables such as Away Game and B-Ball Bot\n* -- Own The Court\n* Wrote promotional posts on the Playstation Blog and responded to consumer questions and comments.', u'title': u'NBA Series on Playstation Portable'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006 ~ 2007', u'description': u'High Velocity Bowling was released through the Playstation Network and featured unique motion controls using the DualShock 3 and realistic physics simulations for bowling balls, spin, lane oil patterns and pin collisions.\n\nIt was later re-released with Playstation Move motion controls and support for 3D compatible TVs.\n\nJosh Hart's Responsibilities:\n* Conceived of and Proposed the innovative way to hold the Playstation DualShock 3 controller to best simulate holding a bowling ball.\n* Designed and implemented many of the downloadable Trick Shot packs.\n* Wrote the commentary for various characters to say while bowling.\n* Worked with the audio team to cast and direct some of the voice actors.\n* Assisted the Producer with scheduling and design of new features such as: \n* -- Head-to-Head Online Play\n* -- Voice Chat\n* -- Weekly Leaderboards\n* -- New DLC Characters and Balls\n* -- Playstation Trophies\n* -- Trick Shot Packs\n* -- Custom Music Playlists\n* Wrote promotional posts on the Playstation Blog and responded to consumer questions and comments.', u'title': u'High Velocity Bowling'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010 ~ 2011', u'description': u'ModNation Racers: Road Trip was a launch title for the Playstation Vita.  It is a highly customizable kart racing game which allows players to create their own riders (Mods), karts and even tracks.\n\nJosh Hart's Responsibilities:\n* Designed and implemented new tracks utilizing the in-game level editor.\n* Collaborated with other designers on the development of new tracks, weapons and game modes.\n* Collaborated with other designers and programmers on the new touch-capable level editor.\n* Designed and implemented new game modes including:\n* -- Asynchronous, competitive Ghost races.\n* -- Leaderboards and new ways to sort them including by players' locations.\n* -- Mod Pictures (uses the Vita's cameras to put the player's Mods and Karts into the real world).\n* -- Mod Traveler (uses the Vita's location data to earn points as you travel).\n* -- Mod Explorer (uses the Vita's location data to check-in at certain hotspots to unlock content).\n* -- Support for the Playstation Vita's innovative \', u'title': u'ModNation Racers: Road Trip'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009 ~ 2010', u'description': u'Pinball Heroes is a mix-and-match set of games that feature pinball tables based on your favorite PlayStation games! Each table has its own set of unique table rules, game modes and more to keep you on your toes.  There are 2 Bundles with 4 tables in each.\n\nTables are themed on various Playstation Franchises including: Uncharted, High Velocity Bowling, Hot Shots Golf, Pain, WipeOut, MotorStorm, Fat Princess and ModNation Racers.\n\nPinball Heroes was ported to the Sony Tablet S and to the Playstation Vita.\n\nJosh Hart's Responsibilities:\n* Designed and implemented 5 of the 8 Pinball Heroes Tables: High Velocity Bowling, Pain, Hot Shots Golf, MotorStorm and ModNation Racers.\n* -- Designed the gameplay for each table based on its featured game.  For example, the MotorStorm Pinball Heroes table features 8 ways to traverse the ramps based on the 8 tracks featured in the PS3 game, MotorStorm.\n* -- Created, tested and tuned the gameplay logic for each pinball table.\n* -- Worked with the lead programmer to improve the pinball logic editor.\n* -- Learned to edit each pinball table's logic using .XML.\n* -- Worked with the artist to fulfill all of the requirements for each table including changes to gameplay using a table's collision map.\n* -- Worked with the audio team to implement sfx, music and voices from the featured game into each of the pinball tables.\n* Wrote promotional posts on the Playstation Blog and responded to consumer questions and comments.', u'title': u'Pinball Heroes PSP'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1999 ~ 2000', u'description': u'Smuggler's Run is an open world, off-road racing game involving taking and delivering packages.  It was developed by Angel Studios and published by Rockstar Games.\n\nJosh Hart's Responsibilities: \n* Assisting the Producer and the Lead Designer as well as performing various Quality Assurance tasks.', u'title': u'Smuggler's Run'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2000 ~ 2001', u'description': u'Test Drive: Off-Road Wide Open is an open world off-road racing game featuring multiple locations with numerous vehicles and upgrades.  It was developed by Angel Studios and published by Infogrames.\n\nJosh Hart's Responsibilities:\n* Created the initial Game Design Document.\n* Led a small team of level designers and supervised their creations.\n* Provided physics and camera tuning for all of the vehicles and their upgrades.\n* Tweaked and tuned the 2 basic types of vehicles (Power vs. Speed) so that they play differently while still allowing each type to be a viable choice for players on every track.\n* Designed tracks and manipulated terrain geometry to allow the 2 vehicle types to have an equal chance of success.\n* Implemented, tested and tweaked AI paths for races.\n* Worked with Producers, Artists and Sound Designers on all aspects of the game's development.', u'title': u'Test Drive: Off-Road Wide Open'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.6 ~ 2013.7', u'description': u'Created a web app that allows the user to view BVH Motion Capture files. A BVH file specifies the position and movement of joints, and this viewer allows users to view and play any BVH file on the web. Different BVH files tend to have different formats, so a lot of testing was done to make sure all types of BVH files were accounted for. Used technologies were JavaScript, WebGL, three.js.', u'title': u'BVH File Viewer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2014.1', u'description': u'Selected as one of six finalist teams from a pool of 231 applicants in Walt Disney Imagineering's annual design competition.\n\nWorked in a team of four in the conception, development, and theoretical implementation of a fully-functional, immersive experience at Istanbul, Turkey, adhering to a deliberately open prompt: \', u'title': u'Disney ImagiNations Finalist'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.6 ~ now', u'description': u'DORA is an immersive teleoperated robotic platform designed for navigation and exploration of remote locations. Through the use of a VR head mounted display such as the Oculus Rift DK2, the system can mimic the head movements of the user, while providing visual feedback through two cameras mounted on the head of the robot. The project won first place in the annual engineering competition Intel Cornell Cup, and got covered by media outlets such as The Wall Street Journal, Popular Science, IEEE Spectrum and IGN.\n\nThe system is made up of a 3 Degrees of Freedom head gimbal that tracks the orientation of the user, along with a 3 Degrees of Freedom translation stage system that tracks the user's head position. In addition, the gimbal and stages sit on a mobile base that the user can control with a standard game controller. All of these systems are wireless. We've also made a clean graphical user interface envisioning the future of this system, where a user can sign in and then choose a location to go to, to connect to the robot stationed at that location. ', u'title': u'DORA - Dexterous Observational Roving Automaton'}]

summary: Recently graduated from CPE Lyon, I have a Master's degree in Computer Science. I am passionate about computer vision, robotics and new technologies. \n\nI worked during one year on computer vision and robotics for Robert Bosch GmbH, located in Hildesheim, Germany. In September 2015, I moved to Oregon to gain skills in deep learning and to improve my computer vision expertise at Oregon State University. I deeply believe that computer vision and deep learning will be indivisible in the future. I did my master thesis at Novumind Inc, working on computer vision applications for autonomous navigation of airbones vehicles in 2016. So, I decided to create a game completely by myself and see what happens. I am pleased with the results (both dusting off my coding skills and the game design), and its now in the App Store. Mission accomplished! :-)', u'title': u'XO Football (iOS game)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1996 ~ 1996', u'description': u'An extension to Open Inventor for the chemistry markets.', u'title': u'Molecular Inventor'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1990 ~ 1998', u'description': u'Conceived and led project with Paul Strauss at SGI. This eventually led to us creating VRML.', u'title': u'Open Inventor 3D Framework'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'We created a prequel to Thresh Wars on Facebook. We mainly wanted to build a fb game and learn the ropes, and dip our toe in the water. I developed the front-end (Flash/Flex), Ethan developed a completely new back-end, and Jim did the artwork. The results proved to be very similar to Thresh Wars and while we had a reasonable plan to get over the monetization hump, I was ready for something new.', u'title': u'TW2525 (Thresh Wars Origins on fb)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008 ~ 2011', u'description': u'We created this SyFy turn-based strategy game. It was inspired by Games Workshop real-world miniatures and table-top gaming. The game ran in a web browser (via Flash/Flex front-end + Rails backend). Every player started with a small army and earned credits to buy more units by winning single-player campaigns against an AI. A multi-player lobby enabled players to chat, strategize, and play with teams of up to 5 players in PvP games. We introduced premium units that could be purchased via game credits or cash.\n\nscreenshots: http://www.flickr.com/photos/rikk/sets/72157607718705795/\nblog: http:threshwars.wordpress.com\n\nPost-mortem: The game grew to ~50,000 players, but engagement levels stagnated, primarly due ot the synchronous turn-based mechanic (i.e. one slow player could ruin the battle). Monetization was very good, but the engagement issues prevented it from growing. We tried various common sense solutions to the synchronous problem (e.g. AI steps in to make a slow player's move), but we realized that asynchronous (e.g. KixEye) was a better business. In the end, we decided that it would be better to start from scratch on a new game than continue with the existing code base.', u'title': u'Thresh Wars game'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'While at SGI, our team conceived and developed VRML (Virtual Reality Modeling Language). This included the public spec, various run-time implementations and authoring systems. We were too early.', u'title': u'VRML'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.4 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'This dual project is our final project for Computer Graphics, a senior design course at Cal. We implemented a ray tracer renderer with 'photon mapping' technique to achieve various realistic effects and a physical based simulator for cloth using finite element methods. Most importantly, the data from our cloth simulator can be serialized into our ray tracer renderer to produce high quality images.\n\nRenderer Showcase: yanzhao.me/project/ray_tracer\nSimulator Showcase: yanzhao.me/project/cloth_sim\n\nMy role involved:\n\xb7 Simulates stretching and sheering force with energy condition method by Professor David Baraff.\n\xb7 Simulates bending force with edge spring method described by Professor Robert Bridson.\n\xb7 Implements sphere and cube collision detection/correction, as well as effects of aerodynamic force\n\xb7 Implements functionality to visually present each particle based on applied physical force.\n\xb7 Implements axis-aligned bounding boxes to accelerate the render speed to log asymptotically fast.\n\xb7 Implements MC method in multiple sampling on each single pixel to achieve anti-aliasing effect.', u'title': u'Cloth Simulation with Finite Element Method & Global Illumination Renderer with Photon Mapping in C++'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.4', u'description': u'Implements K-Means clustering algorithm with CUDA, and support Numpy interface.', u'title': u'K-Means clustering with Cuda and Python interface'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'PeakDemand is a product from one of my senior design course at Cal. PeakDemand is aiming to alleviate the alleviate the communication cost between resource providers and resource consumers within the EECS department regarding to computing resources (Cluster, Printer, etc).\n\nShowcase: yanzhao.me/project/peakdemand \nGithub: github.com/zhaoyan1117/PeakDemand \n\nMy role involved:\n\xb7 Work on back end logic including database schema design, RESTful controller implementation.\n\xb7 Implement front end Ajax component with jQuery for demand detail twitter-bootstrap modal.\n\xb7 Keep test coverage beyond 95%, set up Code Climate report, Travis-CI, and Pivotal Tracker.\n\xb7 Contribute back to an open-source gem that is used to integrate with Google calendar services.\n\xb7 Serve as scrum master: including organizing team activities, creating user stories with customers.', u'title': u'PeakDemand: SaaS to record future demands for resources to help scheduling with RoR'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Side product of me learning neural network; also an admiration to the great caffe (http://caffe.berkeleyvision.org/).\n\nUsage demo:\nyanzhao.me/ipython/nnet.html', u'title': u'Artificial Neural Network implemented with Python and Cuda'}]

I have become proficient in programs such as the Adobe Master Suite and Autodesk Suite. These programs include professional software such as Photoshop, Illustrator, Premiere Pro, After Effects, InDesign, 3DS Max, Maya, and MotionBuilder.\nI have a strong passion for art and great attention to detail. I like to apply my skills in photo manipulation and 3D modeling whenever I get inspired by other great works or my own ideas. If you would like to see more of my work, than please feel free to visit my website wburdick.com where I post my work.

summary: I've been at Pixar since 1993, when I was a summer intern, and full-time since 1995.  Originally, I was the NYC office of Pixar, while my wife worked in Manhattan.  I did R&D for our (now defunct) Interactive Division for Pam Kerwin.  Sometime in 1997 I moved over to report directly to Pixar co-founder Ed Catmull, then CTO, and continued to do R&D work.  In 1997 we moved to Chicago so my wife could go to grad school at the Institute of Design at IIT and I became the Chicago office of Pixar.  Finally, in 1999, we moved out to the Bay Area, where I moved into the Studio Tools Group at Pixar.  \n\nI've written tools for most parts of our pipeline, but for the last twelve years I've been working on tools for the early part of film development pipeline; especially in Story, Editorial, Art and Production Management.  \n\nI still oversee the Story & Editorial pipeline, but am currently trying to understand the best way to jumpstart the process of quickly building the prototypes of our films. It's a hard, subtle, complicated problem. Anyone who tells you otherwise is lying.\n\nSpecialties: interaction design, information architecture, application design, social engineering, triage, public speaking, plumbing, debugging

summary: I've spent 6+ years developing software and providing frontline support for production pipelines for animated feature films and VFX. I'm currently the lead designer and engineer for an end-to-end production pipeline for lightfield VR using the Lytro Immerge VR Camera.\n\nMy strength is primarily software engineering in Python, and I have been working professionally as an embedded software engineer and technical consultant for several artist groups in Python-centric pipelines for over six years in the animation and VFX industry.\n\nI've spent significant amounts of my own develop doing android development in Java. Troubleshooting and hobbyist pursuits have required me to dive into some C++ or C# code as well. I've also scripted in TCL, Lua and TCSH. I've worked quite a bit with both SQL and NoSQL databases. I also worked for nearly two years doing primarily PHP/HTML/CSS/JavaScript development.\n\nI really building things, breaking down complex problems and solving them one piece at a time, and coming up with innovate solutions that push workflows and possibilities forward.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2008.8 ~ now', u'description': u'CVR is a software framework, based on OGRE 3D, for the development of immersive collaborative virtual reality applications with emphasis on full-body interaction with virtual humans. The framework is designed to be scalable and adaptable to different hardware con\ufb01gurations, using either commodity or more expensive hardware setups.\nHigh level programming abstractions handle object replication and communication channels for con\ufb01gurations based on multiple rendering nodes. The system provides tools for full-body character\nanimation, real-time full-body tracking and retargeting to virtual humans, including motion reconstruction from a small set of sensors. Such capabilities allow new full-body interaction metaphors to be developed in \ufb01xed or user-perspective stereo visualization.\nThe framework is scalable, customizable, cross-platform and it is only based on tools with source code available', u'title': u'CVR Framework'}]

summary: I am a Computer Graphics Engineer/R&D at Avametric. My primary role consists on designing, developing and maintaining the micro services based rendering and simulation platform at Avametric. The system is based on the growing virtualization open platform for distributed applications  Docker/Kubernetes.\n\nI completed my PhD at the University of California, Merced in 2015 in Computer Graphics and Animation. My thesis, titled `Immersive Virtual Human Training Systems based on Direct Demonstration`, analyzes the effectiveness of avatars as human trainers in monitored, feedback-based, virtual environments for training and learning where human-oriented motion skills are key to the learning material. My thesis addresses the challenge of designing such training systems with the approach of motion modeling by direct demonstration and relying on immersive motion capture interfaces. The proposed concepts were applied to the application of delivering monitored upper-body physical therapy.\n\nBefore joining UC Merced, I was a research associate at the National Research Council of Italy (ITABC), where I developed different applications for virtual heritage projects, which are now in exposition in international museums. \n\nI graduated in Computer Science (M.S.) in 2005 at the University of Bologna with a thesis in 3D virtual environments over the web (OSG4Web). This work was developed in collaboration with the largest Italian non-profit computing center CINECA.\n\nMy primary interests are in 3D visualization, virtual reality, computer animation and simulation. \n\nSpecialties: Computer graphics, computer animation, motion tracking and capturing systems, virtual reality, collaborative virtual environments, software engineering and development, 3D visualization, 3D data post-processing, 3D modeling, computational geometry, visual effects, movie post-production.

summary: My current research focuses on the interdisciplinary digital design of sustainable architecture and computer graphics. I work on advanced numeric simulations that derive a building’s daylighting behavior, thermal performance, and material properties. I develop novel approaches for simulating, manipulating, and physically realizing sustainable designs in all phases of a building’s lifecycle. This research directly impacts smart-building design, early-stage design, and retrofitting buildings. I also work on high dimensional light transport problems, such as complex illumination, material appearance, physically-based simulation, and spectral rendering, which facilitate a unique approach to provide both more accurate simulations and efficient algorithms for simulating sustainable architecture and smart buildings.

summary: I'm currently a Research Engineer at Snap Research. Previously I was a Senior Research Engineer at Activision Central Tech. Prior to that, I worked as a postdoc researcher at UBC and USC with Prof. Alla Sheffer and Prof. Hao Li respectively. I obtained my Ph.D. in Computer Science from Institute for Advanced Study of Tsinghua University in 2012, and received my B.S. in Mathematics and Physics from Fundamental Science Class of Tsinghua University in 2007. My research focuses on visual content creation, including but not limited to motion capture, human digitization, face tracking, data-driven 3D reconstruction and animation, digital geometry processing and texture synthesis.
