projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.7 ~ 2015.7', u'description': u'Winner of \', u'title': u'Bounties - Star Wars: Commander Hack-a-thon 2015'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Implemented an interactive deferred shader on the GPU using WebGl. Features Blinn-Phong shading, optional bloom and toon shading effects, scissor test culling for point lights, and material defined specular exponents.', u'title': u'WebGL Based Deferred Shader - CIS-565 GPU Programming and Architecture Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.7 ~ 2015.7', u'description': u'An extension of Commander's existing \', u'title': u'Droid Parts - Star Wars: Commander Hack-a-thon 2015'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'Implemented a real-time GPU-based Forward+ renderer based on the paper Forward+: Bringing Deferred Rendering to the Next Level by Takahiro Harada, Jay McKee, and Jason C. Yang in C++ and OpenGL. Our implementation uses OpenGL compute shaders to perform a light culling stage. In this stage we divide the screen into tiles and determine which lights are visible in each tile. In the final shading calculations, we only consider lights that passed the previous culling stage for that fragment's tile. In testing, our Forward+ method showed a 53x performance increase over a naive Forward rendering implementation in a scene featuring 1024 point lights. The average frame rate jumped from 1.7 to 89.8 frames per second.\n\nAdditional features include high dynamic range lighting with Reinhard tone mapping, tangent space normal mapping, interactive controls, and support for complex model loading using Assimp.', u'title': u'Forward+ Renderer - CIS-565 GPU Programming and Architecture Final Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'An augmented reality based real-time strategy multiplayer game for iOS and Android using Unity, C#, and Qualcomm's Vuforia SDK. Players can project the game onto a tabletop using their device as a viewfinder to observe the play space from different angles and call in airstrikes on enemy units and buildings. Players compete to control territory in order to gain advantages such as placing troops and faster movement speed. The first player to destroy their opponent's base wins.\nI implemented networked multiplayer, combat, and AI systems.', u'title': u'ConqAR - CIS-568 Game Design Practicum Final Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Implemented a 3D Semi-Lagrangian smoke fluid simulation using the Navier-Stokes equations and a marker-and-cell (MAC) grid in C++ and rendered in real-time using OpenGL. Velocity, density, and temperature are advected onto the smoke particles and buoyancy and vorticity confinement external forces are applied on the system. Incompressibility is maintained by doing a pressure solve using a conjugate gradient solver and then projecting it onto the system.\n\nMy implementation is based off the SIGGRAPH 2007 Course Notes on Fluid Simulation by Robert Bridson and Matthias M\xfcller.', u'title': u'3D Smoke Fluid Simulation - CIS-563 Physically Based Animation Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.7 ~ 2015.7', u'description': u'A system allowing players to earn cosmetic upgrades to their avatar to incentivize elder game PvP content. Inspired by Diablo 3's Paragon system, players earn a rank based on the number of total PvP battles they've won. The higher their rank, the more complex their avatar icon becomes. The project ultimately became a feature in the live game. I designed and implemented the system, including a utility to check and display the ranking of players, displaying a celebration when a new upgrade is earned, handling returning user flow for cases when an upgrade is earned while the player is offline, and methods to assist QA testing.', u'title': u'Faction Icon Upgrades - Star Wars: Commander Hack-a-thon 2015'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2015.9', u'description': u'Implemented an interactive GPU accelerated path tracer with support for diffuse, specular, mirrored, and refractive surfaces. Additional features include depth of field, motion blur, and work efficient stream compaction. Implementation details of each feature and performance results can be found on the project's GitHub repository.', u'title': u'CUDA Based Path Tracer - CIS-565 GPU Programming and Architecture Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Implemented an interactive GPU accelerated rasterizer. The project uses a scanline rasterization technique and can render obj models using triangle, line, or point primitives. Additional features include interactive mouse controls, backface culling, scissor test culling, and color and normal interpolation to support smooth models.', u'title': u'CUDA Based Rasterizer - CIS-565 GPU Programming and Architecture Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'Developed a real-time fluid solid coupling simulation in C++ based on the paper Unified Particle Physics for Real-Time Applications by Miles Macklin, Matthias M\xfcller, Nuttapong Chentanez, and Tae-Yong Kim. The system can simulate rigid bodies and fluids simultaneously using a particle representation and a mass-weighted version of Position Based Fluids. To represent rigid bodies, particles are held in the correct configuration by shape matching constraints. Interaction between fluids of differing densities is supported, as is buoyancy for rigid body objects. Neighbor search for particle-particle collision detection is sped up by using a Spatial Hash Grid. The simulation is multithreaded using Intel's Threading Building Blocks (TBB) library.', u'title': u'Paanipuri: Real-Time Fluid Solid Coupling Simulation - CIS-563 Physically Based Animation Final Project'}]

summary: I graduated from Purdue University, where I earned a Bachelors of Science in Computer Graphics Technology, with a minor in Organizational Leadership and Supervision. I am an experienced front-end web designer with a strong grasp of HTML and CSS, as well as experience working in a wide variety of content management systems, including SharePoint, Drupal, Wordpress, and Joomla.\n\nFollowing my university studies I enrolled in and completed an 18 month program at Animation Mentor, where I earned a Certificate in Advanced Studies in Character Animation. I have taken numerous foundation courses in Maya, giving me experience in 3D modeling, texturing and lighting, rigging, and animation.\n\nI'm very much a detail-oriented perfectionist, and have a passion for finding the optimal design solution for my clients. summary: I am currently the sign maker and flyer designer at NEX JEB Little Creek.I am also a freelance Graphic Designer and digital illustrator. Personal and Business logos, book and magazine layout, web design or anything you might want designed for your business or personal use. My professional approach to designing what you want involves a collaboration of both me and the client coming up with the ideas that would best represent your business in a professional look and marketing appeal. \n \nDesigner, print and web/interactive.\n I enjoy designing just about anything for businesses or web pages.  The web would probably be the more lucrative and advancing field but, I’d still like the projects of designing and creating posters business packages, commercial advertising, etc.  Since I was a kid, I’ve always found commercial art to be just as creative and cool in a sense that most people just look at it and take it for granted.  \n\nMotion Graphics/Video Editor.  \nSince taking a couple of classes in Video Techniques and Motion Graphics,  I’ve found that I really enjoy doing all the aspects of creating and editing.  The creation of a project starting with it’s idea inception, filming, laying audio and editing the project to it’s final cut is just an incredible experience.  And something that I also thoroughly enjoyed.\n\nHere is the link to my digital portfolio on my wordpress page.\n\nhttp://ajvavrek.files.wordpress.com/2014/05/vavrek_presentation_portfolio_web.pdf\n\nAnd you can also check out some of my work and non digital projects on Behance at\n\nhttps://www.behance.net/AjVavrek\n\nAnd on Facebook\n\nwww.facebook.com/ajvavrekGD\n\nI can also e-mail a pdf file if you would prefer.\n\nThanks for looking!

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.2 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'I implemented an algorithm to detect when and where a foot is down to the ground. Based on this detection algorithm, I implemented a foot-skating cleanup algorithm for motion capture editing, and embedded this functionality into the motion representation and synthesis in function space.', u'title': u'Motion representation and synthesis in function space (collaborated)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.10 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'We proposed a novel surface remeshing method based on minimal angle elimination, which is the first in literature that can explicitly bound both the approximation error and element quality (Expressed as minimal angle), while preserving features implicitly. Since a variety of applications such as FEA and 3D printing require both the mesh quality and geometry fidelity to be controllable, our method is extremely useful in such applications.', u'title': u'Robust surface remeshing'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.1 ~ 2012.7', u'description': u'As a team leader, I led the team members and accomplished the following aspects:\n1) Designed and implemented a retrieval system platform, and built up the parts and assemblies retrieval  benchmarks for public reuse;\n2) Proposed and implemented a parts retrieval methods based on typical face matching which is more functionality-oriented than existing methods;\n3) Proposed and implemented a best view selection algorithm for CAD parts which is effective for generating isometric views for CAD models;\n4) Proposed and implemented the first light-weighted assembly retrieval algorithm and system using Vector Space Model (VSM).', u'title': u'Content-based 3D CAD components retrieval'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2016.5', u'description': u'In this collaborated project, I did the following things:\n1) Proposed and implemented a bilateral farthest point sampling algorithm for particle tracking, using Kd-tree and CGAL infrastructures;\n2) Implemented an algorithm to uniformly sample on a discrete mesh model with sample numbers and spacing constraints, for sensor placement;\n3) Designed and implemented the algorithms for saliency estimation, shape correspondence and interaction transfer using our interaction descriptor.', u'title': u'Understanding and exploiting object interaction landscape (collaborated)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.2 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'We proposed a simple yet effective point descriptor, called 3D Laplacian Pyramid Signature (3DLPS), by extending and adapting the Laplacian Pyramid defined in 2D images to 3D shapes. We show that this point signature potentially benefit the applications involved in shape analysis, especially in point correspondence detection, best view selection and automatic mesh segmentation.', u'title': u'Robust 3D shape signatures'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2007.8 ~ 2009.12', u'description': u'As a team leader, I led the team members and accomplished the following things:\n1) Designed and implemented the data exchange algorithms for CAD parts based based on B-rep in the geometry-modeling system (TiGEMS);\n2) Extended the IGES representation schema for CAD assembly so that the mating conditions can be exchanged between CAD systems;\n3) Proposed and implemented a production rule-based algorithm for assembly data exchange which is compatible with commercial CAD systems.', u'title': u'The data exchange theory and implementation of CAD componenets'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.5 ~ 2016.5', u'description': u'We are investigating how to panelize a 3D surface model with a set of given tiles, and optionally some constraints. The applications includes fabrications, building constructions, shape approximations and so on. The techniques that are used include optimization methods, shape matching, registration...', u'title': u'Shape panelization with 3D surface tiles'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2016.6', u'description': u'1) For 3D reconstruction from a set of tilted images, I implemented the WBP and SIRT 3D reconstruction methods along with image alignment, for the micro-structure analysis of batteries.\n2) For 3D synthesis, I improved the 3D volume data synthesis algorithm from orthogonal images with Markov Random Filed assumption, and designed and implemented a method to extract the particles from the volume data, with Marching cubes and edge-weld algorithms.', u'title': u'3D model reconstruction and synthesis from images'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.7 ~ 2016.7', u'description': u'We are developing the applications that combine the virtual reality techniques (Oculus RIFT, Google Cardboard, Sumsung Gear VR, etc.) and haptic interactions for efficient sports training. We have implemented three prototype systems for football, taekwondo and visual training during the SURF program at Purdue University.', u'title': u'Haptic virtual reality for sports training'}]

summary: Bryan Bentley is currently working as a creature technical director for the Industrial Light and Magic(ILM) division of Lucas Film Entertainment, in Singapore. Before moving to ILM Singapore he worked at ILM's main branch  in San Francisco on Rango, which went on to win the Oscar for Best Animated Film. Previouse to working at ILM he worked at Rhythm & Hues studios, in Los Angeles, on the Golden Compass, which won the academy award for best visual effects, Alvin and the Chipmunks which has the 5th highest Christmas opening in cinema history, and HULK a revision of one of marvel comics most popular franchises. \n\nBryan has a Bachelors in science from Purdue University and in Fine Arts from Savannah College of Art and Design. At Purdue University he was awarded the black caucus and faculty award twice and made the deans list. Also while attending Purdue Bryan was granted to opportunity to tech at the collegiate level at the University of Technology in Rezerwowe Poland. He spent three months teaching Design Theory with 3d and 2d applications such as, 3D studio max, Alias Maya, and Adobe Photoshop and Adobe Illustrator.  He later parlayed this experience in to numerous peer tutoring and lectures throughout his collegiate career. He is currentley also a Part-Time Professor at Nanyang Technological University in Singapre, were he teches an introduction to character rigging course.\n\nSpecialties: Rigging, Cloth Simulation, Python Programming, Rigid Simulation and geometry fractureing for Destruction.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2010.8 ~ 2010.9', u'description': u'A particle system which uses an attractor force that pulls particles to a respective position in space. These positions were based off vertex positions from an obj object.', u'title': u'Particle System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.10 ~ 2010.11', u'description': u'The scene is a 4-sided room containing a polished gold metallic sphere, polished copper metallic teapot, and polished silver metallic torus. I created an interface control which allows switching between vertex Gouraud shading and per-pixel Phong shading.', u'title': u'Phong Shading, Garoud Shading (GLSL)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008.4 ~ 2008.5', u'description': u'Ray tracer scene containing a sphere and a triangle. Implemented simple phong lighting (ambient, diffuse, specular model) and also casts shadows.', u'title': u'Ray Tracer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.11 ~ 2010.11', u'description': u'The scene contains a bump-mapped floor and a bump-mapped swimming fish. The fish is a cylinder which has been warped using a vertex program. The \u201cwriggles\u201d of the fish body are simulated using a sin wave which starts from the fish midline towards the tail. This animation is controlled using an interface which allows the user to vary the \u201cwriggles\u201d speed. There is also an interface control to switch from phong shading to toon-shading.', u'title': u'Bump Mapped Swimming Fish (GLSL)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.11 ~ 2010.12', u'description': u'This is a shader implementation of Real-Time Hatching, Praun et al. [2001]. The scene contains a real-time rendering of hatching strokes over various objects. They use tonal art maps containing different stroke sizes and density at various resolutions. Using these tonal art maps, we can render strokes on complex surfaces.', u'title': u'Hatching Shader'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.1 ~ 2012.6', u'description': u'We present a straightforward, easy-to-implement, point-based approach for animating elastoplastic materials. The core idea of our approach is the introduction of embedded space, the least-squares best fit of the material's rest state into three dimensions. Nearest neighbor queries in the embedded space efficiently update particle neighborhoods to account for plastic flow. These queries are simpler and more efficient than remeshing strategies employed in mesh-based finite element methods. We also introduce a new estimate for the volume of a particle, allowing particle masses to vary spatially and temporally with fixed density. Our approach can handle simultaneous extreme elastic and plastic deformations. We demonstrate our approach on a variety of examples that exhibit a wide range of material behaviors.', u'title': u'Deformation Embedding for Point-Based Elastoplastic Simulation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.9 ~ 2010.10', u'description': u'The scene contains a 4-sided room that are light-colored blue. Within this scene are various objects included a texture-mapped sphere and several stacked objects. There are 3 different shadow algorithms being used: projective shadows, shadow volumes, and shadow maps. Projective shadows from objects will only cast shadows on the floor and room, but not on each other or themselves. Shadow volumes and shadow maps will cast shadows on both themselves, other objects, and the floor. There is a white point light source which adjustable by a user.', u'title': u'Shadow Algorithms'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.8 ~ 2010.9', u'description': u'Texture mapped a 4-sided room such that one wall has front-side culling applied. The floor is texture mapped using a checkerboard image and also feature mip mapping. The walls of the room are a repeated brick texture. There is a floating sphere in the center of the room texture mapped with the image of the earth. There is a control feature which \u201cdissolves\u201d the earth image into an image of my face. The \u201cdissolve\u201d is controlled using a set of interface controls which starts/stops/resets and varies the speed of the dissolve. Also included is a lightmap with multi-texturing for the floor. The lightmap only lights a small spot on the floor and acts like a \u201cflashlight\u201d. The interface controls also provides 4 main modes of texturing: modulate, replace, blend, and decal which is applied to the earth texture. Lastly, there is a reflective or environment mapped sphere in the scene which was created using a cube map.', u'title': u'Texture Mapping'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.9 ~ 2010.10', u'description': u'Created a deformable bodies simulator and compared Euler integration methods. Based on \', u'title': u'Deformable Bodies'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.3 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'Arc9 makes working collaboratively with any type of creative media easy', u'title': u'Arc9'}]

summary: As an Independent Software Consultant specializing in Microsoft Office, I provide superior assistance, no matter the scope of your company. I've been professionally using, teaching, and supporting Microsoft Office for decades, bringing an ardent combination of Microsoft Certified Master Instructor and VBA Software Developer, plus a wide variety of real-world project experience in several industries. I'm a Subject Matter Expert ready to help you.\n\nWhere do you get stuck when using Office?\nWhat skills do you want to grow through training?\nHow do you want to use that data you've collected?\nWhat if your employees got more done with less time and effort?\nWhat consistent results do you need from Word,  Excel, Outlook, and PowerPoint?\nHow would you benefit from customized automation development, forms, and/or templates?\n\nHere are a few of my credentials:\n• Microsoft Certified Master Instructor for Microsoft Office and excellent software training since 1985\n• Support Specialist - help desk (all levels), curricula, job aids, styles, formula-driven workbooks, etc.\n• Software Developer - fully customized macros, dialog boxes, and templates for Word and Excel\n• Experience at over 50 law firms and scores of other companies\n\nThrough training, including Train The Trainer sessions, I can educate and empower your employees to use what's available in Microsoft Office (there is a lot). Through software development, when it's necessary or desirable, I can create unique automation tools that run inside Office and give your end-users unprecedented advantages that pay you back in saved time and effort. Together, training and automation can revolutionize how you work, and proactively leverage your investment in Microsoft Office into measurable increases in your bottom-line productivity and workforce efficiency.\n\nLet's explore the possibilities of how we can work together to help you get the most out of this powerful software you already own and use every day.\n\nRob@MicrosoftOfficeGuru.com

summary: I'm a serial entrepreneur and an angel investor. The last couple of years I've been particularly interested in crowdsourcing, cloud labor, and human computation -- disruptive technologies that are transforming the way people work all over the world.\n\nA hacker at heart, I've spent way too many years banging out code in assembler, C, and other languages used by real cowboys. I've got a long background in computer graphics, and was the CTO and one of the founders of Hybrid Graphics, a pioneer in real-time 3D graphics technologies. We created some of the very first commercial 3D engines and licensed them to games companies all over the world. I was the co-author of the SurRender3D engine & Umbra visibility optimization middleware (http://umbrasoftware.com).\n\nLater on, we wrote the first implementations of OpenGL ES, OpenVG, JSR-184 and other graphics standards, and licensed them to hundreds of millions of embedded devices in the mobile phone and automotive industries. Hybrid was acquired by NVIDIA in 2006.\n\nThese days I'm the CEO & founder at Microtask (http://www.microtask.com).\n\nI am an angel investor, board member and advisor in several graphics technology, crowdsourcing & games companies in Europe and Silicon Valley.\n\nIn my free time, I travel around the planet, and over the years have become a semi-professional photographer (http://www.flickr.com/photos/wili).\n\nYou can reach me at wili@microtask.com.

summary: Born and raised in Pasadena, California, in the 80s—an era that saw an influx of drugs, gangs, violence, and lack of opportunity enter into many inner cities across America—Brandon, began navigating his way through life with the dreams of becoming a professional athlete. In 1997, after his father separated from the family, the responsibilities that come with living in a single-parent household fell upon him. This traumatic shift led Brandon to the streets where a lifestyle of gangs and hustling put his professional athletic aspirations on hold, indefinitely.\n\nAfter years of living the street life on the west side of Pasadena, Brandon was blessed with a daughter in 2005, which refocused his outlook on life and realigned his priorities. Ironically, this refocusing and realigning, inspired by his daughter, led to Brandon picking up a camera in which he would begin capturing family and friends in various settings. As Brandon began to hone his eye, his passion and skill-set grew from freelance photography and adding to his repertoire videographer, graphic designer, and visual artist.\n\nBrandon's uniqueness comes from an uncanny ability to illuminate the beauty that oft lies hidden in the most gritty subjects. His appreciation and exhortation for the beauty in all things and advocacy for their impact on our lives is found in his photographer's philosophy: A photograph taken today is a lifetime of yesterdays preserved for all tomorrows.

This workflow involves five stakeholders responsible within a captioning request process which needed to be strategically clarified to ITS and eventually  students, faculty and staff. The increased and succinct understanding of the process can prevent delays and reduce miscommunications. summary: I’m passionate about bringing together data science, machine learning and the human experience into beautiful products that benefit humanity.\n\nMy training is in perceptual neuroscience and computer science. My scientific research, published in top journals such as Nature Neuroscience and SIGGRAPH, has received over a thousand citations and received press from The New York Times, NPR, and Science News. \n\nI have strong visual and aesthetic training and managed bestselling interactive music app products for the musicians Philip Glass and Björk that have topped the app charts and have been exhibited at the Museum of Modern Art (NY) and the Contemporary Jewish Museum (SF), and written up by Wired and Rolling Stone.\n\nMy work has directly:\n• Provided deep learning tools to enhance doctors’ diagnostic performance\n• Discovered how human brains integrate visual information according to statistically optimal algorithms\n• Informed rules for the perception and design of data visualization, and 2D and 3D display software and hardware\n\nMy specialties are: user experience research (quantitative and qualitative), data science, machine learning and perception, deep learning, data visualization, visual perception, product R&D, product management.

summary: I graduated as mathematician at the Eötvös Loránd University of Budapest, Hungary, in 1979. After a brief scholarship at the Université Paris VI I joined the Hungarian research institute in computer science (SZTAKI) where I worked for 6 years. I left Hungary in 1986 and, after a few years in industry, I joined the Centre for Mathematics and Computer Sciences (CWI) in Amsterdam where I've held a tenure position since 1988. I received a PhD degree in Computer Science in 1990 at the Leiden University, in the Netherlands. I joined the W3C team as Head of Offices in January 2001 while maintaining my position at CWI. I served as Head of Offices until June 2006, then as Semantic Web Activity lead until December 2013. In 2013 W3C has set up a separate Activity on Digital Publishing, to create bridges between the Publishing and the Web industries, and I am now the leader of that Activity.\n\nBefore joining W3C I worked in quite different areas (distributed and dataflow programming, language design, system programming), but I spent most of my research years in computer graphics and visualization. I also participated in various graphics related ISO standardization activities and software developments. I was member of the Executive Committee of the Eurographics Association for 15 years, and vice-chair of Association between 2000 and 2002. I was the co-chair of the 9th World Wide Web Conference, in Amsterdam, May 2000. I am also member of IW3C2, the committee responsible for the World Wide Web Conference series.\n\nSpecialties: Technical expertise: web standards in general; Semantic Web, metadata standards, ontologies, vocabularies; electronic books; programming in C, C++, Java, Python; computer graphics and visualization. More general expertise: standardization process; training; scientific cooperation and organization; general technical outreach; international organizations; conference organizations.

summary: Gary Singh is a professional journalist with nearly 1000 articles in numerous trade and consumer publications, including newspaper columns, feature stories, travel essays, arts criticism, sports writing, business journalism, poetry and short fiction. For 600 straight weeks, his newspaper columns have appeared in Metro, the alternative weekly paper of San Jose and Silicon Valley. His poems have been published in The Pedestal Magazine, Dirty Chai, Maudlin House and more. Currently, he is the author of The San Jose Earthquakes: A Seismic Soccer Legacy (2015, The History Press). He is currently a Steinbeck Fellow in Creative Writing at San Jose State University (2016/17).

Unicorn is supposed to be something can heal sickness, and a symbol of purity and grace. summary: For me it all started with playing games on the Commodore 64 that my brother helped me set up. A series of upcoming events lead me further down the path I'm now traveling. Such as my father teaching me AutoCAD at the age of 14, me discovering 3ds Max through a magazine article and teaching it to myself during upper secondary school, and eventually stumbling upon a university programme in game development. The pieces had started falling into place.\n\nBeing surrounded by fellow artist was a wonderful experience and the years in school really made me grow. I realised that I had a deeper understanding of the technology behind the art and could help my friends with solving problems and reduce miscommunication between artist and programmers. The school projects also gave me a lot of experience in project management. All these traits came in handy as I later became a teacher and tutored my students during their projects.\n\nNothing is impossible if you have unlimited time and resources, but you never do. Therefor good planning and creative solutions to get around problems are needed in order to deliver on time.\n\nSince my childhood I have been enjoying creative writing to express my imagination. I also created my own board games or role-playing games. Game development is fascinating since it combines so many of my skills. I’m also interested in game technologies for other purposes such as education, training simulation, research and health.\n\nMartial art is yet another passion of mine. With computers you have different technologies and with martial art you have different techniques. What they all have in common is that they keep evolving and new ones are invented. You will never be fully accomplished in any of these fields, and that’s the beauty of it!\n\nThe fact that there is always something new on the horizon makes the journey even more enjoyable.\n\nFeel free to add me as a connection and shoot me an email, we might have much to gain from one another!

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2016.11 ~ 2016.11', u'description': u'Use GLSL and WebGL to implement a deferred shading pipeline and various lighting and visual effects.\nFeatures I Implemented:\n  Deferred Blinn-Phong shading\n  Bloom using blur\n  Bloom using two-pass Gaussian blur (extract, blur, blurtwice, combine)\n  Toon Shading (ramp shading, edge detection)\n  Scissor Test Optimization (with debug view)\n  Screen-space Motion Blur\n  G-Buffer Optimization', u'title': u'WebGL Deferred Shading'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2015.9', u'description': u'Realizing Functions with C++ such as Multiple Importance Sampling, Direct and Indirect Lighting, Depth of field, Volumetric Rendering, Acceleration Structures, Anti-Aliasing, Normal Mapping, etc.\n\nUsing BVH tree data structure to increase ray tracing process by 90%.\nMore selected work: Xueyin's Simple Simpe Simple Demo Reel 2015 Fall.', u'title': u'Monte Carlo Path Tracer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.3 ~ 2016.3', u'description': u'Our Project is aimed at the creation of a Maya plug-in to generate 3D model which could match the character\u2019s figure in a single image, both the pose and the shape. As we all know, currently if users want to create a 3D model to represent a specific pose and shape, they have to start from a single mesh from scratch. But great news is that: Our system could generate a 3D model template to allow the users to manipulate a small set of semantically friendly parameters (weight, height, girth) to change the shape of the 3D model, and easily get the model they want.\nGeneration of realistic humans is an essential part of many projects in today\u2019s media industry, and is an increasingly important discipline in the computer graphics community, especially the games and special effects industry heavily depend on realistic human shape.\nWe\u2019re basing our implementation on the paper: Parametric Reshaping of Human Bodies in Images [Shizhe Zhou, Hongbo Fu, Ligang Liu, Daniel Cohen-Or, Xiaoguang Han].The main work-flow of our authoring tool, Figure Reshaper, is to take a human-aware image as input, match a 3D model to the body in the image. Since shapes and poses of vary, the tool need to provide features for adjusting. Next, the user is provided a small set of semantically meaningful parameters (e.g. weight, height) that the user can tune so that the shape of the human body model can be changed in a desired way, e.g. become fatter, taller, or slimmer.', u'title': u'Figure Reshaper'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.2', u'description': u'Currently I designed 5 levels in my breakout game. As level goes up, players may found that the game is getting harder.\n\nFirst, players will encounter different resources: For example, the \u201cpurple heart\u201d shape will falling down from the upper side and if players could catch them, they will have an extra life.\n\n\u201cRed skull\u201d will make players to lose life, so try your best to avoid them!\n\u201cBattery\u201d will make players\u2019 paddle extend 2 times for 10 seconds!\n\u201cBomb\u201d will make players\u2019 directly game over! Avoid them!\n\nThe goals changed from not only destroy all the bricks in order to get into next level, players need also figure out what resources and good for them and what may cause them lose life or scores, and try their taking advantage of the resources. This is one of the most challenging part of my enhanced game.\n\nAlso from level 4, I designed some metal bricks in my game, which need players to hit twice in order to destroy them. (The original bricks need only one hit to die, and mental bricks are the enhanced bricks!) This makes the game much harder and challenging\n\nPlayers may also use \u201cUp\u201d and \u201cDown\u201d arrows to enjoy the 3D feeling!', u'title': u'Enhanced Breakout'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.2 ~ 2012.6', u'description': u'Undergraduate Graduation Design Project.\nFocused on innovating a camera calibrating system that made use of binocular stereovision to measure volume.\nDeveloped a user-defined coordinate system to calculate the whole volume of a specific object by summing volumes of all sub-triangular prisms derived from subdivision, taking advantage of invariable features of some geometrical quantities.\nLeveraged SIFT and Harris Algorithm to detect and match corresponding points from different pictures.\nTools and Language: MFC, OpenCV, C++.', u'title': u'Volume Measurement Baesd on Spatial Invariant Features'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ 2015.2', u'description': u'Program for National Science-Technology Support Plan Project in China: \u201cInvestigative Techniques for Re-Development of Rural Land\u201d (Project No.2013BAJ13B01)\nDesigned a system to reconstruct the surface of different geometric shapes of irregular terrain.\nImproved Delaunay algorithm to construct triangulated irregular network to describe surfaces.\nConstructed a data structure to describe spatial points and a datum plane to improve calculation accuracy.\nTools and Language: PCL, MFC, OpenCV, OpenGL, C++.', u'title': u'Three-Dimensional Reconstructrion of Irregular Terrain'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.6 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'Program for National Science-Technology Support Plan Project: \u201cObtaining Technologies Development of Space-Air-Ground Integration of Rural Land Information\u201d (Project No. 2012BAJ23B02)\nDesigned a system to generate advanced image operations, such as photo righting, image mosaic, manually pixel point selection, image noise removal, etc.\nDevelop a program for adjusting basic image properties (resolution, brightness, contrast, etc.)\nCo-authored papers on Impulse Noise Removal Algorithms (see publication section).\nTools and Language: MFC, OpenCV, C++, Matlab', u'title': u'Simple Image Processing System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.2', u'description': u'Dragon Hunt is a game prototype we created using Unreal Engine for the course Game Design Practicum at University of Pennsylvania. The game is about an army hunting a dragon. We designed this game as an asymmetric 1v1 where one player commands an army like playing an RTS and the other plays as a dragon like a flight simulator (or a \u201cdragon simulator\u201d). \nDemo: https://vimeo.com/160589724', u'title': u'Dragon Hunt'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.11 ~ 2016.11', u'description': u'Use CUDA to implement a simplified rasterized graphics pipeline, similar to the OpenGL pipeline.\nMy CUDA Rasterizer Features:\n  About Graphics Pipeline:\n    Vertex shading\n    Primitive assembly with support for triangles read from buffers of index and vertex data\n    Rasterization\n    Fragment shading\n    A depth buffer for storing and depth testing fragments\n    Fragment-to-depth-buffer writing (with atomics for race avoidance)\n  Extra Coolness:\n    Lambert and Blinn-Phong shading\n    UV texture mapping with bilinear texture filtering\n    UV texture mapping with perspective correct texture coordinates\n    Support rasterizing Triangles, Lines, Points\n    Super Sampling Anti-Aliasing (SSAA)\n    Correct color interpolation between points on a primitive\n\n\n', u'title': u'CUDA Rasterizer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.2', u'description': u'Created an L-System command, an L-System node and GUIs using C++, MEL and Maya & Houdini Plug-in API.\nAlso use SWIG to access C++ functionality from within Python.', u'title': u'L-System Plug-in For Maya and Houdini'}]

summary: Real Estate Investor / Entrepreneur\n\nBrian Lucier has been actively investing in residential apartment buildings and has been involved in all aspects of analyzing, inspecting, acquiring, overseeing contractors and the day-to-day operations of all of BHB Group holdings.\n\nBrian is also on the accredited landlords list for several of Central Massachusetts Housing Authorities. He is an active participant in these programs with the common goal of providing housing for qualified families. Brian also participates in the annual fund raising activities for the Montachusett Opportunity Council for Children and Families.\n\nBrian manages Aegis Housing Solutions, Inc. Brian’s responsibilities include partnering with Realtors on the research and development of leads for homes to assist families in transition looking to purchase and sell homes or investment properties. Brian assists buyers through the rent-to-own transition towards the goal of home ownership.\n\nBrian has been elected by the Northern Worcester County Landlord Association to the BoD and nominated by the board to the office of president of the association. He has demonstrated solid leadership in this role and is directly responsible for charting the growth and development of the association. \n\nBrian manages the content and creation of the NWCLA’s web site presence. He also is a contributing editor and author responsible for publishing the monthly NWCLA eNewsletter. The publication is sent to over 450 NWCLA members as well as Housing Court Judges, Court Clerk officials and many of the guest speakers and affiliated professionals that support our association throughout the year.\n\nMost recently, Brian is involved in the day-to-day operations for the acquisition of large apartment complexes of 100+ units in emerging markets across the United States. As the managing director of BHB Group, Brian is responsible for overseeing the target market analysis, property due diligence, securing funds and closing these acquisitions.

summary: What I love most about graphic design is the challenges that accompany each project. Each project deserves the same amount of attention and respect as the last. I can be a perfectionist at times and work hard to use whatever resources I can to solve the unique challenges that come with each project. I don’t give up easily, but do know when to move on to another solution and when it’s time to ask for help. I get a lot of joy from learning something new and being able to pass that knowledge on to someone else.\n\nSOFTWARE & CODING SKILLS\n• Adobe CC: InDesign, Photoshop, Illustrator, Acrobat Pro, Bridge, Muse\n• Macintosh OS X\n• iWorks and Microsoft Office\n• HTML and CSS principles. Familiar with Chrome Developer Tools and Twitter Bootstrap\n• Can work directly in CSS to modify site designs\n• Typekit and Google font integration\n• Basic ActionScript and AIR file creation\n\nDESIGN SKILLS\nInteractive design, page layout, from creation, interface design, web banners, book layout, design, digital photography, direct mail, newsletters, photography, posters, print production, training materials, web site production design and development, promotional materials, exhibit design.

summary: Bivas has worked as a Software Engineer/Consultant for 19 years on mission critical projects (ITAR, DO-178B) as well as commercial applications in the Aerospace/Defense industry. He is an Engineering Fellow at the Manpower group and has worked as a Computer Scientist for US Defense projects through Honeywell Aerospace. He has a Masters Degree in Computer Science from Arizona State University. \n\nBivas was awarded a certificate of achievement in Software Engineering for his work on 3D Computer Graphics and Display Subsystems for commercial jetliners and Unmanned Aerial Vehicles. \n\nBivas is equally passionate about the Arts. He has financed, produced and co-produced 3 feature films and has directed a feature. In 2008, he was awarded the Arizona Filmmaker of the Year by the Phoenix Film Festival, and was named as The Best Local Filmmaker by the Best of Phoenix magazine. He is a SAG-AFTRA actor with leading roles in independent features. \n\nDuring his free time he composes music and mentors college students and adults on their career path in the tech industry. He has over 600 hours of teaching experience with programming languages like C++, Java, Javascript, OpenGL, WebGL, and Android. \n\n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.12 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'This is a project developed to better understand and explore the theory and practice behind many computer graphics fundamentals. Project was developed entirely in C++ as a rendering pipeline that is implemented completely in software. The only call made to OpenGL is glDrawPixels. Furthermore, I want to be part of this revolution and maybe someday develop interesting applications that use these technologies in interesting ways. This is why I've embarked in an adventure to learn about the Unreal Engine 4, a AAA Game Engine used across platforms nowadays. My goal is to eventually leverage UE4 with Virtual Reality/Augmented reality devices in order to learn, experiment and have fun.\n\nPlease feel free to visit my blog to catch a glimpse of my progress so far!', u'title': u'Project 8D'}]

summary: Ahmad Humayun is a PhD student at the School of Interactive Computing (part of College of Computing), at the Georgia Institute of Technology. He received his MSc. in Computer Graphics, Vision and Imaging from University College London in 2010 for which he was awarded the Microsoft Research Prize and BBC Best Overall Student Prize. He joined the Computational Perception Lab at Georgia Institute of Technology in 2011 where he researches in computer vision and is advised by James M. Rehg. His research interests are in the use of motion cues for perception, applying machine learning to video data and discrete optimization techniques for segmentation.

summary: A hardworking recent Marketing and Computer Graphics graduate from UNCO excited about a career in Advertising.\n\nI recently graduated from the University of Northern Colorado with dual degrees in Marketing and Computer Graphics. I am pursuing a career in one of my passions, advertising.\n\n Growing up, I knew that I was going to be the next big rock star. My friends and I were going to start a band and make it big. But instead of learning to play an instrument, I spent my free time drawing logos and album covers for our band, dreaming about how we were going to enjoy our fame and fortune. \n As you can tell, I am not a major rock star (though I still love Rock music), however; I still love to design and create. I am pursuing a career in advertising because it would give me the structure of a business as well as the ability to live out my creative passion. While pursuing my passions at UNC, I had many great experiences to grow as professional the most significant being\n\n\t- I have had two internships in Social Media:  in Events at the Greeley Tribune, and at The\n         University of Northern Colorado. These internships have given me experience in developing \n         social media strategies and tactics for established brands, creating and scheduling social \n         media content both written and visual, and measuring and analyzing social media efforts.\n\n\t- I have been an active member of the UNC Marketing Association as the Social Media \n        Coordinator, and Co-President. In these leadership positions I have helped coordinate a team\n        of officers to plan many club activities, and conduct reporting for our chapter.\n\n\t- In the art program I have had multiple works of art chosen for various art shows, including \n          the 2014 Annual Juried Art Show, 2013 Foundations Art Show, and 2014 UNC Gala Art \n          Exhibit.\n\nPlease feel free to connect with me: camjgrimes@gmail.com\n

summary: Eric is the author of Foundations of Game Engine Development, the editor for the Game Engine Gems series, and the creator of the Tombstone game engine. More than 15 years ago, he wrote the first book focused on mathematics in games, the best-selling Mathematics for 3D Game Programming & Computer Graphics. Eric has also been a long-time member of the editorial board for the Journal of Graphics Tools, and he has been a major contributor to the successful Game Programming Gems series.\n\nEric previously worked in the advanced technology group at Naughty Dog and is credited on several PlayStation 3 titles based on rendering technology that he developed there. He was also the lead programmer for the fifth installment of Sierra Studio's popular RPG adventure series Quest for Glory.\n\nSpecialties: Computer Graphics / Game Engines

summary: I am a Senior Technical Director / Developer in the VFX industry, with experience working on FX, lighting and pipeline on feature films. I can create FX setups using Houdini/Maya, render in RenderMan/Mantra and demonstrate the usability of these elements using Nuke. I also script using Python, MEL, VEX/VOP, RSL to help get the work done.\n\nFilms that I have worked on:\n\nSuicide Squad (2016)\nAlice Through the Looking Glass (2016)\nAvengers: Age of Ultron (2015)\nStrange Magic (2015)\nX-Men: Days of Future Past (2014)\nPacific Rim (2013)\nJohn Carter (2012)\nCaptain America: The First Avenger (2011)\nPaul (2011)\nIron Man 2 (2010)\nThe Sorcerer's Apprentice (2010)\nGreen Zone (2010)\nKick-Ass (2010)\nScott Pilgrim vs. the World (2010)\nSherlock Holmes (2009)\n\nMy computer graphics education allows me to implement a variety of FX algorithms in Houdini/Maya, including fluids, soft/rigid bodies and deformers. Together with my experience in VFX pipelines, I can create easy-to-use FX setups for artists.\n\n[Software]\nHoudini, Maya, Nuke, Katana, RenderMan (PRMan/Mantra)\n\n[FX Tools]\nHoudini - Pyro, FLIP, RBD, particles, cloth\nMaya - fluid, nParticles, SOuP, nCloth\n\n[Programming]\nGeneral - Python, C/C++, C#, Java\nGPGPU - CUDA, GLSL\nVFX - MEL, VOP/VEX, RSL\nWeb - JavaScript, HTML5, CSS3, XML, SQL\n\n[Software Engineering]\nVersion control - git, svn\nUnit testing - doctest, unittest, QUnit\nCode doc - epydoc, doxygen, JSDoc\nBuild - make, scons\nAgile/Scrum\n\n[APIs/SDKs]\nVFX: PyQt, Maya API (C++/Python)\nGraphics - XNA, OGRE, OpenGL\nWeb - Three.js/WebGL, jQuery, WebRTC, JSARToolKit/js-aruco, Physijs\n\n[CG Programming]\nFluid sim (particle-based, voxel-based, height fields), soft/rigid bodies, cloth, particles, muscles, ray-tracing, collision detection etc\n\n[OS] \nLinux, Windows\n\nI do open-source coding: https://github.com/skeelogy\nI like helping others too: http://stackoverflow.com/users/2643134/skeelogy

summary: I work on the VR video live streaming with Nokia OZO camera.\nPersonal website: http://www.tongxin.zone/\n\nSKILL HIGHLIGHTS:\n- Computer graphics: interactive rendering\n- Computer vision: Optical flow and panorama stitching.\n- High performance computing: GPU based parallel computation and CPU multi-threading.\n- Visualization: Large scale data analysis/visualization\n- Human computer interaction with touch screen, virtual reality and motion camera interaction.\n\nCOMPUTER SKILLS:\n- Programing Languages: C/C++, Python, Matlab, JAVA, C#, R, ActionScript, VB.NET\n- Systems: Windows, Unix.\n- Programming Libraries: CUDA, OpenCL, OpenGL, Caffe, VTK, Qt, Thrust, CMake, OpenMP, MPI, Boost, OptiX, NetCDF, ArcGIS.\n- Software tools: Git, CMake, Visual Studio, VIM, Valgrind, Qt Creator, Eclipse, Flash Builder, ParaView, NetCDF tools, ArcGIS, SketchUp, AutoCAD, SQL Server.\n- Devices: OSVR virtual reality headset, Leap Motion camera, multi-touch screen, 3Dconnexion (3D Mouse).\n\nCOURSEWORKS:\nIntroduction to Data Mining, Computer Vision, Methods of Pattern Recognition, Introduction to High-Performance Computing, Introduction to Parallel Computing, Distributed Operating System, Geometric Modeling, Introduction to 3D Image Generation, Analysis of Algorithms, Principles of Programing Languages, Theory of Statistical Analysis, Applied Multivariate Analysis.

summary: I am a momtrepreneur from Switzerland living in Bangalore, India. I specialize in mobile apps, from product marketing and sales to design and development.\n\nIn 2009, I obtained a PhD in Computer Graphics from EPFL, Switzerland, where I've taken part in the creation of a real-time crowd simulation engine.\n\nIn december 2008, I co-founded a startup: Minsh!\n\nAt Minsh, we have created a platform that creates custom mobile applications to help organisations communicate with their teams. summary: Award-winning entrepreneur, leader, business strategist and innovation expert in the fields of FinTech, Business Process Management (BPM) and Enterprise Software. With extensive experience in driving companies to successfully achieve innovation, revenue and business growth objectives. Currently CEO of Strands, boosting growth and strengthening its position as global FinTech leader. Previously, founder of Polymita (acquired by Red Hat) pioneering the BPM software industry, recognized as a Visionary by Gartner (Magic Quadrant 2009 & 2010) and Major Player by IDC (MarketScape 2011).\n\nCo-founder of multiple companies within enterprise software, mobile and Internet businesses, also including Intelligent Software Components (iSOCO) acquired by B2B Factory Ventures, Enzyme Advising Group (acquired by Nexe Group) and Altea Consulting. Board Advisor and startup investor of several ventures in enterprise software and applications (Five Points Development, SmartMonkey, Athento: Smart Document Management, Club-BPM, FindThatLead, Clubberize and Wannay). Raised 25M€ of venture funding for the businesses.  \n\nInvited speaker and lecturer on Innovation, Entrepreneurship, Lean Startups, Leadership, FinTech, Application of Artificial Intelligence, Enterprise Software and Business Process Management. \n\nMember of the CEO Collaborative Forum (CEO-CF) and the Entrepreneurs' Organization (EO), where he served as Finance Chair and Membership Chair for the Spain Chapter\n\nNamed among the 100 Leaders of the Future (Capital Magazine, Spain, 2009) and Entrepreneur of the Year (Entrepreneurs Magazine, 2006, Spain).

summary: I have been in the creative media industries for over 25 years. My experience spans across several disciplines including: graphic design for print and digital media, film production, video production, motion graphics, visual effects, audio production, web design and illustration.\n\nI have extensive Director level management experience as Art Director, Creative Director, and Program Director. After serving for ten years as a corporate Graphic Designer and Art Director, I opened a creative agency with offices in Salt Lake City, Utah and the Boston, Massachusetts area.\n\nI have subsequeny worked for several years in the video and film production industries, taking on the roles of Director, Producer, Director of Photography, Editor, Sound Designer, and Special Effects Artist.\n\nI have created award winning graphic design, video media, and online marketing for a variety of clients including: The Home Depot, Jamba Juice, Beijer Electronics, PRMI, and BMW.\n\nIn addition to developing professional creative media, I am Program Director of the Visual Media and Graphic Design department at a four year college. As Program Director, I manage the adjunct teaching staff, develop course materials, direct student academic affairs and teach courses in accredited associate and bachelor degree programs. Subjects include: graphic design, video production & editing, motion graphics, digital illustration, photography, marketing, and web design.

summary: Ben Hogan has been helping agile teams visualise their work since 2002, building team walls, information radiators and project war rooms. Ben has an enduring passion for awesome stationery and can perform magic with index cards. He is a veteran of introducing visualisation to many IT projects, IT operations teams and business teams including marketing, HR, finance and customer service. At the enterprise scale Ben has introduced visualisation practices in industries such as higher education, insurance and a start-up training organisations. He is one of the first people to teach Kanban in Australia, is a Lean Kanban Coach and is a participant in the Kanban Leadership Retreat. Ben has spoken on Visual Management at the Scrum Australia and Agile Australia conferences, and is an invited speaker to the upcoming Agile Encore conference.   \n\nBen is also a highly experienced lean and agile coach, trainer and facilitator and has extensive experience helping clients to implement agile organisational transformation including Kanban, Scrum and Extreme Programming. \n\nBen is actively involved with the local and international agile community. Ben has spoken at local and international agile conferences including “how to introduce agile to an organisation using agile techniques” presented at Agile Australia. He is a member of the Limited WIP Society, Sydney and Melbourne Scrum Users Groups, a facilitator of the Sydney XP Activities Club, is a member of the London XP community, is a Certified Scrum Master and is a regular participant in international conferences, recently returning from the 2012 Kanban Leadership Retreat in Austria.\n\nSpecialties: Agile software development including Lean, Kanban, Scrum and  Extreme Programming.\nAgile coaching and organisational transformation.\nCloud computing, automated deployment, continuous delivery and DevOps.

summary: I am a geek. I love technology and figuring out how it functions. I also love humans and figuring out how they function.\n\nI have a vast experience in both delivering and managing software projects using agile methodologies. My personal goal is to help teams and companies develop valuable, quality software without all the pains that so often accompany this type of work.\n\nI believe the best way of developing software is to follow a few simple practices: increase communication and feedback between company and customers and between management and developers, focus on quality and continuous improvement and establish an appropriate level of control, then let teams self-organize within those boundaries.

summary: As a Silicon Valley veteran of 20 years, I help companies build and scale new digital products, find and master product-market fit, and improve software development process and teamwork.\n\nI work with product teams to develop and ship new digital products from ideas to product-market fit. I've been teaching startup best practices to teams for years, and recently published the book, Startup Patterns. I use a structured framework that combines the best practices of Design Thinking, Lean Startup, and Agile development into one seamless process. My coaching style is rigorous and hands-on, working directly with teams through an iterative, experiment-focused approach to product development. Every engagement produces a working digital product at completion, and everyone on the team learns something new and important about product delivery.\n\nAt work or in the community, I am committed to making the world a better and more livable place for all people. I have many years of experience as a community activist, and I am particularly interested in the intersection of open source and community organizing.\n\nAnd, YES, I still code. :-)

summary: I am an agile adoption specialist and technology trainer with experience rooted in development and forged in management.  I believe that agile should lead to more management insight into projects while allowing the development team higher self-actualization.\n\nI am one of the few people in the US certified through Scrum.org to teach scrum master, product owner, and developer classes.  I am also one of the few people in the US certified through all three major certification bodies (PMI, Scrum.org, Agile Alliance) as a practitioner of agile techniques.\n\nSkilled at enterprise level agile adoption, I deal with all levels of a business from developers to C level executives. \n\nI have experienced in a wide range of industries such as healthcare, telecom, DOD, manufacturing, finance, marketing, casino gaming, shrink-wrapped software, banking, and sales.\n\nI am passionate about lifelong learning and I have the heart of a teacher.

summary: Ian is a consultant, coach, and speaker on all topics related to Lean, Kanban and Agile software development. His 25 years of hands-on experience helps clients transform their organisations using Kanban and other Lean and Agile techniques to lower costs while increasing their ability to respond to changing market demands and outperform competitors. Ian has trained and coached hundreds of software development teams in Agile, Lean, and Kanban techniques, and has broken new ground by scaling lean principles to the portfolio level and beyond.\n\nIan founded Lean Agile Manchester. summary: I am proud to say that at this moment I'm one of two acknowledged Agile Certified Enterprise Coaches (CEC) in the Netherlands registered at Scrum Alliance and Certified LeSS Practitioner & SAFe Agilist. There are other ways to run a project but over the years I found out that the hands-on way of working with scrum and kanban and agile thinking seems to work the best. I’m not a fan of documentation or elaborate reports (you're not gonna get them from me). And I hate meaningless meetings. I like to grab things with both hands and getting things done. Roaring like viking although i'm gentle and understanding most of the time. After working as a project-manager and disliking the way projects where done, I made the transition to the more Agile way of thinking. I like to provide training and coaching to help people reach their goals. Working together and sharing knowledge is my thing.\n\nAs a Certified Designer & Facilitator of workshops with the Lego Serious Play Method I like to facilitate workshops with LEGO SERIOUS PLAY, a very strong method to get those tough question out in the open and work towards a possible solution. \n\nIn my spare time I like to write short stories and blogs, I'm a professional photographer who likes to try everything at least once but specialized in model-photography.  I also like to run around in combat gear playing Airsoft and do the same thing on my PS4.\n\nKeywords: \nApple, Agile, Scrum, LeSS, SAFe, Kanban, Networking, Public speaking, Facilitation, OpenSpaces, Eye contact, Seduction at the workplace,  photography, Lego Serious Play, Lego Education Teacher Trainer, Communication, thinking out of the box (or change te box if you can't), Positive, Effective and I don't like stuff that does not work.\n\nClients I worked for and facilitated:\n\nPGGM\nING\nDelta lloyd\nConexys\nCentric\nYouwe\nVippromo\nDAF\nIT-Works\nDTG\nJustlease/Terberg Leasing\nKentalis\nVGZ\nHoge school Utrecht\nTalentpeaks\nNovartis

summary: Technology expert with 14 years’ experience in evolving companies. An enterprising and personable facilitator with a reputation for helping individuals, teams and organisations to work effectively using Scrum or Kanban. Adept at leading change from within organisations, whilst causing mimimal disruption. Heavily involved with the lean and agile communities, and author of popular blog (scrumandkanban.co.uk). One of only two people in the UK with both KCP and CSP certifications.\n\nKEY SKILLS\n•\tAgile/Lean Coach (CSM, CSP, KCP, PSM): Having worked with a variety of companies from start-ups to large organisations in a range of industries (including finance, fashion, hotels, communities, recruitment, fine art, travel), understands that there is not one solution to suit all; a tailored approach is essential. Uses an organic approach of evolution not revolution to deliver improvements with minimal disruption.\n•\tMentor: Experienced in dealing with individuals as well as large organisations. Has independently mentored a number of people in their personal development to roles within Scrum teams. Currently introducing a not-for-profit Scrum Mentorship Programme.\n•\tTrainer and Presenter: Regularly delivers workshops on the basics of agile and Scrum, as well as an introduction to Kanban. summary: Pro-active Sr. Agile Coach, and Agile Program Manager with Agile Transformation, Consulting and hands-on Development experience. A career in IT of 15 years in IT, over 9 years as Agile Coach, Agile Project Manager or Agile Consultant. I have led teams to deliver valuable software and technology solutions in a variety of industries by using a pragmatic blend of technical knowledge, business acumen, and several Agile and Lean methods including Scrum, SAFe, Kanban, and Extreme Programming.\n\nExperience working with Agile at scale, at the Program and Portfolio levels; having led large geographically dispersed teams to successfully deliver software and technology solutions across several industries including technology, healthcare and finance. Solid experience working with a DevOps mindset and practices, including Continuous Releases, Jenkins, Micro-Services, ATDD, and BDD.\n\nMoreover, I have hands-on experience in all aspects of the Software Development Life Cycle having delivered projects not only as an Agile Coach, or Agile Project Manager, but also as Product Manager, and even Developer. I have a 360 view of IT and Software Development which has proven valuable for the teams, and organizations I have worked for. Furthermore, this experience has led me to deliver several successful Agile Transformations, leading teams to higher levels of performance, and synergy.\n\nMy current focus is on Agile and Lean methods, and particularly scaling them to larger organizations without losing flexibility or speed. For that reason, I am updating the Kanban Ace Framework to offer many innovations such as light-weight agile at scale, and support for both Scrum and SAFe. \n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2014.10 ~ 2014.10', u'description': u'Traditional PMOs are considered the motherships of project management disasters. Over the past 2 decades, DSDM has proven to be a rigorous Agile method allowing companies to deliver projects successfully in an Agile manner. However, we still need to find ways to address the most common challenges encountered by most organisations trying to adopt Agile ways: \n\n- Coordinate the deliverables and needs of multiple Agile teams; \n- Create an environment of effective collaboration and communication across the organisational boundaries; \n- Expand Agility beyond the traditional IT space; and, \n- Balance the demand and capabilities of organisations to produce improved business flow. \n\nFew companies truly treat themselves as a network of interdependent components that work together to try to accomplish a common goal. Does your PMO follow a systemic approach? How do you maintain the continuity and flow of the system? The challenge is to maximise the desirable Agile benefits from \u2018Individuals (Teams) and Interactions\u2019 to multiple teams and ever-larger systems, without losing our Lean temperament. In this presentation, the authors will present how Lean Thinking and Kanban can be used in conjunction with the DSDM lifecycle to successfully create an improved PMO focused on re-architecting the Business Flow and Balance of Demand.', u'title': u'The Kanban PMO: How to improve an existing PMO using Kanban and AgilePM'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.4 ~ 2014.4', u'description': u'London Lean Kanban Day\nDate: Monday 28 April 2014, 9.00am - 5.30pm \nVenue: BCS London, First Floor, The Davidson Building, 5 Southampton Street, London, WC2E 7HA\nProgramme: http://lanyrd.com/2014/llkd14/\n\nDescription:\n\nLondon Lean Kanban Day will be the premier Kanban event in London for 2014 including some of the most respected figures in the Kanban world. The event will combine traditional speaker-led sessions with an Open Space.\n\nThe sold out event was limited to 120 participants ', u'title': u'London Lean Kanban Day 2014 (LLKD14)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.10 ~ 2012.10', u'description': u'BCS Agile SG organises an inspirational talk with the co-creator of Scrum, Dr. Jeff Sutherland.\n\nThe leading expert will be speaking about the Origins of Scrum, how these values and influences appear today and where he sees that Scrum is headed.\n\nThe methodology that Jeff developed in 1993 and formalised in 1995 with Ken Schwaber has since been adopted by the vast majority of software development companies around the world. But Jeff realised that the benefits of Scrum are not limited to software and product development. He has adapted this successful strategy for several other industries including: finance, healthcare, higher education and telecom.\n\nJeff sets the vision for success with Scrum. He continues to share best practices with organisations around the globe and has written extensively on Scrum rules and methods. With a deep understanding of business process -gleaned from years as CTO/CEO of eleven different software companies- Jeff is able to describe the high level organisational benefits of Scrum and what it takes to create hyper-productive teams.\n\nThe event is kindly hosted and sponsored by ExactTarget, London.', u'title': u'Jeff Sutherland at BCS'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ now', u'description': u'Lean Kanban-based humanitarian and regional development programme to form synergies amongst local businesses, offer service packages with complementary product/service offerings and design cohesive tourism operations. More information to follow in due course.', u'title': u'The UN & Phuket Rajabhat University'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.10 ~ 2012.10', u'description': u'Agile in government and private sector is about putting the user first, highlighting the importance of collaboration, continuous learning and adaptation. We share our experiences, exchange ideas and discuss about what went right or wrong and why.\n\nConsultants from the entire spectrum of verticals are able to promote their case studies, lessons learnt, project statistics, retrospective analyses, successes and failures of Agile transformation projects.', u'title': u'Agile Project Register'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.11 ~ 2012.11', u'description': u'E-Tourism has significantly changed tourism industry and tourist behaviour by creating new services, fostering international exposure and providing access to local knowledge through its enabling role.\n\nThe quality of e-tourism content is significant and frequently forces the establishment of national knowledge providers to centrally manage the national brand and facilitate collaboration amongst various stakeholders.\n\nThe lecture focuses on successful implementation approaches, which fill the gap between knowledge supply and demand through the innovative integration of tools, services, human resources management and knowledge management.\n\nDiscussion includes the case of New Zealand, highlighting how an integrated portal transformed the online tourism presence and attracted millions of visitors worldwide.\n\nPhuket Rajabhat University, Phuket, April 2013.', u'title': u'E-Tourism: Filling the Gap between Knowledge Demand and Supply'}]

summary: I’m passionate about people, music and the arts.  That could seem an odd fit with the corporate world, so dominated by logic and reason and management-speak, but the hardest part of change is persuading people to change themselves: their attitudes, their behaviours and their expectations.  And you can’t reach them with logic and reason alone.\n\nIt’s for that reason that I use a broad spectrum of techniques derived from Cognitive Psychology combined with cutting-edge Lean and Agile tools.  The easy part of transforming work is process, structures and procedures.  They all matter, but mean nothing if people won’t change too.  And if that were easy then no-one would ever need a transformation consultant who works effectively on both challenges together!\n\nI’ve worked with organisations large and small, including mission-critical projects for SaaS companies (a proud Salesforce-r/ExactTarget-er), McKinsey, KPMG and the European Commission.  I’m no stranger to challenging constraints and strongly political environments.\n\nI use many specific tools in my work that I passionately advocate; including the Coaching Manual, Management 3.0, Organisational Therapy, Systems Thinking and Distributed Leadership.  These help me teach people to create a continuous improvement culture founded on sustainable delivery with clear ownership and commitment.\n\nBut what really matters most are the people I work with: unleashing the potential of teams and individuals and inspiring them to become happier and more productive, so they continue to improve and grow without needing external help.  That’s what motivates me and drives me to succeed.\n\nGET IN TOUCH\nE.: lazaro@lazarowolf.com\nT.: +44 7780 782206\n\nTESTIMONIALS\n\

summary: Dimitar Bakardzhiev is an expert in managing successful and cost-effective technology development, often in geographically distributed environments, and delivering cutting-edge, large-scale projects for multinational organizations. With his blend of technical, managerial and operational expertise with advanced skills in planning, product development and resource allocation, Dimitar effectively combines the theory and practice of Agile and Kanban Method to deliver business results.\n\nAs a Lean-Kanban University (LKU)-Accredited Kanban Trainer (AKT) and avid, expert Kanban practitioner and  Brickell Key Award 2015 Finalist, Dimitar puts lean principles to work every day when managing complex software projects. Dimitar has been one of the leading proponents and evangelists of Kanban in his native Bulgaria and has published David Anderson’s Kanban book as well as books on Lean, Theory of Constraints by Goldratt and Deming's Theory of Management in the local language. He is also a lecturer and frequent speaker at numerous industry conferences and his passion is to educate audiences on the benefits of Lean principles and Agile methodologies for software development.

summary: Public speaker | Consultant | Author\n\nExpert in Effectiveness for Individuals, Teams, or Organizations\n\njim@moduscooperandi.com | @ourfounder | moduscooperandi.com\n\nAt Modus, we help people see and understand their work so they can act.\n\nIn my career I have led teams that built light rail, freeways, cities, software packages, popular web sites, books, a few houses, and an on-line school. \n\nI have learned one key truth that inhibits our success: people are overworked.\n\nAlmost every client (individual or organizational) I have worked with, regardless of vertical, is overworked. Being overworked means they don’t have time to pay attention to their work, its context, or their co-workers. This fosters hasty decisions made with a lack of information. These poor decisions create re-work, unnecessary emergencies, and unrewarding working conditions.\n\nSince writing Personal Kanban and winning the Shingo Research Award, I have had the good fortune to:\n\n   * work with Fortune 10 companies, major world governments, and the most dynamic startups\n   \n   * monthly keynote conferences globally\n\n   * be interviewed in major publications including Time, Newsweek, Wired, LifeHacker, The New York Times, the Times of London, Inc, and Businessweek.\n\nI am a noted expert in business process, personal work management, and the application of Lean to personal work and life.\n\nI believe that the best process is the least process necessary to achieve goals. I have zero tolerance for process waste.\n\nI enjoy helping people and teams work out sticky problems, an advocate of people actually seeing their work, and inventing new ways to work at the intersection of Lean thinking, brain science, and leadership.

summary: I want to deliver quality experiences that make people forget about the technology they are using. \n\nI'm as much a project manager as I am a digital architect. I have a load of experience in leading web production projects, digital marketing, social media projects and I have a strong background in software development. \n\nOn the subject of people management I strongly believe in coaching, empowerment and facilitation. People describe me as a teamplayer who'll explain difficult stuff in human language.\n\nI'm a PRINCE2 certified Project Manager since 2010. \n\nI have a Lean Kanban University certification and I'm a certified Scrum Product Owner.\n\nMy specialties in no particular order: \n► project management\n► communicating design with wireframes and diagrams\n► functional and business analysis\n► information architecture and user experience design\n► leading web production\n► social media and digital marketing campaigns\n\n---\n\nSome of my past experiences include:\n\n• Digital advertising and marketing for Ogilvy, TBWA and Duval Guillaume. Ranging from big projects such as a major water preservation campaign for the European Commission (several websites and social media channels), to websites like the Telenet Corporate website and short track campaigns for Miele, De Lijn, BPost, BMW, Spadel, Pfizer, Oregon and several others.\n\n• Product and sales tool development of a global geocoder for TomTom.\n\n• Analysis, development and technical lead of a large distributed online mobile project (J2ME)\n\n• I worked at Nascom as a Java developer and project manager where I was on the team that made ClubVaio for Sony Europe (an online community platform that's been retired) and the official Sony European VAIO product portal.\n\n• I have worked on several Django (Python) based projects. (in my free time I still hack around for skills and for fun)\n\n• I worked as an independent contractor and consultant.\n\n• I've been a speaker at several Barcamp and Bizcamp events.

summary: I’m a proactive agile coach, with extensive knowledge of agile processes (XP, Scrum, Kanban, SAFe, Disciplined Agile Delivery) and the technical practices required to make an agile team productive and successful (TDD, BDD, Pair Programming, Mob Programming, Clean Code). I enjoy helping teams transform into effective and productive agile teams. Using a Servant Leadership style I’m able to help the team grow at the same time as ensuring the team hits all objectives that have been set. Communication is key for any team to be successful both internally to the team and externally to stakeholders. Using techniques from BDD to allow us to create a ubiquitous language for specifications we can ensure that the whole team has an understanding of what is required. A high level of openness reduces the need for conflict resolution, but when this is required I feel have the humility and assertiveness to resolve issues swiftly and effectively. \n\nI find that an agile team works best by selecting the agile practices from many different methodologies that work for them. Although this needs to be underpinned with Technical Practices for example Test Driven Development, Behaviour Driven Development, Pair Programming and Clean Code. As well as being an Agile Coach / Scrum Master / Kanban Practitioner I’m a practising software craftsman. I understand that having a clean code base and correctly structured modules will help a team keep agile and moving fast. I’m driven by the desire for successful outcomes. \n\nI’m able to facilitate many different types of meetings, from the standard agile ceremonies – Daily Stand-ups, Planning Meetings, Retrospectives to more formal business meetings for requirements gatherings and stakeholder management with regular updates on project status.\n

summary: Helen is an outgoing and driven coach and trainer who is passionate about working with Individuals, teams and organisations on their road to agility. Helen has working with many varied organisations and teams in many different industries and brings this vast wealth of experience and knowledge to her training and coaching.\n\nHelen has a holistic approach to coaching operating with individual team members, whole teams, leaders, managers and executives across technical and non-technical departments.  You will often find her working with clients on rolling out enterprise level Kanban or Scrum.\nHelen is proud to be an Accredited Kanban Trainer with the Lean Kanban University and runs regular classes publicly and privately.  Not forgetting her roots Helen is a regular trainer for Agile and Scrum.\n\nHelen is a great believer in sharing her knowledge and encouraging other to do the same and enjoys growing the Agile and Kanban communities. She has many achievements under her belt including:\n\n•\tFounding the Agile Coaching Exchange (ACE) and Kanban Coaching Exchange (KCE) user groups.
