summary: Alan has over 15 years experience in software development & services, with a background in software engineering, quality assurance, business analysis, project management, & process improvement.  He has spent the last eight years leading Agile projects; as well as, helping senior leadership & standards organizations (such as PMO's) adopt value driven & innovative software development practices.  Alan has also developed training course ware for Agile software development & has personally trained hundreds of software professionals on Agile software development, Scaled Agile Framework (SAFe), & IBM Rational Unified Process (RUP)\n\nAlan has collaborated with and led numerous teams that were both large in size and widely distributed with team members in Brazil, Canada, China, Germany, India, Malaysia, Pakistan, Philippines, and Romania.  He has experience in multiple verticals, including Consumer Products,  Energy, Environmental Services, Grocery, Insurance, Manufacturing, Medical Devices, Non-Profit, Publishing, and Telecom.  Years of well rounded experience and his impartial, no-nonsense advice makes Alan a trusted adviser to his clients.\n\nAlan was a founding member of Agile Leadership Network Houston & is currently on the leadership team of Agile Cincinnati where he is focused on turning it into a great organization. He was also a question writer for the PMI-ACP exam & was on the exam's standards setting committee, which determined the passing score range & final question bank.\n\nAlan's passion is to continue to give back to the software development community & push the profession forward through speaking engagements, writing (www.xceleratepartners.com/blog/), & his work with non-profits such as Agile Cincinnati (www.agilecincy.org).\n\nSpecialties: \n* Agile Development\n* Project Management\n* Requirements Management (UML, Use Cases, & User Stories)\n* Process Engineering/Improvement\n* Waterfall, Iterative, & Agile SDLC Methodologies, such as SAFe, Scrum, Lean, Kanban, & RUP

summary: Imagine… everyone able to work consistently at their best:\n\n• Individuals, teams, between teams, across the organisation\n• Right conversations, right people, best possible moment\n• Needs anticipated, met at just the right time\n\nFun to imagine, but how do you begin to bring that kind of Lean-Agile vision to life? How do you bring about continuous transformation in your organisation, and how do you do it without resorting to the questionable top-down and bottom-up approaches of the 20th century?\n\nAgendashift describes an inclusive, values-based, and methodology-neutral approach fit for the 21st century, based on genuine participation and integrating the best of modern techniques from Clean Language, Cynefin, Agile, Lean Startup, A3, and Kanban.\n\n• Read the book: https://leanpub.com/agendashift\n• Agendashift home – Tools, workshops, resources, and events: https://www.agendashift.com/\n\nAgendashift is brought to you by Positive Incline Ltd, UK-based specialists in leadership and change management with Lean, Kanban and Agile. Founder Mike Burrows is known for pioneering the values model for the Kanban Method that led to his definitive book, Kanban from the Inside. His second book Agendashift: clean conversations, coherent collaboration, continuous transformation was published in May 2017.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.3 ~ 2012.3', u'description': u'This is the case study of improving line balancing and assembly line performance of a Toyota brake assembly at Toyota Production Systems laboratory of RIT. The product is systematically teared down into individual parts and assembly structure and precedence constraints are identified using fishbone diagrams. The total assembly time is estimated using Westinghouse DFA methods and Boothroyd - dewhurst DFMA software. A line balancing algorithm is used to find out the minimum number of stations required to assemble the product and thereby finding out task-to station assignments. This project also involves development of a framework to identify the precedence constraints that restrict the assembly line performance and eliminating them with a systematic redesign procedure.', u'title': u'A case study of Toyota brake assembly'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2013.7', u'description': u' The current manufacturing and process capabilities of a toy manufacturing unit was analyzed. Various components of variability like Repeatability, Reproducibility and part-part variation were systematically analyzed and process improvement suggestions were given. The need for improving accuracy and precision of measurement system was emphasized.', u'title': u'Measurement System Analysis, Gage R&R stdudies'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.1 ~ 2013.3', u'description': u'This project uses Statistical process control tools to monitor the daily dietary process and identify the sources of variation. ', u'title': u'Statistical Process Control tools used to improve health care practices'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.8 ~ 2011.12', u'description': u'1) Designed a Cam in solid works and given a tool path in MasterCAM, machined on 3 and half axis CNC machine and Injection molded with Polypropylene.\n', u'title': u'Injection Molding of a Cam.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2013.9', u'description': u'Designing the Supply Chain for Jones Microwaves (Pseudo Company) by defining their Competitive\nstrategy, most critical drivers and metrics, selecting a network design, defining materials and finished\nproduct sourcing and transportation strategies, Demand Forecasting and Aggregate Planning to make\ntheir supply chain cost effective to meet stiff market competition in North America and Europe.', u'title': u'Supply Chain Design'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.8 ~ 2011.12', u'description': u'1) Redesigned a vacuum cleaner using reverse engineering tools like customer needs assessment, QFD, CVCA, DFA, DFE.\n\n2) Achieved 25% reduction in cost, better and greener design.', u'title': u'Product Design and Development with Reverse Engineering'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.12 ~ 2012.2', u'description': u'An experiment was conducted to compare the readability of the Arial font and the Times New Roman font. A pilot study was conducted to determine a simple size of 2 replications for every condition of the experiment. In the experiment, 16 readings were taken by reading an article of exactly 800 words. The reading times for each reading were noted and 2^k experiment was performed using Minitab. The output of the experiment yielded strong main effects for Font Size and Reading Interface. summary: Brendan Wovchko is a technology entrepreneur and community organizer based in Nashville. He draws from a rich set of experiences as a founder, executive, and consultant.  His clients have included Huffington Post, Big Commerce, Emma, HCA, Big Machine Records, Walden Media, and Dave Ramsey.  On the behalf of his clients, he has led large-scale initiatives for Avon, National Guard, and US Department of Commerce, among many others.  He has led teams in Nashville, Manhattan, Chicago, Boston, San Diego, London, Sydney, Istanbul, Stockholm, and Hyderabad.\n\nToday Mr. Wovchko and his team at HUGE I/O help leaders and their teams redefine the instrumentation they use to operate their technology organizations with Lean and Agile.  He is an accredited Kanban trainer, experienced Kanban coach and a long-time Scrum coach and trainer.  He is also a certified strategic interventionist.\n\nMr. Wovchko is the co-founder of Hack Tennessee, a rapidly growing community of 1,300+ software engineers and IxD professionals.  Hack Tennessee is the largest maker event in the southeast and one of the largest events of its kind globally.  He has partnered with Hospital Corporation of America (HCA) to produce Hack for the Community and the Mayor's Office of Innovation in co-founding The National Day for Civic Hacking in Nashville.  He also serves on the Board of Directors of TEDx Nashville and mentors at Nashville Software School and Jumpstart Foundry.

summary: I'm a passionate Software Developer, Agile/Lean enthusiast and Software Craftsman. I want to make the software industry better. \n\nUsing my excellent technical skills and strong agile background I help teams deliver the highest possible value:\n­- I strive to have good clear communication between all stakeholders, sharing information with everybody, setting clear goals and not letting false expectations grow\n-­ I work with the whole group to create a performing team (way more than the sum of its members!)\n­- I always observe the system to keep it in a state of continuous improvement \n- I'm soft on people but hard on the process\n\nI'm eager to be part of a team and use my experience to help:\n- create large Java applications with complex architecture\n- build the RIGHT THING (stakeholders' feedback, BDD, Acceptance tests, demos, MVPs, etc.)\n- build the THING RIGHT (TDD, pair programming, refactoring, collective code ownership, etc.)\n- keep the code base always production-ready (continuous integration, continuous deployment, etc.)\n- work on the ever-evolving architecture, keeping it consistent but also as simple as possible\n- write clean code that is easy to understand for humans rather than for computers\n- help and mentor team mates on how to use TDD, refactoring and Clean Code\n- use ideas from Scrum, XP, Kanban and Lean to experiment and create a self-organized team\n- facilitate get-togethers like standups, retrospectives, backlog grooming meetings\n- use visual management and information radiators for better communication\n\nPlease contact me to exchange ideas and experiences, I'd love to learn from you!

summary: Tom Illmensee is Co-founder of Orbital Music Park, an early-stage startup that facilitates local networking, collaborative play and creative space for musical people, inclusive of all instruments, styles and abilities. He was previously Director of Design and User Experience at Prezi. During Tom’s 17-year career in user experience he has collaborated with cross-functional teams to solve complex problems for many different types of people. He is an experienced and passionate community and practice leader, team manager, strategist, researcher, interaction designer and information architect. Among his superpowers are storytelling, kaizen, improvisation, and seeing hidden possibilities in challenging contexts. He recently moved from Budapest, Hungary to Richmond, Virginia, where he plays guitar entirely too loud and runs every day.\n\nSpecialties: User experience design, field research, personas, customer development, product discovery, interaction design, prototyping, usability testing, user-centered design, information architecture, A/B testing, Agile, Scrum, Kanban, Lean Startup, Lean UX, design thinking, professional development, product vision, community-building, design team management, cross-functional balanced team work, entrepreneurship.

summary: As specialists in deep draw technologies, National Manufacturing Co., Inc. has been producing precision deep drawn enclosures and shallow drawn metal components for over 70 years. The company is known for its tightest tolerance deep draw, and its ability to work with complex shapes, sharp corners, exotic and difficult-to-draw materials. National serves a broad spectrum of industries worldwide, including the aerospace, battery, defense, electronics, fuel cell, industrial, medical, telecommunications, commercial and consumer markets.\n\nAs an ISO 9001, AS9100 and ISO 13485 certified company, National practices six sigma and lean principles, and participates in kanban, dock-to-stock, and vendor managed inventory programs with its customer base. National’s engineering team collaborates during your design phase to ensure a robust and economical design, and utilizes National’s library of tools to reduce upfront costs and lead times. In-house tooling design, in conjunction with concurrent engineering, ensures precision tolerances, unsurpassed quality, short lead times and low costs. Value-added services include assembly, machining, welding, and various surface treatments and coatings.
